<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> London Shares Close Lower / British Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The London Stock Exchange blue chip index fell  
Friday, but NatWest shares soared on an unsolicited takeover bid. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed down  
32.1 points, or 0.5 percent, at 5,937.6. 
</P>
<P>
	Provisional volume came to 1.3 billion shares, compared with 1.2  
billion on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Reuters Group PLC shares, which dropped 15 percent on Thursday,  
fell an additional 3 percent Friday. The media and financial 
information company's stock faded following a briefing for analysts 
Wednesday that raised questions about the performance of its 
Instinet electronic stock-trading unit. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest Bank shares soared 29 percent after Bank of Scotland  
made an unsolicited $34.3 billion bid for its rival, which is more 
than three times its size. Analysts said they expected additional 
bids for NatWest. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland shares rose 6.2 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	The bid shook up the rest of the banking sector, as investors  
eyed other potential marriages with the view that one merger would 
push others to the altar in order to stay competitive. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
