<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duncan To Promote Virgin Islands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- NBA Finals MVP Tim  
Duncan of the San Antonio Spurs signed a contract Friday to promote 
his native U.S. Virgin Islands in exchange for tax breaks on his 
planned business enterprises there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Welcome home,'' Gov. Charles Turnbull said at a small ceremony  
on Duncan's native island of St. Croix, attended by Duncan's 
father, sister and about 100 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan will participate in three official advertisements a year  
for 15 years to promote the U.S. Caribbean territory as a tourist 
destination. The tax breaks he will receive will apply to Duncan's 
T.D. Enterprises Inc., from which he plans to set up businesses 
such as sports bars and promotional merchandising outlets. 
</P>
<P>
	The local legislature must still approve the contract, which is  
to go into effect Nov. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the deal, Duncan reestablished his residency in the  
U.S. Virgin Islands and will pay income tax from his multimillion 
dollar NBA salary and other sources to the island government, which 
has been seeking new revenues to chip away at its more than $1 
billion in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not often that you see a situation where both parties  
come up with a good deal,'' Duncan told Radio WRRA after the 
ceremony. ``We're still in the process of looking at a bunch of 
(business ideas). There's not a rush to do anything now -- the thing 
will be on its way soon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 15-year tax breaks cover corporate income taxes, gross  
receipt, Customs and excise taxes. T.D. Enterprises' real property 
taxes will be waived for one executive headquarters, two 
promotional merchandising outlets and two sports bars. 
</P>
<P>
	As a resident of the U.S. Virgin Islands, Duncan will not pay  
income tax to the U.S. federal government. Duncan is entering the 
final year of a three-year, $10 million contract he signed as the 
NBA's No. 1 draft pick in 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
