<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Sudan Missile Strike Challenged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A high-priced team of lawyers, investigators  
and scientists has collected soil samples and other evidence in an 
effort to get the Clinton administration to reimburse a Mideast 
businessman $30 million for the U.S. missile strike against his 
pharmaceutical plant in Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration already has quietly freed $25 million in  
assets belonging to the plant owner, although it maintains the 
bombing was justified. The strike on Aug. 20, 1998, was based on a 
single soil sample that indicated chemical weapons activity at the 
plant and on a suspected link to accused terrorist leader Osama bin 
Laden. 
</P>
<P>
	But the plant's owner, Salah Idris, a Sudanese citizen with a  
Saudi passport, denies any ties to bin Laden, believed to be in 
Afghanistan. His lawyers say they're awaiting his go-ahead to sue 
if the U.S. government refuses to pay. The administration 
acknowledges it didn't know Idris was the owner when it struck. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are ready to go to trial,'' said lead attorney George  
Salem. ``The plant came out clean and, of course, our client came 
out clean.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salem said Idris feels the unfreezing of his assets already  
clears his name of involvement in terrorism, and he is weighing the 
risks of suing the U.S. government, which can suppress evidence 
based on national security interests. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Idris is a great believer in the American system of  
justice,'' Salem said. ``It has vindicated him thus far, and before 
taking this next step, he wishes to make sure that all of his other 
options are exhausted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Idris' plant was destroyed in a cruise missile attack that also  
included strikes on an alleged terrorist training camp in 
Afghanistan -- all in response to the bombings two weeks earlier of 
U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania that killed 224 people, 
including 12 Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	Idris contends his factory provided 50 percent of Sudan's basic  
medicines, including treatments for malaria and tuberculosis. 
Sudanese officials say Idris' plant alone saved the government 28 
percent of the hard currency it spends on imported medicines. The 
bombing killed one person was killed and injured several others. 
</P>
<P>
	The government freed Idris' assets in May after he filed an  
earlier lawsuit. Officials said then they still had sensitive 
information about him but weren't willing to reveal it. At the 
time, a senior official told reporters that U.S. agents were 
monitoring Idris and ``his network.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Idris got $24 million the U.S. Treasury had ordered frozen plus  
another $1 million in accumulated interest. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, officials have refused to discuss Idris, even  
in background briefings, citing pending litigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last official statement more than one month ago, State  
Department spokesman James Foley acknowledged that U.S. officials 
only learned who owned the plant after the strike. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our actions against the al-Shifa plant were not in any way  
predicated on that person's ownership of the plant,'' said Foley. 
He said it had to do with bin Laden's intentions, his ties to Sudan 
and the discovery at the plant of the chemical Empta, which is used 
in the production of VX nerve gas. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate and House intelligence committees have raised questions  
about the retaliatory strike. Along with the mistaken CIA targeting 
of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade during NATO attacks on 
Yugoslavia, the Khartoum bombing has put a negative spotlight on 
the intelligence agency's role in target planning. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant owner has hired heavyweights to help him.  
</P>
<P>
	Salem leads a group of partners at the high-octane Washington  
firm of Akin, Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Field. He declined to discuss 
costs but described as low an estimate that Idris is paying $3 
million for his U.S. legal work. 
</P>
<P>
	``We put together a first-class team of scientists, chemists,  
environmentalists, experts in every realm, in order to give a 
proper defense,'' Salem said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyers had E. Norbert Garrett, a former CIA station chief  
in Kuwait, investigate Idris' claims and background -- he has been a 
banker and exporter. They also enlisted Thomas D. Tullius, 
chemistry department chairman at Boston University, to direct a 
soil investigation using a British environmental engineer to 
collect samples from the plant and recognized laboratories to test 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to clean soil tests, Salem said a layout of the  
factory shows that dangerous chemicals could not possibly have been 
manufactured there. ``If they were, all the people working on it 
would have been killed,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Their suit would demand about $30 million for the plant itself.  
The Sudanese government is reportedly turning the ruins into a 
memorial to remind citizens of the U.S. attack. Washington 
maintains sanctions against Sudan, accusing it of sponsoring 
terrorism. 
</P>
<P>
	On the bombing anniversary, Sudan announced completion of two  
similar plants, and Idris is building a $45 million unit in the 
same neighborhood. He says all produce common drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Sudan, which denies it support terrorism, also has asked for  
compensation and for a U.N. inquiry into the bombing. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
