<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Takes Issue With Bush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton took a swipe at Republican  
front-runner George W. Bush over tax cuts Friday and reminded 
voters that the United States was jolted by a recession during the 
last Republican administration -- when Bush's father was president. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's take just a little walk down memory lane here, shall  
we?'' Clinton said in partisan speech that delighted the Democratic 
National Committee's annual fall meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, I saw a survey the other day that said that times  
had been so good for so long, the American people couldn't remember 
when it was bad and tended to give everybody good ratings on the 
economy -- Bush, Hoover, the whole crowd,'' Clinton said to 
Democratic laughter. 
</P>
<P>
	Underscoring his point, Clinton repeated practically the same  
line later in a separate speech to Democratic businessmen. 
</P>
<P>
	The president also suggested that Vice President Al Gore should  
not be disheartened by recent polls showing him running neck and 
neck with Democratic rival Bill Bradley in New Hampshire and New 
York, and behind Republican Gov. Bush nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long time between now and November of 2000,'' the  
president said. ``In June of 1992, you know where I was in the 
polls? Not behind. Third. Third.'' He said he would never forget 
his comeback victory in California primary June 2, 1992, and 
subsequent successes in New Jersey and Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Americans are not paying attention to politics now, Clinton  
said. ``For most people,'' he said, ``the election is not going on. 
If you live in Iowa or New Hampshire, it's already going on. If you 
live in Arkansas, you're still worried about the price of cattle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Clinton generally has refrained from attacking Gov.  
Bush, he knocked the Republican presidential hopeful for saying he 
would have signed the Republicans' $792 billion tax cut bill. 
Clinton voted the bill Thursday -- the same day Bush promised to 
increase military pay, accelerate high-tech weaponry and develop an 
anti-missile system. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I thought to myself,'' Clinton said, ``this is a nice  
speech but if I sign this tax bill that (Bush) is for, there won't 
be any money for the promise he just made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton suggested Bush should be thankful for the veto, which is  
likely to boost the already soaring budget surplus. ``I need to 
quit helping these Republicans this way,'' Clinton joked. The 
president playfully lamented that he has helped Bush build a huge 
campaign warchest. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, my economy has made it possible for those  
Republicans to give George Bush all that money,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush did not seem perturbed by the attention.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm flattered that once again the president has taken time  
from his busy schedule to talk about me and my policies, even 
before I've won my party's nomination,'' Bush told The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the projected surpluses,'' Bush said, ``I believe  
America's military can be strengthened and our taxes cut. This 
unprecendeted attention by the Clinton-Gore administration must 
mean they're extremely worried about my candidacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While many Americans are basking in prosperous times, Clinton  
used his two speeches to recall the economic downturn under Bush's 
father, President Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	``And lo and behold,'' Clinton said, '' after the '88 election,  
we found ourselves in the worst recession since the Great 
Depression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he and Gore set out to fix the economy. ``And now  
we have the longest peacetime expansion in our history instead of 
the worst recession since the Great Depression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, Clinton's recollection was incorrect. The 1981-82  
recession during the Reagan administration was the worst since the 
Depression. In comparison, the 1990-91 recession during the Bush 
administration was relatively mild. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
