</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland Bids for NatWest  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Bank of Scotland PLC today launched a hostile  
$34.3 billion takeover bid for National Westminster Bank PLC. 
NatWest, which is three times bigger than Bank of Scotland, quickly 
rejected the offer, and its shares soared as analysts speculated 
that other bidders might join the pursuit. Even though the offer 
would represent Britain's biggest bank merger, ``It's not a 
knockout bid. It's feasible someone could come in with a higher 
bid,'' said David Liston, analyst at Capel Cure Sharp. NatWest's 
U.S. shares rose 27.5 percent on the New York Stock Exchange, 
surging $27.81 1/4 to close at $128.81 1/4. Bank of Scotland shares were 
up 6.2 percent in London, where Legal &AMP; General shares fell 6 
percent. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Shuffles Management  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler's North American chief retired as  
part of a management shakeup today, putting the company's German 
executives in even more dominant roles. The shuffle raised new 
questions about the ultimate success of the merger of Chrysler and 
Daimler-Benz. Thomas Stallkamp, the president of the Chrysler 
division and a 19-year Chrysler veteran, will retire Dec. 31. He 
will give up his seat on DaimlerChrysler's management board, and be 
replaced as head of Chrysler by James Holden, executive vice 
president for sales and marketing. DaimlerChrysler shares were up 
33/64 at 67 5/8 

</P>
<P>
	Sales of Existing Homes Off 2.8 Pct  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sales of existing homes fell in August for the  
second straight month after hitting a record high in June. Still, 
sales are on track for a banner year. The National Association of 
Realtors said today that sales of existing single-family homes 
decreased by 2.8 percent in August to a seasonally adjusted annual 
rate of 5.25 million units. Rising interest rates were believed a 
major factor. August's sales level was the lowest since May when 5 
million units were sold. The 2.8 percent decline in August, 
followed a 4 percent drop in sales in July. In June, sales hit an 
all-time high of 5.63 million units sold. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Markets Brace for Big Jolt  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- The Taipei Stock Exchange, closed since a  
disastrous earthquake shook Taiwan early this week, will resume 
trading Monday, and traders expect shares to fall as far as the 
rules allow. Since the quake struck, many traders around the island 
have been unable to work because their electronic dealing systems 
had no power. There was little information available about damage 
sustained by listed companies. The extent of the fallout is still 
far from clear. Analysts say the main question they have is not 
whether prices will be hurt, but how much. 

</P>
<P>
	Allstate Stock Down on Outlook  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Allstate stock plummeted today after the insurer  
said third-quarter earnings would come in well below expectations, 
citing losses from Hurricane Floyd and intense competition. The 
nation's largest publicly held insurance company also revised its 
fourth-quarter earnings downward sharply. But an analyst said 
losses from Floyd should have a minimal effect on the insurance 
industry, noting the other reasons cited by Allstate for its 
revision. Allstate said third-quarter operating earnings would be 
50 cents to 55 cents per share -- down from 76 cents for the same 
period a year ago and well under the 78 cents that an analysts' 
consensus had anticipated. Allstate shares were down 3 1/2 at 28 1/4. 

</P>
<P>
	Mercedes CEO Moves to AutoNation  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The president and chief executive of luxury car  
maker Mercedes-Benz USA Inc. has been named as chief executive of 
the nation's biggest auto retailer, AutoNation Inc. Michael J. 
Jackson was named today to replace Steven Berrard, who left earlier 
this year after serving as right-hand man to AutoNation chairman H. 
Wayne Huizenga. Five other executives have also left this year at 
AutoNation. 

</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid To Cut 330 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp. cut 330 jobs today, about  
half of them near its Pennsylvania headquarters, in a move the drug 
store chain said would save $31.5 million. The layoffs, which 
involve administrative and field staff positions, come just a day 
after the company revealed plans to close a distribution center in 
Utah and eliminate 500 jobs. The cuts won't affect staffing levels 
at Rite Aid stores, where the company hopes to place some of the 
employees losing their jobs, said spokeswoman Karen Rugen. Shares 
of Riteaid were down 1 at 11. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Gov. Edwards Faces Charges  
</P>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Gov. Edwin Edwards and the state  
insurance commissioner were indicted today by a federal grand jury 
on charges stemming from the 1993 failure of an insurance company. 
The indictment charges that they and four other people ``corrupted 
the office of the Louisiana insurance commissioner and the state 
judicial system'' to benefit Cascade Insurance Co. operater David 
Disiere. Charges against Louisiana Insurance Commissioner Jim Brown 
include mail and wire fraud, conspiracy, insurance fraud, witness 
tampering and making false statements to federal officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Ousted Mayor Sues Miami Herald  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Former Mayor Xavier Suarez has filed a libel suit  
against The Miami Herald, accusing the newspaper of portraying him 
as unstable in its Pulitzer Prize-winning coverage of his 
fraud-riddled election. Suarez complained about both news stories 
and columns, citing, among others, columnist Carl Hiaasen, who 
repeatedly called Suarez ``Mayor Loco'' in print. The lawsuit was 
filed yesterday. Herald managing editor Larry Olmstead called the 
lawsuit groundless. 

</P>
<P>
	George Magazine To Stay Alive  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A co-owner of George magazine is making plans to  
keep the publication alive, but with fewer issues each year, 
following the death of John F. Kennedy Jr., its charismatic founder 
and editor. There had been concerns as to whether the four-year-old 
magazine could survive without him. Kennedy died in a plane crash 
in July. Hachette Filipacchi Magazines, which shared ownership of 
the magazine with Kennedy, announced Friday the magazine would cut 
back to 10 issues a year from 12 next year but would guarantee 
advertisers a larger circulation. And starting with the February 
2000 issue, advertisers are being promised circulation of 450,000 
per issue of the magazine that mixed political commentary and 
celebrity profiles, up 12.5 percent from the current 400,000. 

</P>
<P>
	Relief Agency Criticizes IMF  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund is failing to  
complete its mission of reducing poverty in the world's poorest 
nations and needs a radical overhaul, the international relief 
agency Oxfam said today. It suggested a radical overhaul of the 
IMF. A report by the group said IMF programs in developing 
countries not only are failing to spur economic growth but also are 
fostering deep cuts in spending on public health and education. 
Among other things, it faults governments of major industrialized 
countries, which control the IMF, for continuing to insist that 
poor countries comply with IMF programs as a condition for 
receiving foreign aid and debt relief. 

</P>
