<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Kinkel Pleads Guilty to Murder  
</P>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Kip Kinkel, 17, abandoned an insanity  
defense and plead guilty today to murdering his parents at home and 
then shooting to death two classmates at Springfield's Thurston 
High School. He faces a potential life sentence. Kinkel had told 
investigators after his arrest that he had ``no choice'' but to 
kill after shaming his parents by getting expelled from school. His 
attorneys thought that by proving he was insane, or at least not in 
control of his actions, they could spare him life in prison. 
Because he was just 15 at the time of the crimes, Kinkel never 
faced the death penalty. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Military Leaving E. Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Outflanked politically by the United  
Nations and outgunned by international peacekeepers, Indonesia's 
demoralized military is withdrawing from East Timor with little 
grace. Determined not to leave anything behind, soldiers are 
vandalizing and setting fire to their barracks before departing, 
leaving live ammunition behind to explode in the heat. Some delight 
in scaring already-terrorized Timorese civilians by firing shots in 
the air. Others stare sullenly from the backs of trucks hauling 
them, their families and possessions past makeshift refugee camps 
to waiting ships and planes. 

</P>
<P>
	Italy Jury Acquits Andreotti  
</P>
<P>
	PERUGIA, Italy (AP) -- A jury today acquitted former Premier  
Giulio Andreotti of the 1979 murder of an Italian journalist. After 
a three-year trial and four days of deliberations, the jury of two 
judges and six private citizens concluded there was no proof to 
convict Andreotti, 80, one of Italy's most powerful and enduring 
politicians. Andreotti, who was premier seven times and is a 
senator-for-life, was indicted for premeditated murder along with 
five other people in the 1979 slaying of journalist Mino Pecorelli. 

</P>
<P>
	Typhoon in Japan Kills 15  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Typhoon Bart lashed southern Japan Friday, sweeping  
huge waves over homes, knocking cranes onto buildings and leaving 
at least 15 people dead. Dozens were injured and hundreds of 
thousands were left without power when Bart, packing winds of 
nearly 80 mph, pounded Japan's main southwestern island of Kyushu. 
It was expected to pass over the Sea of Japan before shooting over 
the northern island of Hokkaido on Saturday, the agency said. It 
was likely to miss Tokyo. 

</P>
<P>
	Ovarian Implant Called Success  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Young women left infertile due to cancer or  
other ailments may someday have children thanks to an experimental 
ovarian tissue transplant that a doctor says restored a menopausal 
woman's menstrual cycle. Larry Lipshultz, president of the American 
Society for Reproductive Medicine, said that this case indicates 
researchers are on the cusp of safe, reliable transplantation of 
human ovarian tissue. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Shuffles Management  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler's North American chief retired as  
part of a management shakeup today, putting the company's German 
executives in even more dominant roles. The shuffle raised new 
questions about the ultimate success of the merger of Chrysler 
Corp. and Daimler-Benz AG. Thomas Stallkamp, the president of the 
Chrysler division and a 19-year Chrysler veteran, will retire Dec. 
31. He will give up his seat on DaimlerChrysler's management board, 
and be replaced as head of Chrysler by James Holden, executive vice 
president for sales and marketing. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 39.26; Nasdaq Falls 9.42  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rounded out a dismal week with a volatile  
session but generally modest losses today. The Dow Jones industrial 
average, down a total of more than 505 points over the previous 
three sessions, lost another 39.26 and closed at 10,279.33. 
Decliners on the New York Stock Exchange lead advancers 
1,824-1,172. The Nasdaq was down 9.42 at 2,740.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Europeans Lead Ryder Cup Tournament  
</P>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Golfers Colin Montgomerie and Paul  
Lawrie won the first match and Sergio Garcia won his first pairing 
with Tiger Woods today as Europe got off to a fast start in defense 
of the Ryder Cup. Garcia gave the European team its second point 
when he and Jesper Parnevik teamed to beat Woods and Tom Lehman, 
helping Europe to a 2 1/2-1 1/2 lead after the four morning alternate 
shot matches. In the afternoon, the Europeans were leading two of 
the four matches and even in another match midway through the best 
ball competition. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD  
  	   	
</P>
