<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Shuffles Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler's North American chief retired as  
part of a management shakeup Friday, putting the company's German 
executives in even more dominant roles. The shuffle raised new 
questions about the ultimate success of the merger of Chrysler 
Corp. and Daimler-Benz AG. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler's profits have been disappointing and its stock  
is at a 52-week low. Industry analysts, while saying the moves 
weren't surprising, wondered if Chrysler's freewheeling corporate 
culture will be stifled by a more rigid Daimler management system. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's this view within this company that there's Chrysler  
guys and there's Daimler guys,'' said Rod Lache, an analyst with 
Deutsche Bank Securities in New York. ``Although the functions have 
been integrated, the cultures haven't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the moves announced Friday, Thomas Stallkamp, the  
president of the Chrysler division and a 19-year Chrysler veteran, 
will retire Dec. 31. He will give up his seat on DaimlerChrysler's 
management board, and be replaced as head of Chrysler by James 
Holden, executive vice president for sales and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-chairmen Juergen Schrempp and Robert Eaton also announced  
that the management board would be trimmed from 17 to 14. In 
addition to Stallkamp, another Chrysler executive and two former 
Daimler-Benz AG executives will lose their seats. One former 
Daimler executive will join the board. All the moves are effective 
Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The new board will focus its automotive tasks in three areas --  
Chrysler cars and trucks, Mercedes-Benz vehicles and commercial 
trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrempp and Eaton have said the board needed to be pruned once  
the first part of the merger was complete. Eaton said Friday the 
move would allow the company to move faster, and was not a shift in 
power towards one side of the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't a German or American thing,'' he said. ``This is  
one company striving to be the No. 1 automotive transportation 
company in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of the merger in November 1998, Chrysler was known  
for having a more progressive, open culture. It was credited with 
innovations such as the first minivan, and vehicles such as the 
retro Chrysler PT Cruiser, due out next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Adding that style to the more traditional, top-down management  
culture of Daimler-Benz AG was supposed to help both companies by 
improving Chrysler's quality while helping Daimler expand its reach 
outside luxury cars and trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton and Schrempp portrayed it as a marriage of equals, keeping  
dual headquarters in Stuttgart, Germany and Auburn Hills, Mich., 
outside Detroit. They also acknowledged the risks: Their own study 
of transnational mergers found 70 percent failed to achieve the 
kind of success that was anticipated. 
</P>
<P>
	And one of the stars of the merger was Stallkamp. Before  
becoming president of Chrysler in January 1998, he was credited 
with helping the company shed billions in costs, and was expected 
to help the German side do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	The 53-year-old executive threw himself into making the merger  
work. He took German language classes, learned how to criss-cross 
the Atlantic in a day without jet lag and sent out scores of 
e-mails to employees with questions about the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``The folks at Daimler-Benz and the folks at Chrysler are a lot  
more alike than you might think,'' he said in an interview last 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	But in recent months, there have been signs of trouble in the  
marriage. In July, DaimlerChrysler announced lower-than-expected 
earnings, even though U.S. car buyers are on track to set an 
all-time record for yearly sales. The company said losses due to 
the Smart small cars sold in Europe, a weak Euro and trouble in 
Latin America dragged profits down. 
</P>
<P>
	Those concerns pushed the company's stock down from about $90 to  
about $75. News of Stallkamp's departure help send the stock to its 
all-time low Thursday of $66.25. It was up 3.2 percent Friday on 
the New York Stock Exchange, or by $2.12 1/2, to close at $68.37 1/2 a 
share. 
</P>
<P>
	Stallkamp ``was an icon of the old Chrysler Corp.,'' Lache said.  
``He was also very vocal since the merger and fairly critical of 
certain programs that didn't have a strong business position, such 
as Smart. He echoed shareholders views well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christian Breitsprecher, auto analyst at Deutsche Morgan  
Grenfell in Frankfurt, said the move consolidated Schrempp's power 
over the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to realize that this was never a 'merger of equals'  
to start with,'' he said. ``In the end it was clear that Schrempp 
would have the say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others said that since Eaton is scheduled to retire in a few  
years, Schrempp had already established himself as the company's 
leader, and the move was just another part of shuffling two 
companies together. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, the authority resides in Stuttgart,'' said Alan  
Baum, an analyst with IRN Inc. ``None of this is surprising -- that 
certain people didn't carry through. But I don't think anybody 
would have said a year ago that Stallkamp would not carry 
through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scott F. Merliss, an analyst with Wasserstein Perella Securites  
Inc. in New York, upgraded his view of the company after the 
announcement Friday, saying the company had a lot of profitable 
cars and trucks on the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sad to see Tom go, but they have great products with great  
earnings,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In an e-mail to employees, Stallkamp said he had left on good  
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``In any merger, issues may arise as a result of different  
styles or corporate cultures. But, these issues have been worked 
out, and will be worked out in the future, because they are not the 
result of personalities or national differences,'' Stallkamp said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 08:20:37 </DATE_TIME>
