<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Stocks Fall After U.S. Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices ended moderately lower on Wall Street  
today in a volatile session that saw stocks try in vain to regain 
some of the massive losses they suffered earlier this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average, down more than 505 points over  
the previous three sessions, lost an additional 39.26 and closed at 
10,279.33. The index changed course several times during the 
session. The Dow fell more than 127 points in morning trading, 
recovered to move into positive territory and then dropped more 
than 131 points in afternoon trading before recovering somewhat at 
the close. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow finished the week 524.30 points below last Friday's  
close, a loss of 4.9 percent. It has now dropped 9.2 percent from 
its record high close of 11,326.04, set Aug. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks also fell in overseas trading. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX  
index fell 2.13 percent and the CAC index in Paris fell 1.31 
percent. In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange index closed 
with a decline of 0.54 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the day, Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock  
Average dropped 454.03 points, or 2.62 percent. The Tokyo exchange 
was closed for a holiday Thursday, and today's slide followed a 
drop of 3.4 percent in share values on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks plunged Thursday in heavy selling on Wall Street as  
investors worried about higher interest rates and the strength of 
the dollar. A warning from Microsoft president Steve Ballmer that 
technology stocks are overvalued robbed the market of what had been 
a big source of strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street was also uneasy about the weakness of the dollar and  
the possibility of a third increase in U.S. interest rates this 
year. The Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee meets Oct. 5 to 
assess inflation and the economy and decide whether rates should be 
pushed higher once more. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said they expected the market to remain uncertain until  
after the Fed meeting. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 18:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unearthed Coffins Collected in N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Coast Guardsmen plied the 20-foot  
floodwaters of eastern North Carolina on Friday, trying to snag 
scores of coffins that popped out of the ground after Hurricane 
Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, a team of funeral home directors will begin  
identifying the wayward caskets to help get them back to what were 
supposed to be their final resting places. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing this to ensure that all the caskets are identified  
so that we can notify their loved ones,'' said Coast Guard Lt. 
Scott Bates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard crews spent the day in Princeville, across the  
Tar River from Tarboro, trying to round up as many as 100 airtight 
caskets that were forced from the ground by the river's 
floodwaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Too heavy to pull onto boats, the caskets were either towed to  
shore or tied to trees as Coast Guard crews recorded their 
locations. All appeared to be sealed. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers' ID numbers on the caskets can be traced to  
funeral homes and ultimately the families who bought them, but the 
bodies still must be identified and the coffins repaired before 
they are reburied, said Buddy Bell, a mortuary liaison officer for 
the U.S. Public Health Service. 
</P>
<P>
	Identifying the bodies could be as simple as a relative  
describing the clothing the person was buried in or it could 
require the use of dental records, officials said. Family members 
won't be asked to make visual identifications. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to be able to positively identify the person and  
assure the family they are getting their loved ones back,'' Bell 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Search crews, meanwhile, used dogs trained to detect bodies to  
look for victims of the floodwaters that swallowed Princeville, a 
town of 1,900, a week ago. At least 42 deaths have been blamed on 
Hurricane Floyd in eastern North Carolina alone, and the numbers 
could rise as floodwaters recede. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the river in downtown Tarboro, some business owners were  
finally able to get into their stores for the first time since 
floodwaters forced them to evacuate Sept. 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Rex Browning, 66, remained upbeat as he cleaned up his jewelry  
store five blocks from the river. The paneling was wilted 4 feet up 
the wall, marking the floodwaters' high point. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started here 42 years ago with nothing, so I guess I have  
more than that now,'' Browning said as he examined broken watches. 
</P>
<P>
	A stench filled the air and some people wore masks over their  
mouths and noses. Murky water poured into the streets from whirring 
pumps emptying businesses. Wet carpeting, twisted furniture and 
other items littered the sidewalks. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the day, dump trucks and other heavy construction  
equipment rumbled down the muddy streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Webb's office supply store was open again, thanks to a  
4-foot-high concrete dam she had built a week ago in front of the 
place. ``It was almost as hard to tear down as it was to build,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a week after 20 inches of rain fell on parts of the  
state, emergency management officials said 2,700 people remained in 
24 shelters. Preliminary damage estimates released by the state 
showed about 7,000 homes had been damaged and more than 600 had 
been destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Utility crews were able to restore power to nearly all the 1.5  
million people who lost electricity. But it could be at least two 
weeks before classes resume in all the school districts affected by 
the flooding. Eleven districts with about 176,000 students remained 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In some cases the schools are OK, but the communities are  
gone,'' said Ben Matthews, state director of school support. ``In 
other cases, the community is all right, but the road to the school 
is washed out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a visit to Greenville, Gov. Jim Hunt pledged to find the  
money for repairs and improvements so the region isn't ravaged by 
flooding again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to fix up something and have it happen again two  
years from now,'' he said. ``This time, fix it right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
