<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reggie May Join Bid To Buy Angels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hall of Famer Reggie Jackson, already part of  
a group trying to buy the Oakland Athletics, said he might be 
interested in entering a group bidding for the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson said he has discussed joining billionaires Henry  
Nicholas III and Henry Samueli in their attempt to buy the Angels 
from Disney. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Nicholas and Samueli and we have had a short visit,''  
Jackson told The Los Angeles Times. ``I'd certainly be interested, 
but there is nothing concrete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The slugger said he has met with Nicholas, president and chief  
executive officer of the Irvine-based semiconductor group Broadcom 
Corp., and Samueli, Broadcom's co-chairman and vice president, to 
discuss the possibility of his involvement if they were to buy the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's role could perhaps be as an investor and as an  
executive in the team's front office, the newspaper said. The 
report did not specify when the three had discussions. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Nicholas and a small group of investors,  
including Samueli, were reportedly close to a signing a letter of 
intent to buy the Angels and Mighty Ducks from the Walt Disney Co. 
for between $400 million and $500 million. Both Disney and Broadcom 
declined to comment on that report. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcom did not return calls from The Associated Press about  
Jackson's possible involvement. Disney spokeswoman Chris Castro 
declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Tavares, president of Disney subsidiary Anaheim Sports  
Inc., responded last week to sale rumors at the baseball owners 
meetings in New York. He acknowledged that Disney had been 
approached from people interested in the teams and said the company 
was ``in a listening mode.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any deal involving the Angels would need the approval of Major  
League Baseball. Tavares said last week that talks weren't at the 
stage where the team would seek permission from the commissioner's 
office to share its financial information with possible investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney bought the Angels for $140 million three years ago. The  
company also paid a $50 million franchise fee for the hockey team. 
However, both teams have not been big money makers. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest development in the speculation of the Angels' sale  
has the added wrinkle of bringing in a renowned baseball player who 
already has ties to the team. Jackson played on two of the team's 
three division winners during five years with the Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson is currently director of new business alliances for  
Viking Components, which makes computer memory. He is also a 
principal of Ulico Insurance Group of Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson has been involved in a group seeking to buy the A's, but  
major league owners recently shelved the deal, pending a report of 
a committee studying the sport's economic problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson told the Times he would be available to join Nicholas'  
investment group because he considered the A's purchase to be a 
dead issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Angels represent a great brand in a great market,''  
Jackson said. ``They've had a difficult year and will still draw 
more than 2 million. It's all there. They just need some strategic 
direction.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
