<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 13:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Bill Would Extend Tax Credits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Republican bill to renew expiring tax  
credits and protect millions of middle-class taxpayers from what 
the GOP called a tax ``time bomb'' began moving Friday in the 
House. It drew a fresh veto threat from the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The individual items in the five-year, $23.3 billion package  
have strong bipartisan support, but Treasury Secretary Lawrence 
Summers told Democrats privately he would recommend a veto because 
the measure would consume part of the projected budget surplus 
before other priorities are met. 
</P>
<P>
	That infuriated House Republicans, who accused President Clinton  
and Democrats of using the ``extenders'' package as a bargaining 
chip in larger spending and tax battles. The president vetoed the 
GOP's centerpiece 10-year, $792 billion tax cut a day earlier, but 
said he might sign a smaller package. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm terribly confused,'' said Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas,  
chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee. ``It is becoming 
painfully clear that the only specific priority for the president 
this fall is higher and higher Washington spending.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the top Democrat on the panel, Rep. Charles Rangel of New  
York, said the president was rightly holding the line on spending 
the budget surplus until the future solvency of Social Security and 
Medicare is ensured and the elderly gain a new prescription drug 
benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bill is not paid for,'' Rangel said. ``These are very,  
very popular items, but they don't want to work it out with the 
president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means Committee approved the extenders package on a  
strict party-line vote after defeating a Democratic alternative 
that would have paid the costs by closing several corporate tax 
shelters. The bill next moves to the full House. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally part of the larger tax cut, the package includes a  
five-year extension of the research and development tax credit 
popular with high-tech industry and manufacturers. In addition, it 
would permanently ensure that middle-class taxpayers who claim 
credits such as the $500-per-child credit do not become entangled 
in the complex, costly alternative minimum tax, or AMT. 
</P>
<P>
	Archer estimated that unless the AMT fix is approved, 1 million  
taxpayers could be faced with higher income taxes -- ``the tax-hike 
time bomb,'' he said -- if they claim too many credits. The AMT was 
originally intended to prevent the wealthy from escaping taxes 
through legal credits and deductions, but it is not indexed for 
inflation and has been affecting more and more people with modest 
incomes. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also renews credits encouraging businesses to hire  
former welfare recipients and people from groups who traditionally 
have trouble keeping jobs. It extends an oil and gas provision and 
one exempting from taxes certain foreign corporate income from 
banking, insurance or financing business. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the bill would be paid for using projected budget  
surpluses, but its $1.5 billion cost in fiscal 2000 would be offset 
by raising taxes on high-income individuals for that year only. 
Also to save money, companies would be temporarily ``suspended'' 
from taking the R&AMP;D credit until Oct. 1, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The veto rhetoric aside, the sheer popularity of the extenders  
and the need to get them done quickly -- the Internal Revenue 
Service says it needs guidance by Oct. 7 to do the proper AMT forms 
-- means they will likely win final approval one way or another. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the package is one more piece of leverage the White  
House can use to push through at least its Medicare reform and 
prescription drug benefit, if not a Social Security fix. 
</P>
<P>
	Toward that end, Summers and White House Chief of Staff John  
Podesta met Friday with Senate Finance Committee Chairman William 
Roth, R-Del., to begin exploring common ground on these issues as 
well as tax relief. Roth has said he will work this fall on a 
Medicare reform bill, including prescription drugs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
