<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hakkinen Blazes Practice in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NUERBURGRING, Germany (AP) -- Mika Hakkinen, the defending  
Formula One champion, drove his McLaren-Mercedes to the fastest 
time in Friday's free practice for the European Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far everything has gone well and we will continue to focus  
on improving the car over the weekend,'' said Hakkinen, who hopes 
to bounce back from his major disappointment two weeks ago in the 
Italian Grand Prix at Monza. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen was comfortably in the lead when he made a mistake and  
spun out of the race. He then broke down in tears. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of strengthening his lead in the drivers' standings,  
Hakkinen dropped into a tie for first place with Eddie Irvine, who 
is seeking to become the first Ferrari driver to win the title in 
20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen and Irvine are tied at 60 points, with three races left  
in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	A victory Sunday, worth 10 points, would give either driver a  
significant lead before the championship is decided in the final 
two races -- in Malaysia Oct. 17 and Japan Oct. 31. Second place 
brings only six points. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen dominated Friday's two practice sessions and will be  
favorite to win his 12th pole position of the season in Saturday's 
qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an interesting track for a driver as you carry a lot  
of speed into the corners, but this also means that you have to 
work hard to get the balance right,'' said Hakkinen, whose team 
used only one set of tires. 
</P>
<P>
	A Ferrari was second, although it was not driven not by Irvine  
but his teammate Mika Salo, giving Finnish drivers the top two 
places in the practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen's best lap on the 2.831-mile Nuerburgring was one  
minute, 20.758 seconds. Salo was clocked in 1:20.920, just .162 
behind Hakkinen. 
</P>
<P>
	Free practice times may not mean much for the qualifying and the  
race itself since many teams use the two sessions to experiment 
with various setups. 
</P>
<P>
	``All the work we have done over the past few days has paid off  
and the car is much better, although not perfect,'' Irvine said. 
``The main effect of the changes is that we have more grip.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
