<DOCNO> APW19990924.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 04:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Senators Form Waco Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Democrats are refusing to participate  
in a Republican-led task force that will investigate how President 
Clinton's Justice Department handled inquiries into the Waco 
standoff, alleged campaign finance abuses and nuclear espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	A key Democratic lawmaker scoffed at the Republican's offer to  
make the probe bipartisan, saying the task force had been set up 
over Democratic objections and had been announced to reporters 
first. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a Republican task force. No Democrats have been  
involved,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont, the senior Democrat 
on the Senate Judiciary Committee. ``I don't intend to be part of a 
Republican-organized, partisan investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At an earlier news conference, Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott, R-Miss., said the task force would be chaired by Sen. Arlen 
Specter, R-Pa., and would focus on ``what in the world is happening 
at the Justice Department, why is there no justice at the Justice 
Department?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott said the five-member task force would include two Democrats  
and two more Republicans in addition to Specter. But only one other 
Republican member, Sen. Charles Grassley of Iowa, was present at 
Thursday's announcement. No Democrats attended. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans had squabbled among themselves for weeks over the  
size and scope of the probe. But even as they debated, Specter was 
moving forward. He said his aides had traveled to Texas to preserve 
evidence collected from the FBI's 1993 siege against members of the 
Branch Davidian cult. The 51-day siege ended when the cult's 
compound near Waco erupted in flames. Davidian leader David Koresh 
and some 80 followers died during the inferno, some from fire, 
others from gunshot wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Specter said his aides found only one of two canisters that  
federal agents only recently admitted firing. ``Nobody knows'' what 
happened to the other one, Specter said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also confirmed he had talked with Charles LaBella about  
leading the panel's investigation. LaBella is a former Justice 
Department prosecutor who publicly disagreed with Attorney General 
Janet Reno's decision not to have an outside, independent counsel 
investigate alleged fund-raising abuses by the Clinton-Gore 
campaign in the 1996 election. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a great, great many questions which are left  
unanswered,'' Specter said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Things just aren't right,'' agreed Grassley.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina will round out the  
Republican side of the panel, Specter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Specter said that at the request of former Sen. John Danforth he  
will hold off for 30 days before talking to witnesses to the 
government siege. Reno named Danforth to head an independent 
investigation of the government's use of force against the 
Davidians. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to the Judiciary Committee last week, Danforth  
complained that Specter's investigators already had interviewed 
witnesses. ``In the interest of avoiding even the appearance of a 
turf battle,'' Specter told reporters Thursday, he agreed to hold 
off on interviews. 
</P>
<P>
	The probes were sparked by public disclosures last month that  
the FBI used the potentially incendiary tear gas on the final day 
of the siege. Although Republicans had accused the FBI of covering 
up use of such devices for years, the Justice Department, in fact, 
had informed Congress in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials maintain that Branch Davidians, and not  
federal agents, set the fatal fire on April 19, 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the Senate Judiciary Committee  
chairman, had wanted a narrowly focused probe; Specter and Lott 
advocated a broader look at the Justice Department. Hatch did not 
attend Thursday's news conference on the issue, and later told 
reporters he grudgingly signed off on Specter's plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have preferred it be done another way,'' Hatch said.  
``It's out of my hands now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Specter was ready to start putting a staff in place. LaBella, he  
said, ``would hit the ground with a sprint.'' But he added that he 
will not extend a formal offer to LaBella until after he has spoken 
with Democrats over the next few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerned that LaBella's stewardship of an investigation that  
would focus largely on his former boss' performance, Specter said 
he has received informal approval for the hiring from officials on 
the Senate Ethics Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	LaBella would have intimate knowledge of the campaign finance  
investigation, but Specter said the task force probe would stretch 
to a third topic, the Justice Department's handling of alleged 
nuclear espionage by China. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI has expanded its China spying probe following criticism  
that for more than three years it focused too narrowly on the Los 
Alamos nuclear weapons lab in New Mexico. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 14:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  London Stages Fashion Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Shrugging off the absence of several of its stars,  
London Fashion Week again proved it deserves its reputation for 
exciting, cutting-edge design. 
</P>
<P>
	From Hussein Chalayan's remote-controlled glass-fiber dress over  
a fluffy pink tutu, to Amanda Wakeley's sleekly classic evening 
sheaths, London has not lost its wow factor -- or its claim to be a 
fashion capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, it's been what people love London about: very  
extreme, very bold, very exciting,'' said designer Paul Costelloe, 
who opened proceedings Monday night with a collection of long 
tunics and fluid trousers in the brightest pinks. 
</P>
<P>
	While fashion ``may grow up elsewhere,'' said Daily Telegraph  
fashion editor Hilary Alexander, ``London is where you see fashion 
being born.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 40 designers held catwalk shows over four days and  
more than 200 others exhibited accessories and jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
	The look for spring/summer 2000 is ruched, ruffled and ridged,  
in layers of buttery leather, delicate lace or wisps of chiffon 
printed with florals, spots and stripes or scattered with sequins. 
The palette is white, moss, flesh tones and pastels. Look for 
blouson tops, the tiniest hot pants and daring backless dresses 
with this season's new neckline, the halter. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander McQueen, Vivienne Westwood and Nicole Farhi opted out  
of the London scene after unveiling their collections in New York 
last week. And once again, Antonio Berardi will stage his show in 
Milan. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chalayan, the British Designer of the Year, was there with  
an array of his trademark precision-cut garments. 
</P>
<P>
	In keeping with the season's very feminine look, he showed  
concertina frills and fluted hems on tutus and ballerina dresses. 
Some had cutaway backs with intricately scrolled petticoats that 
resembled rosebuds. 
</P>
<P>
	A child used a remote control device to open the glass-fiber  
panels of one dress, revealing a confection of tulle petticoats. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Smith produced trouser suits and shirts in candy stripes  
that evoked gracious 1920s tennis parties, and embroidered velvets 
inspired by India. Owen Gaster shone with skirts in skin-tight 
snakeskin, tailored pink tweed and leather printed with holograms. 
</P>
<P>
	Red or Dead's Wayne Hemingway sent ``real people'' down the  
catwalk in African prints and outfits in batik, cheesecloth and 
crushed linen, hessian, muslin and leather. He said he decided not 
to use models to give ``a sense of an egalitarian future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Welsh designer Julien Macdonald, known for his glorious knits,  
injected a note of glamour by having Mel G -- Scary Spice to her 
fans -- model a translucent pink beaded dress with slim jeweled 
straps. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Macdonald creations included vivid PVC bomber jackets  
printed with computer graphics, tie-dye jackets and fluorescent 
miniskirts and mirrored halter dresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Another up-and-coming designer, Matthew Williamson, produced  
sequin-studded camisoles and low-slung ``harem'' skirts studded 
with jewels, inspired by India's exotic Kathkali dancers. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, most shows were held in marquees erected at the main  
venue, the Natural History Museum. But this year many designers 
opted for the battered warehouses that line Brick Lane in east 
London, the historical home of Britain's garment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	They included Preen, which showed dramatically draped leather  
tunics with halter tops and torn hems and Clements Ribeiro, who 
produced dresses, blouson tops, skirts and micro shorts in 
transparent chiffon scattered with flowers or sequins in pink, 
plum, brown and yellow. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonja Nuttall displayed her pleated and ruched outfits in stone,  
black and honey on racks in the back of a parked truck. 
</P>
<P>
	The $28 billion a year British fashion industry now employs  
300,000 people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 15:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Strikes Back at GOP Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pat Buchanan accused Republican presidential  
rivals on Friday of `piling on me'' in their criticism of his views 
about Nazi Germany, as he prepared to consult with Reform Party 
founder Ross Perot about possibly leaving the GOP for a third-party 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican and conservative leaders, including at least three  
fellow presidential candidates, have issued harsh judgments of 
Buchanan's campaign book, ``A Republican, Not an Empire.'' The book 
questioned the timing of United States' entry into World War II and 
its participation in the battle against Adolf Hitler. 
</P>
<P>
	In a detailed statement, Buchanan argued that ``liberal  
interventionism,'' not isolationism, spawned Hitler's fascism. 
``While the West is busy erecting Holocaust museums, it has failed 
to study the history that produced it,'' Buchanan said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, the United States is handing out war guarantees all  
over Eastern Europe, guarantees a future generation of Americans 
may refuse to honor, guarantees that are driving a defeated, 
demoralized, divided and democratic Russia, with 20,000 nuclear 
weapons, straight into the arms of a Chinese Communist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the book was written to prevent ``that cataclysm.''  
</P>
<P>
	``As for my Republican rivals, opportunistically piling on me,  
to the giddy applause of the establishment, do you really think you 
will be spared should you also violate the normal of political 
correctness and speak the truth to power?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential rivals John McCain, Elizabeth Dole and Steve Forbes  
have questioned Buchanan's writings in highly critical terms. 
McCain said Republicans should welcome Buchanan's departure from 
the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Front-runner George W. Bush said in an interview Friday that he  
wants Buchanan to remain Republican, though he disagreed with his 
opinion that Germany was not a threat to the United States after 
1940. ``Germany (was) a threat,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, meanwhile, was planning to hold a long-expected  
conversation with Perot by telephone in the next few days, 
according to officials close to both men. 
</P>
<P>
	For Buchanan, the call is a matter of courtesy extended to the  
party's founder. He also may get a sense of Perot's feelings about 
his potential candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Reform Party is the house that Ross built,'' Buchanan  
said, ``and I've got a great respect for Mr. Perot and what he went 
through to build that party and to challenge the two incumbent 
parties, and I would certainly want to speak with him about what 
his intentions were and what he believed is best for that party 
because I think he'd have great influence upon what could happen 
and would happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked what he would like most about the prospect of being the  
Reform nominee, he talked about his place in the presidential 
debates next fall ``standing up on a platform with W. and Al Gore 
for 90 minutes three times in October in the year 2000 because I 
think the debates would probably then decide the election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan has no assurances from Perot or knowledgeable  
associates that the party founder will endorse him, officials in 
both camps said Friday. Nor does Buchanan know whether Perot would 
agree to not block a Buchanan bid, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	They spoke on condition of anonymity, and have cautioned for  
days that Perot has not tipped his hand. However, Buchanan's team 
has been given strong encouragement by Perot supporters, such as 
his former running mate, Pat Choate. 
</P>
<P>
	One senior Perot adviser said it is conceivable that the party  
founder could enter the race himself if an economic crisis or other 
tragedy triggered a groundswell of calls for his candidacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Perot has said little about his plans for 2000.  
</P>
<P>
	``The deafening silence says that he will abide by the  
collective will of the party and not stand in the way of Buchanan 
or (Donald) Trump or George W. Bush, should he decide to leave that 
failed (Republican) Party,'' outgoing Reform Party chairman Russell 
Verney said, denying that Perot is implicitly backing Buchanan. 
</P>
<P>
	In another sign that Buchanan is on the brink of bolting, the  
New Hampshire Reform Party postponed its convention this week after 
Buchanan advisers tried to gain control of the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Others mentioned as potential Reform Party presidential nominees  
are real estate tycoon Trump of New York and Minnesota Gov. Jesse 
Ventura, highest-elected official in the party. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 14:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
