<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Third Man' Tops 100 British Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- ``The Third Man,'' a classic tale of intrigue set  
in post-World War II Vienna, has been named the best British film 
of the century in a poll announced this week by the British Film 
Industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Other films to make the top 10 ranged from Alfred Hitchcock's  
``The 39 Steps,'' at No. 4, to Nicholas Roeg's erotic chiller 
``Don't Look Now,'' at No. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	David Lean was responsible for three top citations, with ``Brief  
Encounter,'' ``Lawrence of Arabia'' and ``Great Expectations'' -- 
placing second, third and fifth, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Alec Guinness starred in more listed films than anyone else,  
with nine, while Michael Caine headlined in seven and Julie 
Christie starred in six. 
</P>
<P>
	The list was chosen by 1,000 people in the British film and  
television industries, who collectively cast 25,700 votes covering 
820 films. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Third Man,'' directed by Carol Reed, is a stylish 1949  
adaptation of a Graham Greene thriller. Filmed against a backdrop 
of ruined buildings and starring Orson Welles and Joseph Cotten, it 
contains some of cinema's most memorable black-and-white images. 
The background theme of zither music is so powerfully connected to 
the story that it is instantly recognized by anyone who has seen 
the film. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the results, the '60s were the evident golden age for  
British movies. Twenty-six films from that decade made the list, as 
opposed to 17 from the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one recent film made the top 10 -- ``Trainspotting,''  
director Danny Boyle's scabrous 1996 look at heroin addicts in 
Scotland. It is also movie that launched Ewan McGregor as an 
international name. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oscar-winning ``Shakespeare In Love,'' Shekhar Kapur's  
``Elizabeth'' and Ken Loach's ``My Name Is Joe'' were three other 
films from last year to make the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of the choices may surprise Americans, since they  
include such films as ``The English Patient,'' ``Sense and 
Sensibility,'' and ``Shakespeare In Love,'' all of which were made 
either largely or wholly with American money. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the purposes of the poll, the industry qualified as a  
British film any movie employing a substantial number of Britons. 
All three of the movies named above used British talent who went on 
to win Academy Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	While most of the films draw on original scripts, many are  
adaptations of novels and plays, reflecting Britain's rich literary 
heritage. Shakespeare, Dickens, Alan Bennett, and Graham Greene 
were among the authorial heavyweights to have made the list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 15:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Crew Chief Leaving Gordon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Jeff Gordon is losing the only crew chief he  
has had in his Winston Cup career. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN-SI reported Friday that Ray Evernham is quitting after  
helping Gordon win three championships in the last four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The network, citing no sources, said Evernham will act as  
Gordon's crew chief for this weekend's MNBA Gold 400, but mechanic 
Brian Whitesell will make the race-day calls. Whitesell will 
replace Evernham when he leaves, perhaps before the end of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Evernham and John Hendrick, head of Hendrick Motorsports, had no  
comment when asked about the report Friday at Dover Downs 
International Speedway. The company plans an announcement next 
month concerning Gordon's team. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon was unable to shed much light on the report.  
</P>
<P>
	``The plan all along has been to take our guys and step them up  
in our program,'' he said. ``That's been Ray's wishes. 
</P>
<P>
	``It looked like things were going to be taking place anyway,  
and we are basically stepping into a little of that right now. 
We're still trying to figure out how everything is going to shake 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evernham has helped Gordon win 47 Winston Cup races. For months,  
there have been reports of friction between Evernham and the 
Hendrick organization. His contract runs through the 2006 season, 
but CNN-SI said a release is being negotiated. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of Evernham's departure has caused speculation that  
he will start his own Winston Cup team. This season, he and Gordon 
started a Busch Grand National team under the banner of 
Gordon-Evernham Motorsports. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN-SI said Gordon is expected to sign a long-term contract with  
Hendrick, which would include partial ownership of all three 
Hendrick teams. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 08:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Starts Hilliard Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. Earl Hilliard is promising full  
cooperation with a House ethics committee investigation into 
allegations arising from his personal and political financial 
activities since his election to Congress in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee announced Thursday that it wants to find out if  
the Alabama Democrat violated House rules or federal laws in three 
specific areas: 
</P>
<P>
	--Loans his campaign committee made to specific individuals in  
1993 and 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	--The Birmingham office space his campaign occupied from 1992  
through 1998, including expenditures for rent and utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	--His compliance with federal financial disclosure laws from 1992  
to 1999 regarding his ownership interest in two companies, 
Hilliards &AMP; Co. Inc., and the Birmingham Greater Golf Associates 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will cooperate with the committee,'' Hilliard said. ``I've  
been through this before and I don't see any reason not to 
cooperate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hilliard said the investigation involves old issues that he  
thought had been resolved. He said he fully expected to be 
exonerated. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics committee asked Hilliard in January 1998 to respond  
to a list of questions about his personal and business dealings 
that were raised by a series of newspaper articles. Hilliard said 
he answered a second, detailed list of questions from the committee 
in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hill, a weekly newspaper that covers Congress, reported in  
late 1997 that Hilliard's campaign committee had paid more than 
$100,000 to companies and nonprofit organizations linked to the 
lawmaker in the six years since he first began campaigning for 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Election Commission records show that since 1992,  
Hilliard's campaign paid $67,100 in rent to various companies that 
share the same address as the congressman's campaign headquarters 
in Birmingham. 
</P>
<P>
	During the same six-year period, the campaign also has made  
payments to companies or nonprofit organizations with links to 
Hilliard, totaling $16,800 for radio advertising fees, $5,973 for 
insurance premiums and $7,200 for donations. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal election law permits campaigns to use candidate-owned  
companies as long as they pay market rates for goods and services. 
The Hill said some of the payments by Hilliard's campaign suggest 
that they may have been converted to personal use or used for 
non-campaign purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee's questions about Hilliard's compliance with  
financial disclosure laws apparently stems from his failure to 
report his interest in Hilliards and Co. and in Birmingham Greater 
Golf Associates Inc. on the financial disclosure forms members of 
Congress must file each year. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilliard said he had filed amendments listing the two companies,  
even though he still contends he was not required to disclose them 
because neither had any assets or value. 
</P>
<P>
	On the loan question, Hilliard said his campaign committee did  
make loans to several individuals who worked for the campaign, but 
he denied any wrongdoing. He said one loan was repaid and two 
others were not. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics committee named Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, to head the  
investigation, and Rep. Martin Olav Sabo, D-Minn., to serve as 
ranking Democrat. Others named to the investigating panel were 
Reps. Kenny Hulshof, R-Mo., and Rep. James Clyburn, D-S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Under committee rules, the panel will decide by majority vote  
whether to file formal charges against Hilliard. Any such charges 
then would be heard by a separate subcommittee. The full ethics 
committee eventually would have to approve any report to the House 
recommending action against Hilliard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 10:40:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Worries About Vietnam Nagged LBJ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Exhausted from campaigning in 1964, President  
Johnson was so worried about the conflict in southeast Asia that 
there was no time for the Texan to bask in what would be the 
largest popular majority vote ever received by a president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wish you'd go get some sun somewhere in Key West or  
something like that,'' Bill Moyers, a special assistant to Johnson 
told him on the phone before the returns were in on Election Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson yawned loudly into the phone and replied that he  
couldn't -- something weighed on his mind: ``I'm afraid of 
Vietnam.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conversation was among the latest batch of Johnson  
recordings released today by the Lyndon Baines Johnson Library in 
Austin, Texas. The tapes are mostly from November and December 
1964, a year after Johnson ascended to the presidency when John F. 
Kennedy was assassinated. 
</P>
<P>
	The tapes capture Johnson's election night phone calls to and  
from supporters. His earthy and often blunt responses were tempered 
by his worries about America's involvement in the Vietnam conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in trouble in Vietnam, serious trouble,'' Johnson told  
Hubert H. Humphrey, his vice presidential running mate shortly 
before 6 p.m. on Election Day -- when they were still guessing how 
large their victory would be. 
</P>
<P>
	Often during the calls Johnson aired his worries over Vietnam  
and sought counsel. 
</P>
<P>
	In a conversation from his Texas ranch with Attorney General  
Robert F. Kennedy, Johnson kidded about how long it took Republican 
presidential candidate Barry Goldwater to concede the election. 
Kennedy said many people sympathized with Johnson about his having 
to wait for the concession speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I'm going to need a hell of a lot of it, I'll tell you  
that,'' Johnson said. ``In the meantime, if you get any solution 
for Vietnam just call me direct, will you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kennedy replied, ``I've got a thought about that.''  
</P>
<P>
	``I want to talk to you,'' said Johnson.  
</P>
<P>
	But the conversation was not without its jocular moment. Earlier  
Johnson and Senate Majority Leader Mike Mansfield, D-Mont., kidded 
Humphrey about donning Western clothes and riding a horse during 
his visit at the ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	``You look great in that Western outfit,'' says Mansfield to  
Humphrey, who was listening in on the line. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you hear what Hubert announced in his speech here?'' says  
Johnson. ``By God, he said he'd resign if there was any more 
horseback riding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Humphrey joked that his Western clothes were ``droopy,'' and  
blamed it on Johnson: ``After all, the president was the man that 
dressed me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
