<DOCNO> APW19990924.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 13:10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Prepares Bare-Bones Tax Measure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Opening a new front in the tax battle, House  
Republicans today began moving a $23.2 billion, five-year measure 
to renew a handful of expiring tax credits that immediately drew a 
fresh veto threat from the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after President Clinton vetoed the GOP's 10-year, $792  
billion tax cut, the House Ways and Means Committee approved the 
``extenders'' measure on a strict party-line vote, clearing it for 
floor action. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally part of the larger bill, the new bill includes a  
five-year extension of the research and development tax credit 
popular with high-tech industry and manufacturers. It would 
permanently ensure that middle-class taxpayers who claim credits 
such as the $500-per-child credit do not become entangled in the 
complex, costly alternative minimum tax. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means Committee chairman, Rep. Bill Archer,  
R-Texas, said the panel was acting with dispatch because the 
Internal Revenue Service needs guidance by Oct. 7 to draft the 
proper tax forms for filing season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unless tax law changes were made by Oct. 7, they would have  
real problems holding down costs and making next year's tax filing 
season run smoothly,'' Archer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the items in the package have bipartisan support, a  
Treasury Department official said Clinton would likely veto it 
because it would spend part of the projected budget surplus over 
five years before agreement is reached on the future solvency of 
Social Security and Medicare. Clinton gave those same reasons for 
his veto of the larger GOP tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The new bill ``does not follow the framework set out by the  
president,'' said Jon Talisman, a top Treasury tax official. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also faces an uncertain future in the Senate, where  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said its success requires that 
members of Congress -- particularly in the Senate -- have the 
discipline not to use it as a vehicle to load up other pet tax 
items. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'd have to have a lot of cooperation,'' Lott said. ``It  
tends to be the engine that pulls a lot of cars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a Rose Garden ceremony Thursday, Clinton followed through on  
his repeated promise to veto the larger $792 billion, 10-year GOP 
tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	``At a time when America is moving in the right direction, this  
bill would turn us back to the failed policies of the past,'' the 
president said. 
</P>
<P>
	That bill would have reduced all income tax rates by 1  
percentage point, eased the marriage penalty on many two-income 
couples, eliminate estate taxes and the alternative minimum income 
tax, reduce capital gains taxes, expand pension and 401(k) laws and 
provide numerous business tax breaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said the GOP measure would undermine efforts to shore up  
the Social Security and Medicare programs, to reduce the national 
debt and to improve education. ``The bill is too big, too bloated, 
places too great a burden on America's economy,'' the president 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would force drastic cuts in education, health care and  
other vital areas,'' Clinton added. ``It would cripple our ability 
to pay down the debt. It would not add a day to the Social Security 
trust fund, it would not add a day to the Medicare trust fund or 
modernize Medicare with prescription drug coverage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans disputed the president and said he had killed tax  
relief for families, for education and for low-income Americans. 
``I regret the president has stolen this tax cut from working 
American families,'' Lott said in a remark echoed by GOP 
colleagues. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders said they would now concentrate on fixing Social  
Security, preventing $248 billion in tax increases urged by the 
administration over 10 years, restraining the growth of government 
and reducing the debt. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
