<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Move Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
        CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices settled mostly higher  
Friday in mixed trading ahead of a big harvest weekend. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat led the gains, responding to rumors that Egypt would  
be purchasing wheat. Prices also was buoyed by heavy Iranian wheat 
imports and by Indonesia's rejection of an Australian wheat deal. 
</P>
<P>
        Corn and soybeans rose on false rumors, traders said, of a  
change in the U.S. Department of Agriculture's loan policy which could 
limit the amount of crops on the market. 
</P>
<P>
        But gains were limited by forecasts predicting weekend weather  
beneficial to harvests throughout the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
        Wheat for December delivery rose 4 1/2 cents to $2.77 3/4 a  
bushel; December corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.08 3/4 a bushel; December 
oats were unchanged at $1.13 1/4 a bushel; November soybeans rose 2 
cents to $4.80 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
        Beef and pork futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.  
</P>
<P>
        October live cattle rose .60 cent to 66.97 cents a pound; October  
feeder cattle rose .62 cent to 80.02 cents a pound; October lean hogs 
rose .40 cent to 46.50 cents a pound; February frozen pork bellies 
rose 3 cents to 62.42 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
