<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ousted Mayor Sues Miami Herald </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Former Mayor Xavier Suarez has filed a libel suit  
against The Miami Herald, accusing the newspaper of portraying him 
as unstable in its Pulitzer Prize-winning coverage of his 
fraud-riddled election. 
</P>
<P>
	Suarez complained about both news stories and columns, citing,  
among others, columnist Carl Hiaasen, who repeatedly called Suarez 
``Mayor Loco'' in print. The lawsuit was filed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Herald managing editor Larry Olmstead called the lawsuit  
groundless. 
</P>
<P>
	Suarez, a lawyer, said the Herald caused him to lose standing in  
Miami's legal community. He estimated the stories cost him $100,000 
in earnings in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	A voter-fraud scandal following the 1997 mayoral election led to  
criminal charges against 57 people, but not Suarez. 
</P>
<P>
	Suarez led Miami through most of the 1980s, but a state appeals  
court threw out his most recent victory and named Joe Carollo 
mayor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
