<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Kinkel Pleads Guilty to Murder  
</P>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Abandoning an insanity defense, Kip Kinkel,  
17, pleaded guilty today to murdering his parents at home and then 
shooting to death two classmates at Springfield's Thurston High 
School. He could get a life sentence. Kinkel had told investigators 
after his arrest that he had ``no choice'' but to kill after 
shaming his parents by getting expelled from school. His attorneys 
had hoped to spare him life in prison by proving he was insane, or 
at least disturbed to the point that he was not fully in control of 
his actions. Because he was just 15 at the time of the crimes, 
Kinkel never faced the death penalty. 

</P>
<P>
	Troops Search East Timor Capital  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Amid reports that entire towns in the  
hinterland had been emptied and torched, multinational peacekeeping 
troops on Friday searched house-to-house for militia suspects in 
East Timor's capital. About 1,000 multinational troops, backed by 
armored personnel carriers and two Blackhawk helicopters, sealed 
off several city blocks in Dili. Earlier, the peacekeepers said 
they had arrested a leader of a pro-Indonesia militia suspected of 
committing atrocities after East Timor's overwhelming vote for 
independence on Aug. 30. 

</P>
<P>
	Italy Jury Acquits Andreotti  
</P>
<P>
	PERUGIA, Italy (AP) -- A jury today acquitted former Premier  
Giulio Andreotti of the 1979 murder of an Italian journalist after 
a three-year trial. After four days of deliberations, the jury of 
two judges and six private citizens concluded there was no proof to 
convict Andreotti, 80, one of Italy's most powerful and enduring 
politicians. Andreotti, who was premier seven times and is a 
senator-for-life, was indicted for premeditated murder along with 
five other people in the 1979 slaying of journalist Mino Pecorelli. 

</P>
<P>
	Typhoon in Japan Kills 15  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Typhoon Bart lashed southern Japan today, sweeping  
huge waves over homes, knocking cranes onto buildings and leaving 
at least 15 people dead.Dozens were injured and hundreds of 
thousands were left without power when Bart, packing winds of 
nearly 80 mph, pounded Japan's main southwestern island of Kyushu. 
It was expected to pass over the Sea of Japan before shooting over 
the northern island of Hokkaido on Saturday, the agency said. It 
was likely to miss Tokyo. 

</P>
<P>
	Ovarian Implant Called Success  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Young women left infertile due to cancer or  
other ailments may someday have children thanks to an experimental 
ovarian tissue transplant that a doctor says restored a menopausal 
woman's menstrual cycle. Larry Lipshultz, president of the American 
Society for Reproductive Medicine, said that this case indicates 
researchers are on the cusp of safe, reliable transplantation of 
human ovarian tissue. 

</P>
<P>
	George Magazine To Stay Alive  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A co-owner of George magazine is making plans to  
keep the publication alive, but with fewer issues each year, 
following the death of John F. Kennedy Jr., its charismatic founder 
and editor. Hachette Filipacchi Magazines, which shared ownership 
of the magazine with Kennedy, announced Friday the magazine would 
cut back to 10 issues a year from 12 next year but would guarantee 
advertisers a larger circulation. Starting with the February 2000 
issue, advertisers are being promised circulation of 450,000 per 
issue of the magazine that mixed political commentary and celebrity 
profiles, up 12.5 percent from the current 400,000. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 17.10; Nasdaq Falls 12.41  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before the close, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 17.10 points at 10,301.49. Decliners on the New 
York Stock Exchange lead advancers 1,924-1,014. The Nasdaq was down 
12.41 at 2,737.42. 

</P>
<P>
	AL Umpire Suspended Three Games  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Shulock became the second umpire to be  
disciplined this season when he was suspended by the American 
League today for three games for his ``display of temper'' in a 
game this week. AL president Gene Budig suspended Shulock and fined 
him an undisclosed amount. The penalties were levied, Budig said, 
for Shulock's ``overly aggressive behavior, display of temper, 
inappropriate remarks and physical contact'' with Tampa Bay catcher 
Mike DeFelice during and following the Devils Rays' game against 
the Anaheim Angels on Monday. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD  
  	   	
</P>
