<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Aid Sent to Victims of Russia Blast  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Trucks carrying tons of aid for victims of a  
Russian apartment blast have arrived in the city of Volgodonsk, the 
ITAR-Tass news agency reported today. The aid for the hundreds of 
people left homeless by the Sept. 18 explosion included food and 
clothing along with construction materials such as doors and 
windows. Volgodonsk is about 500 miles south of Moscow. The blast, 
in which 18 people died, was one of four apartment explosions this 
month that killed some 300 people. Authorities blame the blasts on 
Islamic militants from breakaway Chechnya. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Proposes IMF Changes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, responding to  
growing criticism about its policies toward Russia, says it will 
push for changes at the International Monetary Fund to make sure 
Russia and other countries don't misuse the billions of dollars the 
IMF provides in loans. While insisting the administration's overall 
approach to Russia has been sound, Treasury Secretary Lawrence 
Summers unveiled proposals yesterday that would call on the IMF to 
make wider use of independent audits and allow the lending agency 
to impose stiffer penalties for countries caught lying. 

</P>
<P>
	East Timorese Militia Man Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Multinational peacekeeping forces said  
today they had arrested a leader of a notorious anti-independence 
militia, a move intended to send a message to those out to wreak 
havoc in East Timor. ``You can't run, you can't hide, justice is 
here,'' said Maj. Chip Henriss-Anderssen, who announced the arrest 
of Caitano Da Silva, a platoon commander and the most senior member 
of the Aitarak militia to be caught so far. 

</P>
<P>
	Jakarta Gripped by More Protests  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Violent protests gripped the streets  
of Jakarta for the second day today, as riot police firing rubber 
bullets struggled to contain crowds enraged by a new law giving the 
military power to curb civil liberties. Three people were killed 
and 115 others injured since the protests began Thursday morning, 
hospital officials said. One of the three was a police officer who 
was killed when he was run over by a car. About 500 riot police 
stormed the Atma Jaya Catholic University before dawn, firing 
volleys of tear gas and rubber bullets at students who had taken 
over the campus. 

</P>
<P>
	Hope for Quake Survivors Fade  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- On a day traditionally reserved for joyous  
celebration, Taiwanese today vented anger at their government's 
bungled life-saving efforts and mourned the more than 2,100 people 
who perished in a deadly earthquake. ``The government reacted too 
slowly. It was many hours before they sent in troops to rescue 
victims and many hours until they sent helicopters,'' said Tsai 
Chia-ching as Buddhist monks chanted prayers for the dead at a 
Taipei memorial service. The government admits it was not fully 
prepared to cope with a disaster of such magnitude, even though 
Taiwan is prone to periodic quakes. 

</P>
<P>
	Men executed in Delaware, N.C.  
</P>
<P>
	SMYRNA, Del. (AP) -- A man described by his lawyers as mentally  
retarded was executed by injection early today for the stabbing and 
beating death of an elderly greenhouse worker. Willie Sullivan, 28, 
was pronounced dead at 12:24 a.m. He became the 10th person 
executed in Delaware since the state resumed capital punishment in 
1992. Also today, in North Carolina, Harvey Lee Green was executed 
by injection at 2:16 a.m. for the beating deaths of two people. The 
38-year-old was the first black person executed in that state since 
it restored the death penalty in 1977. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Vetoes GOP's $792B Tax Cut  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Believing they have a 2000 campaign issue in  
President Clinton's veto of a $792 billion tax cut, Republicans are 
turning their attention to a modest bill that would renew a handful 
of popular expiring tax credits. GOP leaders said Thursday's veto 
likely doomed any chance for a broad tax cut this year. But the 
House Ways and Means Committee today was scheduled to begin moving 
the ``extenders'' package tentatively estimated at $22 billion over 
five years. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Plunge  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo share prices fell today. The Nikkei shed  
454.03 points to close at 16,871.73. 

</P>
<P>
	Dodgers 5, Giants 3  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Chan Ho Park won his sixth straight decision  
last night as the Los Angeles Dodgers beat the sputtering San 
Francisco Giants 5-3, clinching a tie for the NL West title for the 
Arizona Diamondbacks. San Francisco has lost five of six -- 
including three of four to the Dodgers -- and is a season-worst 9 1/2 
games out of first place with nine to play. Arizona has 10 games 
remaining. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
