<HEADLINE> Angelica Huston Honored in Spain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN SEBASTIAN, Spain (AP) -- Anjelica Huston was relaxed and  
animated as she talked about two key people in her film career: her 
father, the late director John Huston, and her former lover, actor 
Jack Nicholson. 
</P>
<P>
	The actress was here Friday to receive the San Sebastian Film  
Festival's Donostia award for her contribution to film. She shares 
the prize with Vanessa Redgrave and Spanish actor and director 
Fernando Fernan Gomez-Gomez. 
</P>
<P>
	Huston said she learned the most from her father.  
</P>
<P>
	``For the first twelve years of my life I lived in Ireland and I  
was raised exclusively on his films. Obviously he was my first 
teacher,'' said Huston. 
</P>
<P>
	She won an Oscar for best supporting actress for her role in  
``Prizzi's Honor,'' which also starred Nicholson. Huston and 
Nicholson had broken up by the time they starred together in 1995's 
``The Crossing Guard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In my mind the relationship was unresolved because of outside  
elements, but after doing that film with Jack I felt that noone 
else could have done that film, I don't regret it,'' Huston said. 
  	   	
</P>
