<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tired Teen-Agers Need More Sleep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Your teen-ager insists she cannot fall asleep  
until after midnight. Every morning means yelling to wake her up in 
time to be at school by 7:15 a.m. She loves history class, but it 
is first period and many days she snoozes through it. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the daily grind for millions of students and their  
parents. If it is any comfort, scientists say it is not the 
teen-ager's fault: Biology is behind adolescents' sleep problems, 
and earlier bells at the nation's high schools are turning many 
students into zombies. 
</P>
<P>
	You cannot just order a sleepy teen-ager to bed earlier and  
expect the problem solved. 
</P>
<P>
	Sophisticated studies of teen-agers' sleep patterns show  
adolescents need more slumber -- 9 hours and 15 minutes -- than the 
eight hours recommended for adults. 
</P>
<P>
	But sometime in late puberty, the body secretes the  
sleep-related hormone melatonin at a different time than normal -- 
changing the ``circadian rhythms'' that guide people's sleep-wake 
cycles. So even if you somehow get your teen-ager to turn out the 
lights at 10 p.m., he may just stare at the ceiling until 1 a.m. 
waiting to doze off. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider, too, that many high schools have pushed up the  
starting bell as early as 7:15 a.m., and the average American 
teen-ager gets 6.5 hours of sleep on a school night, some lots 
less. 
</P>
<P>
	Those missing hours of slumber each night add up, depriving  
teen-agers of the benefits that Shakespeare described as knitting 
up ``the ravell'd sleeve of care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sleep deprivation cripples memory and inhibits creativity,  
meaning tired students do not learn much. 
</P>
<P>
	The teen-age years are a struggle to learn to deal with stress  
and control emotion -- irritability, lack of self-confidence and 
mood swings often are common, but sleep deprivation worsens it all. 
</P>
<P>
	There also is evidence that enough sleep is important for a  
robust immune system. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse, many bleary-eyed students are driving to school in the  
morning, and at other times when their body is yearning for a nap. 
Scientists do not know how many car crashes involving teen-age 
drivers are sleep-related, but say it clearly is a safety risk that 
needs serious investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Parents, educators don't understand this,'' complains famed  
sleep researcher Dr. William Dement of Stanford University, who 
helped discover the vital ``rapid eye movement'' or REM stage of 
deep sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	``What can we do about it?'' he asked sleep experts gathered by  
the prestigious National Academy of Sciences this week to determine 
how to educate Americans about the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Conventional wisdom is that your body adjusts to less sleep.  
</P>
<P>
	Not so, insists Dr. Mary Carskadon of Brown University, who  
intensively has studied adolescent sleep. ``Your brain doesn't get 
used to it,'' she warns. 
</P>
<P>
	Carskadon put monitors on sleep-deprived teen-agers. Twelve out  
of 25 could fall into REM sleep in a startling 3 to 4 minutes, far 
faster than a healthy adult can sleep so deeply. In fact, a doctor 
glancing at those test results would assume those 12 teens were 
narcoleptics, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But their ability to nap snapped off around 7:30 p.m., when  
teen-agers' unusual circadian rhythm kicked in to make them fully 
alert. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to such science, some Minnesota schools have moved  
back start times from 7:20 a.m. to 8:30 a.m. It is too early for 
proof, but researchers are reporting better grades and fewer 
discipline problems. 
</P>
<P>
	But changing schools is difficult. Aside from cutting into  
teen-agers' time for after-school jobs or sports practice, most 
school systems use the same buses for elementary through high 
school, letting the littlest kids go in later. Opening high schools 
later means more buses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not in any way, shape or form inexpensive,'' said Mona  
Signer of the Montgomery County, Md., school board, which last year 
said the $1.7 million tab made opening high schools later too 
pricey. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Zoe Lofgren, D-Calif., has introduced legislation that  
would give small grants to school systems that make the change, but 
acknowledges it has no chance of passing Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Academy of Sciences plans to help parents and  
schools learn more by distributing free fact sheets with all the 
proven science regarding adolescent sleep needs early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the National Sleep Foundation offers advice:  
</P>
<P>
	--Stay away from caffeine and nicotine, both stimulants, after  
noon. Also avoid alcohol, which can disrupt sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	--Heavy studying or computer games before bed are arousing, as is  
trying to sleep with a computer or TV flickering in the room. 
</P>
<P>
	--Avoid bright light in the evening, but open blinds or turn on  
lights as soon the morning alarm sounds to jumpstart the body's 
awakening cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sleeping more than two or three hours later than on weekends  
than weekdays can disrupt your body clock even more, making Monday 
morning harder. 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical  
issues for The Associated Press in Washington. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 23:20:09 </DATE_TIME>
