<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Gov. Edwards Faces More Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Gov. Edwin Edwards is facing more  
federal charges, this time stemming from his role in the settlement 
of a failed insurance company. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards was charged Friday with fraud and conspiracy for  
allegedly charging a $100,000 fee to set up a meeting between the 
owner of Cascade Insurance Co. and its court-appointed overseers. 
Authorities say the payment came after he was out of office. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards already faces a Jan. 10 federal racketeering trial with  
six others. In that investigation, the defendants are accused of 
manipulating the state's riverboat licensing procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	Five others also were indicted Friday, including a state judge  
and state Insurance Commissioner Jim Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI wiretaps of Edwards' telephone calls apparently picked up  
conversations between Edwards and Cascade owner David Disiere, also 
indicted Friday. Cascade failed in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards, who did not return telephone calls Friday, has said he  
merely acted as an attorney when he set up meetings between Disiere 
and the court-appointed overseer. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, elected in 1991 as a reformer, is the third-straight  
insurance commissioner to be indicted on federal charges for his 
dealings while in office. The previous two went to prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown said Friday he is innocent and that he did not have the  
authority to be involved in the Cascade settlement. He also claimed 
prosecutors purposely handed down the indictments just before the 
Oct. 23 primary and that a gag order that prohibits him from 
discussing the case will not allow him to tell his side of the 
story to the voters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prosecutors have chosen to bring this indictment just a  
few weeks before the election, knowing full well that I would not 
have time to defend or exonerate myself before election day,'' 
Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Eddie Jordan said the timing was driven by the  
evidence in the case, and was not politically motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	If convicted on all charges, Brown could be sentenced to 290  
years in prison and fined nearly $14 million while Edwards and the 
others could get up to 230 years in prison and nearly $12 million 
in fines. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
