<DOCNO> APW19990924.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 10:28:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Runners Embark on 152-Mile Marathon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Following the footsteps of an ancient  
Greek messenger, 190 runners set out from the foot of the Acropolis 
at dawn Friday on a punishing 152-mile journey from Athens to 
Sparta, nearly six times the distance of a marathon. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletes from 27 countries, many with bottles of water strapped  
to their back, will run along old highways, dirt tracks and up 
steep mountain passes, hoping to arrive at their destination by 
nightfall Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wim Epskamp, 45-year-old Dutchman, was leading the race at  
Corinth, 52 miles west of Athens, after two-time winner Costas 
Repos of Greece dropped out with stomach cramps. Japan's Kimie 
Funada was leading a dozen women, ahead of American favorite Ann 
Trason. 
</P>
<P>
	The race, known as the Spartathlon, traces the legendary course  
run by the messenger Pheidippides nearly 2,500 years ago to enlist 
the help Sparta's warrior kingdom which had allied with rival 
Athens against a Persian invasion. The run was recorded by the 
ancient historian Herodotus. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartathlon has been held every year since 1982, when five  
officers from Britain's Royal Air Force put history to the test, 
running along the route described by the historian. 
</P>
<P>
	About half the field usually quit because of blisters or  
exhaustion. For those who finish, the prize is decidedly Spartan: a 
drink of local water and an olive wreath placed on their head. 
</P>
<P>
	``This race is not about speed. It's endurance and  
determination,'' said John Foden, who led the British team in 1982 
and is a spectator this year. ``The most difficult part is the 
climb up the mountains in the dark over rough track. Sometimes it 
can be very cold.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spartathlon record, 20 hours and 25 minutes, was set by  
Yiannis Kouros of Greece in 1984, and is three hours faster than 
any other athlete has completed the race. Kouros broke a long 
string ultra-distance records in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	A campaign is being pushed to have the Spartathlon staged as an  
exhibition event before the start of the 2004 Olympic Games in 
Athens. 
</P>
<P>
	Pheidippides' run to Sparta may have been unnecessary. The  
advancing forces from the vast Persian Empire were defeated at the 
Battle of Marathon in 490 B.C., before the Spartans arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	But not all his efforts were in vain. According to Greek legend,  
Pheidippides fought with other Athenian soldiers against the 
Persians and ran from the battleground to Athens to announce ``we 
have won'' -- before dropping dead with exhaustion. 
</P>
<P>
	His last 26 miles inspired another race, the marathon.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 12:30:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AL Umpire Suspended Three Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Shulock became the second umpire to be  
disciplined this season when he was suspended by the American 
League today for three games for his ``display of temper'' in a 
game this week. 
</P>
<P>
	AL president Gene Budig, in his first major decision since being  
told his position was being terminated by commissioner Bud Selig, 
suspended Shulock for the final three games his crew is to work 
this season and fined him an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The penalties were levied, Budig said, for Shulock's ``overly  
aggressive behavior, display of temper, inappropriate remarks and 
physical contact'' with Tampa Bay catcher Mike DeFelice during and 
following the Devils Rays' game against the Anaheim Angels on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock apparently became upset with DeFelice during the third  
inning of the Angels' 10-5 victory, a game in which the Devil Rays 
complained about the umpire's ball and strike calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble began when Devils Rays pitcher Wilson Alvarez threw  
a fastball that struck Shulock in the mask. DeFelice barely raised 
his mitt to catch the pitch, and the ball squarely struck Shulock. 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock, unhurt, straightened up and slowly headed toward the  
mound. DeFelice caught up with the umpire as Tampa Bay manager 
Larry Rothschild came out of the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock and Alvarez argued briefly, but the umpire did not eject  
the pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	After the game, Shulock said, ``The more I think about it, I  
think he (Alvarez) did it intentionally. I can't prove it, but I'm 
upset, and I have a right to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the season, National League umpire Tom Hallion was  
suspended for three games without pay for allegedly bumping 
Colorado catcher Jeff Reed and pitching coach Milt May. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Tata, working the game with Hallion, denied Hallion had  
made contact with Reed and May. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball officials couldn't recall another suspension of an  
umpire for an on-field dispute. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
