<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Jailed Correspondent Gets Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Endre Marton now has a complete record of the  
interrogation he withstood more than four decades ago in a 
Hungarian prison. 
</P>
<P>
	His country was under Communist rule, and Marton, a  
correspondent for The Associated Press in Budapest, and his wife, 
Ilona, who worked for United Press, were jailed for 15 months on 
charges of espionage. 
</P>
<P>
	She was placed in a separate cell. They managed to communicate  
through coded tappings on the bars. 
</P>
<P>
	Marton was freed in time to cover the Hungarian revolution in  
1956, an abortive attempt to throw off Soviet control, and they 
left for the United States soon afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday night, the Hungarian foreign minister, Janos  
Martonyi, presented Marton, 88, with Hungary's Officers Cross of 
the Order of Merit and paid tribute to the couple's ``tenacious 
courage when they were fighting for freedom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the award, which was received by Kati Marton, their  
daughter, was a thick envelope containing a transcript of Marton's 
interrogation. 
</P>
<P>
	The minister paid tribute to the Martons for their ``tenacious  
courage when they were fighting for freedom.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremonial dinner was hosted by Kati Marton's husband,  
Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations. 
The Martons did not attend, Kati Marton explaining that her mother 
was not well and that her father would not leave her in alone in 
their home in Bethesda, Md., to come to New York for the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	Marton wrote of his experience in a memoir, ``The Forbidden  
Sky.'' Until his retirement in 1975, he worked as a reporter for 
The Associated Press at the State Department. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
