<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Detroit Teachers Get New Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Detroit teachers who went on strike earlier this  
month voted Friday to ratify a three-year contract, a union 
representative said. 
</P>
<P>
	Union members voted 6,328 to 2,058 to accept the contract, which  
gives all teachers a 2 percent raise each year for the next three 
years. Teachers with more seniority and education will receive 
higher raises to keep up with wages in suburban districts. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm satisfied. I'm encouraged by the vote and the margin of  
the yes and no,'' union President John Elliott said. ``Quite 
frankly, the members voted in their best interests.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott said nearly 11,000 of the Detroit Federation of  
Teachers' 11,500 members were eligible to vote. Teachers secretly 
voted at their work locations. 
</P>
<P>
	Students in Detroit missed the first six days of school after  
union members voted against a 10-day contract extension while 
negotiations continued. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Conn, a Cass Technical High School math teacher who was  
one of the most vocal teachers during the strike, said teachers 
approved the contract by such a large margin because of the way the 
ballot was worded. 
</P>
<P>
	The ballot asked teachers to either accept the agreement or  
reject the contract and ``withhold'' services starting Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's flat out untrue that we would be on strike. There's  
nothing that requires that we walk out on Monday,'' Conn said. ``I 
think if it was a fair yes-no vote, it would have been much 
closer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conn had said before the tentative settlement was announced  
earlier this month that teachers would vote down any contract 
offer. In fact, he urged teachers to reject the settlement before 
details of the contract were announced. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott said the union used the same ballot language it has used  
since the 1970s. He denied that the language was aimed at ensuring 
the contract would be approved. He did say, however, that the 
language probably should be changed for future votes. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 30, the day before classes were to begin, teachers  
rejected their union's proposal for a 10-day contract extension. 
Nine days later, teachers voted overwhelmingly to return to work, 
ending an extended summer vacation for 180,000 students. They also 
approved a temporary extension of their old contract until the 
union could hold a vote on the new deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The teachers had walked off the job because they were not happy  
about proposals for a longer school day, merit pay, and other 
proposals made by the new school reform board. 
</P>
<P>
	The new contract includes a plan to reduce class size in  
kindergarten through third grade. The deal also includes more 
restrictions on unexcused absences of teachers, which was a board 
priority. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
