<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 14:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Brings Back Jailhouse Stripes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW BEDFORD, Mass. (AP) -- A sheriff who has reintroduced chain  
gangs has also brought back old-fashioned black-and-white striped 
prison garb for teen-age inmates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason I chose that type of uniform is that kids today  
have a strong affinity with the clothes they wear and associate 
that with who they are,'' said Bristol County Sheriff Thomas 
Hodgson. ``If they make bad choices, they need to know they will 
lose that privilege.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dress code was implemented in July at a juvenile detention  
center in southeastern Massachusetts. So far, reaction among the 
young detainees has been exactly as Hodgson hoped. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't like them,'' he said. ``They're not a fashion  
statement in their world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some critics disagree with the sheriff's tactic.  
</P>
<P>
	``The striped uniforms are considered a joke in society, like  
Halloween costumes you can buy in a store,'' said attorney Greta 
Janusz, who specializes in prison litigation. ``Kids have a chance 
to be rehabilitated, and we should be concerned with their 
self-esteem. It's esteem problems that often lead to the crime 
itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hodgson, who was elected in November, gained notoriety earlier  
this year when he began offering crews of shackled prison inmates 
for community service projects. He also took away cigarettes, 
televisions and weight-lifting equipment privileges from some 
inmates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
