<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Students Protest  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- The Indonesian government's suspension  
Friday of a new law giving the armed forces expanded emergency 
powers did not immediately quell running battles in Jakarta between 
student-led protesters and riot police backed by marines. The 
policy reversal -- one day after it was passed -- will further erode 
the prestige of President B.J. Habibie, who is running for 
re-election. During much of the day, demonstrators blocked the 
capital's main thoroughfare pelting police with stones and gasoline 
bombs. The national currency, the rupiah, continued to slide on 
fears of political instability and ended six percent lower than 
last week. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush to Buchanan: Stay With GOP  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- GOP presidential front-runner George W. Bush  
today urged Pat Buchanan to remain a Republican and not bolt to a 
Reform Party presidential bid. Discussing a range of foreign policy 
issues in an interview with The Associated Press, Bush said he had 
the will to force United Nations weapons inspectors back into Iraq, 
and he sided with supporters of the troubled F-22 stealth fighter. 
On Buchanan, Bush said he disagreed with the conservative 
commentator's view that Nazi Germany wasn't a threat to the United 
States after 1940. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Strikes Chechnya by Air  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian airstrikes around Chechnya's  
capital Friday sent thousands fleeing as the intensifying campaign 
heightened fears of another war in the breakaway republic. The 
bombings, which killed five people, followed attacks Thursday in 
which Russian planes pounded targets in and near Grozny in the 
first major raid on the city since a 1994-96 war between federal 
forces and Chechen separatists. The Russian government says it is 
trying to destroy Islamic militants based in Chechnya who twice 
invaded the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan since early 
August. 

</P>
<P>
	Kinkel Pleads Guilty to Murder  
</P>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Kip Kinkel, the 17-year-old teen-ager who  
killed his parents and gunned down two classmates at school, 
abandoned his insanity defense today and pleaded guilty to four 
counts of murder and 26 counts of attempted murder. Kinkel could 
get as little as 25 years in jail, meaning he could be free by age 
42. 

</P>
<P>
	Anti-Milosevic Protests Grow Slowly  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Demonstrations against Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic drew about 30,000 people in Belgrade 
on Friday, the biggest crowd so far in the latest round of 
protests. Milosevic's opponents hope to channel popular discontent 
with his autocratic rule into large demonstrations, like those that 
temporarily weakened his grip in late 1996 and early 1997. Some of 
those protests mobilized more than 100,000 people. One opposition 
leader, Democratic Party president Zoran Djindjic, said it was too 
early to conclude that the protests have failed. But, Djindjic 
said, ``if Milosevic is not shaken by November, we will have to 
concede that we didn't succeed.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Financier May Need Public Defender  
</P>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Authorities say rogue financier Martin  
Frankel masterminded one of the largest insurance scams in U.S. 
history, but now he doesn't even have enough money to pay his legal 
bills, according to his lawyer. New Haven defense attorney Hugh 
Keefe said he will withdraw as Frankel's lawyer because federal 
officials have frozen all of Frankel's assets and rejected requests 
to release a portion of the funds. 

</P>
<P>
	Arafat Woos U.S. Business  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Standing before 100 business representatives  
at a U.S. Chamber of Commerce luncheon, Palestinian leader Yasser 
Arafat today touted opportunities in the West Bank and Gaza and 
assured investors they need not worry about terrorist attacks on 
their property. The audience received Arafat warmly, but reminded 
him how easily the Arab-Israeli dispute can affect business 
interests. A month ago, Burger King decided to close down a 
franchise in a Jewish settlement in the West Bank after 
Arab-Americans threatened to boycott the restaurant chain. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 39.26; Nasdaq Falls 9.42  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rounded out a dismal week with a volatile  
session but generally modest losses today. The Dow Jones industrial 
average, down a total of more than 505 points over the previous 
three sessions, lost another 39.26 and closed at 10,279.33. 
Decliners on the New York Stock Exchange lead advancers 
1,824-1,172. The Nasdaq was down 9.42 at 2,740.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Runners Embark on 152-Mile Marathon  
</P>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Following the footsteps of an ancient  
Greek messenger, 190 runners set out from the foot of the Acropolis 
at dawn today on a punishing 152-mile journey from Athens to 
Sparta, nearly six times the distance of a marathon. A campaign is 
being pushed to have the Spartathlon staged as an exhibition event 
before the start of the 2004 Olympic Games in Athens. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
