<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken Has Season of Ups and Downs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cal Ripken proved this season he can still hit  
for average and with power. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iron Man also showed he is a mere mortal, burdened by a back  
injury that required surgery and the emotional blow of his father's 
death. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken's most trying season came to a sudden, early end  
Thursday. The 39-year-old third baseman closed the year just nine 
hits short of 3,000 for his career, a milestone he should reach in 
April if his rehabilitation proceeds as expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can carve this in granite: If anyone can come back from a  
back operation without losing a step, it's Cal Ripken,'' Dr. Bill 
Howard, director of sports medicine at Baltimore's Union Memorial 
Hospital, said Thursday. ``He's got the strength, the conditioning 
and the mindset to make it happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, it was hard to imagine Ripken missing a game, let  
alone a week. Or a month. The most durable player in the history of 
the sport played 2,632 consecutive games before voluntarily ending 
the run in the Orioles' final home date of the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	This year was decidedly different. Ripken twice spent time on  
the disabled list for the first time since his career began in 
1981. He missed three weeks with lower back pain beginning April 20 
and sat out the entire month of August after the back spasms 
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	He finally decided this week surgery was the only option, and he  
had an operation Thursday in Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	The surgery completed a season that began with the loss of his  
father, Cal Sr., who died of lung cancer in March. The emotional 
and physical pain diminished a year in which he hit his 400th 
career homer and compiled a .340 average, 64 points above the .276 
lifetime mark he carried into the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to meet a lot of professional and personal challenges,''  
Ripken said last week. ``When you look back, will it be a season to 
remember? I guess in some ways it would be, but for the most part, 
it represents something of a loss as well as something of a gain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The gain? Ripken found a batting stance that let him either pull  
the ball or drive it to the opposite field. He got a career-high 
six hits in one game and his 18 homers were more than he had in 
four of his previous five seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ironically, in my opinion, his back forced him to have a  
conservative stance for the first time in years,'' teammate Mike 
Mussina said. 
</P>
<P>
	An interesting theory, Ripken says.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think when I first started coming back and swinging the bat  
I was tentative because I didn't know what effect there was on the 
back. I started to get a pretty good feel in the batting cage and I 
developed it from there, so maybe you could say the back injury did 
have something to do with it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The back injury had everything to do with the fact that he  
played in only 86 games, a far cry from his steady 162. 
</P>
<P>
	And even when he was on the field, he couldn't shake the  
memories of his father, a former coach and manager with the Orioles 
who was by far the most notable influence in Ripken's stellar 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``The injuries that I've never had to deal with professionally  
and the loss of my father personally -- that affects everything I 
do, my focus, the ability to concentrate,'' Ripken said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all go through different issues and it all impacts on your  
work or your ability to function in life. I just happened to get a 
double dose of them at the same time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Personally and professionally, it was a hard dose of reality for  
a seemingly invulnerable sports hero. 
</P>
<P>
	``You live and learn,'' he said, ``and you deal with it as best  
you can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He dealt with it well in 1999.  
</P>
<P>
	``Cal certainly has been through a lot this year,'' Orioles  
shortstop Mike Bordick said. ``And then to have the season he's 
having ... well, what else can you call it but Ripkenesque?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
