<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator's Aide Makes Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- The former chief of staff for Sen. Max  
Baucus lodged a sexual harassment complaint against him Friday, 
claiming the Democrat made advances toward her and tried to coerce 
her into dropping her accusations. 
</P>
<P>
	In seeking redress through a congressional employee grievance  
process, Christine Niedermeier said Baucus promised her two months 
of severance pay if she backed off. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement issued Thursday, Baucus reiterated his denial  
that he sexually harassed Niedermeier, and repeated that he fired 
her last month because she had abused his staff and constituents 
with her harsh management style. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look forward to moving this matter to a forum where I will  
be fully vindicated,'' he said. He would not agree to an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Niedermeier, 47 and single, has claimed Baucus, 57 and married,  
made sexual advances from the time she joined his staff in May 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	She made her complaint to the Office of Compliance, a  
legislative agency created in 1995 after the sexual harassment 
scandal of former Sen. Bob Packwood of Oregon. The system first 
turns to counseling and mediation, and if unsuccessful moves to a 
private hearing before a federal judge, or to federal civil courts. 
</P>
<P>
	In her complaint, she said Baucus ``on many occasions engaged in  
conduct in the office that can best be termed abusive, 
temperamental and inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus constantly questioned her about her personal life and  
dating habits, suggested they go away for a weekend together and 
indicated he wanted more than an employer-employee relationship, 
she wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``On many occasions, I let him know that his actions made me  
feel uncomfortable and was unwanted,'' she wrote. ``On some 
occasions I directly asked him to stop.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said he fired her shortly after one such confrontation July  
31. 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus' lawyer, Jean Manning, called Niedermeier's charge a  
fabrication. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is exactly where we wanted the case -- in a forum where  
she has to testify under oath and we'll deal with facts before a 
judge now,'' Manning said. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint accuses Baucus of harassment, gender  
discrimination and retaliation. She wants past and future lost 
wages and benefits, and punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she may also take legal action for breach of contract,  
defamation, extortion and theft. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
