<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ray Is the Hunter at Vegas.com 500 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Greg Ray is used to being the hunted, not the  
hunter. But the Indy Racing League points leader found himself 
chasing Sam Schmidt in Friday's practice for the Vegas.com 500. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt was the fastest driver in both the sessions at the Las  
Vegas Motor Speedway. In his Sprint PCS car with a G Force chassis, 
the Las Vegas resident turned a fast lap of 208.849 mph in the 
morning and went 207.876 mph later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely great to be on the top of the pole, but really  
all that matters is Sunday,'' said Schmidt, who finished a 
career-best second here last year. ``At the same time, if you can 
practice your race setup and be at the front of the pack, it just 
tells you everything is working.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray, winner of three of the last four IRL events, including the  
last two, had the day's second-best speed at 208.631 mph in the 
morning session. He struggled in the afternoon, going 206.889 mph 
in his Glidden-Menards with a Dallara chassis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wasn't confident in the car,'' he said. ``A lot of  
times I drive the car hard when it's not perfect. I don't feel like 
doing that this weekend. I would rather the car be perfect if I'm 
going to commit to it like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ray leads the IRL points standings with 246, 44 ahead of Scott  
Goodyear and 47 ahead of Kenny Brack. Ray needs to increase his 
lead to 56 points or more after Sunday's race to clinch his first 
IRL championship and a $1 million bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray could tie an IRL record for consecutive victories set last  
year by Brack with a victory Sunday. His fourth win of the season 
would be an IRL record. 
</P>
<P>
	Brack went slightly faster in the afternoon (205.950 mph) than  
the morning (205.097) as he adjusts from a Dallara to a G Force 
chassis in his A.J. Foyt-owned car. Foyt made the decision to 
switch after testing the G Force in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very smooth and predictable right now,'' he said. ``We  
haven't raced it yet, so we don't know for sure, but it's very 
consistent and stable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The track temperature rose from 104 degrees in the morning to  
129 degrees by the afternoon. Handling on the 1.5-mile oval can be 
tricky, with the heat and wind often combining for slippery 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmidt, who has four top-10 finishes in his last five races,  
noticed a difference in practice sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fortunately, we were pretty close in both situations,'' he  
said. ``I don't think the heat affected it as much as the increase 
in wind. There really wasn't a whole lot of wind in the morning, 
very minimal. Then we started getting some in our (afternoon) 
session.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephan Gregoire had the day's third-quickest practice speed of  
207.333. Mark Dismore went 206.572 mph and Buddy Lazier was fifth 
at 206.256 mph. Lazier increased his speed from 204.043 mph in the 
morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel good to have made such a gain,'' Lazier said. ``This  
racetrack is very challenging from a grip point of view. It has to 
do with the atmosphere here in the desert and the banking of the 
track. It's like driving 200 mph on snow and ice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Ray's lead, Schmidt and 10 others aren't exactly out of  
the points race. From Goodyear in second to Schmidt in 12th, 11 
drivers are separated by just 30 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodyear has slumped recently, finishing out of the top 10 in  
his last four races. His last victory was in the Longhorn 500 on 
June 12 at Texas Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to stick to our plan, which is to just go out and  
win, and that's our only focus right now,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
