<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Ends Controversial Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Indonesia's government caved in to  
massive public protests today and suspended the implementation of a 
controversial law that would have given the military power to curb 
civil liberties. 
</P>
<P>
	The passage of the law by Indonesia's outgoing parliament on  
Thursday sparked protests across Indonesia. In Jakarta, four people 
were reported killed and 115 injured in violence between 
demonstrators and heavily armed riot police. 
</P>
<P>
	``Half of people do not understand the contents of the bill,''  
military spokesman Maj. Gen. Sudrajat said in announcing the 
Cabinet decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of that, the government has decided to suspend the  
security law,'' said Sudrajat, who like many Indonesians uses only 
one name. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the announcement, violent protests had gripped Jakarta  
for a second day as riot police firing rubber bullets struggled to 
contain crowds of demonstrators. 
</P>
<P>
	An official from Jakarta's Ciptomangunkusumo Hospital said the  
bodies of three protesters had been brought in since late Thursday. 
All had been shot by plastic bullets or live rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	A police officer died in a traffic accident, authorities said.  
</P>
<P>
	About 500 riot police stormed the Atma Jaya Catholic University  
before dawn, firing volleys of tear gas and rubber bullets at 
students who had taken over the campus. 
</P>
<P>
	By early afternoon, the clashes were moving slowly down  
Jakarta's main boulevard, Sudirman Avenue, toward the center of the 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	Many feared the controversial new law could allow the armed  
forces to use the crisis in the territory of East Timor and other 
outbreaks of unrest to gradually seize control of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking on national television today, Sudrajat said the  
legislation was more democratic than the existing law. 
</P>
<P>
	However, ``it will not be implemented until it is clear that the  
people understand the contents and the purpose of this bill,'' 
Sudrajat said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shops and banks in the area of the university closed early and  
sent their employees home at lunch time because of the violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the campus, police smashed the windows of buildings and  
cars and arrested five students. Overall, 42 people were arrested. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are not police, they are pirates and murderers,'' said  
business student Alex Leonardo, 25. 
</P>
<P>
	The university was the focus of massive pro-democracy protests  
last year that led to the ouster of then-President Suharto, the 
military strongman who ruled the country for 32 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Indonesians believe the armed forces, which underpinned  
Suharto's dictatorship, are trying to reassert their political 
clout in the wake of the country's first free elections in four 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	``The military will take advantage of the new bill, that is for  
sure,'' said Amien Rais, a prominent Muslim politician and a member 
of the new parliament that is to be sworn in on Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``The role of the armed forces will be increased and the  
democratic process could be blocked,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The protests swept the nation Thursday after the outgoing  
assembly, dominated by Suharto loyalists, rubber-stamped the 
hastily introduced measure allowing the military to revoke civil 
liberties in ``emergency situations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In today's protests, youths from Jakarta's working class  
districts joined the fray. Several hundred protesters continued to 
taunt police who fired volley after volley of rubber bullets and 
tear gas to keep them at bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The clashes closed the main thoroughfare during morning rush  
hour today, forcing tens of thousands of people to walk to work. 
Many of the commuters were coughing and holding handkerchiefs to 
their faces as they walked through clouds of tear gas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
