<HEADLINE> Gov't Sees No Threat in Copper Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Phelps Dodge has yet to persuade Cyprus Amax  
Minerals Co. and Asarco Inc. to accept its hostile takeover bid, 
but the Justice Department sees no threat to competition if the 
three copper makers become one. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal agency's antitrust division agreed to cut short the  
waiting period during which the government could challenge or 
subject the deal to further review, spokeswoman Jennifer Rose said 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision amounts to a tacit approval of the proposed deal,  
which would merge three of the nation's four largest copper 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Phelps Dodge sweetened its offer to buy the two  
companies, which have already spurned two bids and agreed to push 
ahead their own merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Stockholders for Cyprus Amax, based in Englewood, Colo., and  
Asarco, based in New York, are scheduled to vote on their two-way 
deal on Sept. 30. 



  	   	
