<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Boss Gets His Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Juergen Schrempp caused a lot of queasiness in  
Germany when he took over as chairman of Daimler-Benz in 1995, 
announcing harsh U.S.-style cuts to restore Germany's biggest 
industrial concern to profitability after a year of record losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Now at the top of an even bigger DaimlerChrysler, Schrempp is  
shaking things up again. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's announced departure of Chrysler division president  
Thomas Stallkamp -- an outspoken American and Schrempp critic who 
was considered a possible successor for the top job -- was 
interpreted as a move toward consolidation of power on the German 
side of the Atlantic. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the first time Schrempp, 55, described as both  
charismatic and ruthless, has been seen as edging out rivals with 
differing views. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, then-Mercedes-Benz chairman Helmut Werner resigned  
rather than see his power eroded in Schrempp's plan to merge the 
luxury car and truck manufacturer back into its parent company, 
Daimler-Benz. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan gave Schrempp, who beat out Werner to take over Daimler  
in 1995, more direct control over Mercedes. Werner -- whom Business 
Week included on its 1996 list of the 25 most successful top 
managers -- had opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	Following last year's merger, seven top Chrysler executives  
jumped ship, provoking reports of a culture clash at the 
trans-Atlantic automaker. Schrempp has bristled at hints of 
problems, though. 
</P>
<P>
	``What is the big deal of seven people ... having left? ... No  
deal whatsoever, happens all the time and will continue to 
happen,'' he told reporters in a conference call in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrempp, who began his career more than 30 years ago as a  
mechanic trainee for Mercedes cars, has worked overseas himself, 
including 11 years in South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1982-84 he headed Cleveland-based Euclid, Inc., a Daimler  
subsidiary that produced heavy-duty trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	He was chairman of the board of Daimler-Benz's aerospace  
division when he was tapped to take over the whole company in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Reversing years of untethered expansion under his predecessor,  
Schrempp began slashing away at money-losing divisions that had 
contributed to a record loss of $3.2 billion in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the first German converts to the U.S. philosophy of  
stressing shareholder value, he trimmed the work force by some 10 
percent, ignoring union protests. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Schrempp showed little respect for German traditions of  
labor-management consensus when he made Daimler the first company 
to apply a new law allowing a cut in sick pay. He retreated when 
angry workers walked off their jobs, but his overall efforts 
restored the company to profitability that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Long viewed with suspicion by play-it-safe German business  
circles, the turnaround earned Schrempp respect -- which only grew 
after he pulled off the Chrysler merger coup. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
