<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ovarian Implant Called Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Young women left infertile due to cancer or  
other ailments may someday have children thanks to an experimental 
ovarian tissue transplant that a doctor says restored a menopausal 
woman's menstrual cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	``This case indicates that we are on the cusp of safe, reliable  
transplantation of human ovarian tissue,'' said Larry Lipshultz, 
president of the American Society for Reproductive Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	``This should give great hope to women suffering from ovarian  
and other cancers and may lead to successful treatment for other 
causes of infertility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Kutluk Oktay performed the operation in February on Margaret  
Lloyd-Hart in the hopes of reversing symptoms of menopause brought 
on by the removal of her ovaries. Her first ovary was removed when 
she was 17 because of a cyst. The second was removed two years ago 
for a medical condition described only as benign. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lloyd-Hart, a 30-year-old dancer from Tucson, Ariz., had  
some ovarian tissue from the second operation preserved through 
freezing six months before the implant at New York Methodist 
Hospital. The preserved tissue contained unfertilized eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	Four months after the implant, Oktay gave Ms. Lloyd-Hart  
fertility drugs to test ovarian function. She ovulated and had a 
normal menstrual period, Oktay said. Ms. Lloyd-Hart, who is on 
hormone replacement therapy and now lives in London, won't know 
until her next examination in New York in a couple of months 
whether she is continuing to ovulate, Oktay said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of her condition, there is no way for her to know with  
certainty whether an egg is being released without an examination 
by a specialist. 
</P>
<P>
	Oktay, who will be presenting his work next week at a meeting of  
the American Society for Reproductive Medicine in Toronto, said 
Thursday the surgery gives new hope for young infertile women, 
especially women who had cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's probably the best news they can have,'' Oktay said.  
``After they hear they have cancer, there is someone telling them 
they may have hope for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and other experts say the procedure is not recommended as a  
means for women to delay child-bearing into what would normally be 
menopausal years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ian Craft of the London Fertility Centre noted that women  
already in menopause would not benefit because ``they have no eggs 
left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The American Cancer Society estimates that 25,200 women will be  
diagnosed with ovarian cancer this year. In addition to damage from 
the disease, women can suffer ovarian damage from treatments such 
as chemotherapy. If the new procedure proves successful, such women 
could potentially have their ovaries removed, be treated for cancer 
and then have the ovaries re-implanted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
