<HEADLINE> Owner of Mich. Dailies Seeks Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) -- 21st Century Newspapers Inc., the  
company that owns daily newspapers in Pontiac, Mount Clemens and 
Royal Oak, is looking for a potential merger partner or buyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Employees at The Oakland Press in Pontiac, The Macomb Daily in  
Mount Clemens and The Daily Tribune in Royal Oak were told Thursday 
that owner Frank H. Shepherd has retained Goldman, Sachs and Co. to 
help with a merger or sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Shepherd plans to retire to be with his family once the  
transaction is completed. 
</P>
<P>
	21st Century also owns weekly newspapers and the Greater Detroit  
Newspaper Network, an advertising sales group based in Royal Oak, 
Mich. Shepherd formed the company in 1995 and bought the three 
dailies in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Shepherd, who has more than 35 years experience in the  
publishing industry, mostly in Michigan. He began his career at The 
Times Herald Co. in Port Huron and eventually became general 
manager of The Daily Sentinel in Utica. 
</P>
<P>
	Shepherd joined Panax Corp. in East Lansing in 1968 and became  
chief operating officer, running seven daily newspapers. When Panax 
was sold in 1981, Shepherd bought a publishing company in Houston, 
Texas, then joined the Scripps Howard group in 1984, where he was 
vice president of newspaper operations. 
</P>
<P>
	He also served as president and CEO of Stauffer Communications  
Inc. of Topeka, Kan., until it was sold. Stauffer owned 23 dailies, 
including two in Michigan, 13 broadcast outlets and several 
magazines. 
  	   	
</P>
