<HEADLINE> A Look at Friday's Ryder Cup Play  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- A look at play Friday, the first day of  
the Ryder Cup: 
</P>
<P>
	 *Winners:* Jesper Parnevik and Sergio Garcia combined for two  
wins for the European team, which jumped to a 6-2 lead after the 
first day's matches. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Losers:* Tiger Woods and David Duval, who lost both of their  
matches. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Shot of the day:* Parnevik's iron from 141 yards on No. 8 in  
his afternoon match that went in for an eagle 2. 
</P>
<P>
	 *State of the day:* The 6-2 lead is the largest first day margin  
for the Europeans since 1987, the year they first won the cup on 
American soil. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Needed:* Eight more of the 20 points remaining for the  
Europeans to get what they need to defend the cup. The American 
team needs 14 1/2 points to win the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Format:* Four alternate shot matches and four best ball matches  
Saturday. Twelve 18-hole singles matches on Sunday. One point is 
awarded for each victory, a half-point when the match is a draw. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Pairings:* For Saturday alternate shot matches: Colin  
Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie, Europe, vs. Hal Sutton and Jeff 
Maggert, USA; Darren Clarke and Lee Westwood, Europe, vs. Jim Furyk 
and Mark O'Meara, USA; Miguel Angel Jimenez and Padraig Harrington, 
Europe, vs. Tiger Woods and Steve Pate, USA; Jesper Parnevik and 
Sergio Garcia, Europe, vs. Payne Stewart and Justin Leonard, USA. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Quotable:* ``It was the most enjoyable day's golf I've ever  
experienced -- better than anything before.'' -- Sergio Garcia after 
winning two points for the European team. 
</P>
<P>
	 *Television (all times EDT):* Saturday, 8 a.m. to 6 p.m. (NBC).  
Sunday, 10:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. (NBC). 
  	   	
</P>
