<HEADLINE> 17 Cuban Refugees Reach Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A wooden boat carrying 17 Cuban  
refugeess who said they were at sea for a week landed in Florida 
early Friday and asked residents to call police. 
</P>
<P>
	The 12 men, four women and an 8-year-old boy made landfall near  
Palm Beach, just southeast of West Palm Beach, at about 1 a.m., 
said Border Patrol spokesman Dan Geoghegan. 
</P>
<P>
	They reached shore in what appeared to be an old fishing boat  
powered by a diesel engine, Geoghegan said, though the group said 
the boat was homemade. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the group said they were from Camaguey, the largest  
city in central Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten of the Cubans knocked on the door of a nearby residence  
while the others watched the boat, police said. The resident then 
called police. 
</P>
<P>
	Police turned the group over to the Border Patrol, the  
enforcement arm of the Immigration and Naturalization Service. On 
Friday afternoon the refugees were being held for processing at the 
INS's Krome Detention Center outside Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Since October, 2,227 Cubans, including those picked up Friday,  
were apprehended by the Border Patrol after reaching Florida's 
shores. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
