<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whole Foods To Spin Off Internet Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, (AP) -- Whole Foods Inc. said Thursday it will spin off  
its Internet grocery business and sell shares of the Web venture to 
the public within a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Austin-based natural foods store chain said it wants to  
build a ``healthy-living'' Web site where consumers can get 
information as well as groceries. 
</P>
<P>
	John P. Mackey, the company's founder and chief executive, will  
lead the new company, to be called WholePeople.com. The store chain 
sold a 13.5 percent stake in the new company to venture 
capitalists, whom Mackey would not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	Whole Foods' stock lost more than 9 percent in trading Friday on  
the NASDAQ stock market, down 3 15/32 to 33 3/32. 
</P>
<P>
	Whole Foods is the nation's largest natural foods chain, with  
more than 90 stores in more than 20 states and Washington, D.C. It 
stresses food free of pesticides, preservatives and sweeteners. Its 
stores include Whole Foods Market, Bread &AMP; Circus, Bread of Life, 
Fresh Fields, Merchant of Vino and Wellspring Grocery. The company 
has also moved into the coffee roasting and nutritional-supplements 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, with 14,200 employees, reported sales last year of  
nearly $1.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The new online company will include Amrion Inc., a mail-order  
vitamin-sales firm that Whole Foods bought in 1997, and American 
WholeHealth Inc., a holistic-medicine company. 
</P>
<P>
	An analyst said the spin-off indicates that selling groceries  
over the Internet, which Whole Foods started to do in March, isn't 
a profitable business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you're going to see an explosion of people  
buying broccoli over the Internet, but you will see an explosion in 
people looking for information or easier-to-ship products,'' 
Matthew Patsky of Adams Harkness in Boston told the Austin 
American-Statesman. His company helped find investors for the new 
Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Online grocery sales last year were just $148 million, according  
to Jupiter Communications, an online research company in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Whole Foods is taking a non-recurring charge of $3.5 million to  
close two Amrion divisions. The company also said it would take a 
$6 million charge this quarter for software and hardware purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	Removing Amrion and WholeFoods.com from Whole Foods' balance  
sheet takes away $1.1 billion in revenue and about $34.7 million in 
net income, the company said. That means Whole Foods' fiscal year 
2000 earnings will likely be 18 to 26 cents below analysts' 
estimates of $2.13 per share, Mackey said. 
</P>
<P>
	He predicted that Whole Foods' traditional business will grow 15  
to 20 percent next year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
