<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stations Turn to Web Broadcasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- This past summer, if you were a baseball fan in  
search of Florida Marlins' highlights, you might tune in to WPEC's 
11 p.m. newscast -- or log on to its Web site to watch a simulcast. 
</P>
<P>
	Not anymore. Major League Baseball has cried ``Foul!'' -- and  
copyright infringement -- forcing the station in West Palm Beach, 
Fla., and others around the country to stop broadcasting on the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Disputes over Internet programming rights, though still rare,  
are on the rise as more radio and TV stations run their 
over-the-air feeds on the Web as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is technology is always way ahead of the law,''  
said Kathleen Kirby, a lawyer for the Radio-Television News 
Directors Association, a Washington-based industry group. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet broadcasts generally mirror those sent over the  
airwaves, so some stations do not see the need for additional 
rights. But distributors of sports and entertainment programming 
say their contracts spell out permitted uses and automatically 
prohibit everything else. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball contracts go a step further and include a clause that  
specifically bans Internet broadcasts, even Internet broadcasts of 
highlights. The baseball league found several violators, and 
lawyers stopped the Web broadcasts. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's starting to come up this season,'' said Michael Mellis,  
new media counsel for Major League Baseball Enterprises, the 
licensing division. ``Our game footage is copyrighted, and our 
intellectual property is valuable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	WPEC, which started Web simulcasts of local news shows on June  
21, has since eliminated its entire sports segment from the Web 
version. The station also disabled the Internet archives of past 
news shows because they contain baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, it's no different than re-broadcasting your news on  
cable,'' said Doreen Wade, WPEC's general manager. ``I don't see 
what the big deal is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A sister station, WWMT in Kalamazoo, Mich., initially stopped  
running baseball highlights on its over-the-air newscasts after 
learning of the Internet restriction. The station has since 
restored baseball to regular broadcast but keeps footage off the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really surprised that it became an issue because it's not  
a revenue-driven thing at all here,'' said Al Forist, the station's 
operations manager. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Web service costs more money than it generates, so  
WWMT does not want to pay for separate rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Football League currently permits Web simulcasts of  
highlights for one-time usage but prohibits video broadcasts of 
entire games on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro basketball officials found a few radio stations that carried  
live feeds of games over the Internet but the stations stopped 
after they were contacted by the National Basketball Association. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Adam Silver, president of NBA Entertainment, said given  
the scope of the Internet, ``it's so difficult to police.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Restrictions extend to non-sports programming as well.  
</P>
<P>
	Premiere Radio Networks, a syndicator of radio programming,  
allows Web simulcasts for some shows, but not for lucrative 
holdings such as Rush Limbaugh and Dr. Laura Schlessinger. Premiere 
worked out a licensing agreement with broadcast.com, a site through 
which stations offer simulcasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Radio feeds through broadcast.com began in 1995. The site now  
has programming from 500 radio and 65 TV stations. Yahoo! Inc., 
which runs the site, expects continued growth as better technology 
makes quality feeds possible. 
</P>
<P>
	The company routinely checks with stations to make sure they  
have the proper rights. Difficulties primarily arise, Yahoo! Vice 
President Kevin Parke said, when the contract says nothing on the 
scope of the rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's a question, we try to go ahead and work with the  
rights holder,'' Parke said. ``The last thing we want to do is 
violate anyone's copyright.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Wharton, spokesman for the Washington-based National  
Association of Broadcasters, said broadcasters are sorting through 
the legal ramifications. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a brave new world we're entering.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
