<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Keep Raising 'Soft Money' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Democratic Party has nearly doubled its  
``soft money'' fund raising this year even as party leaders push 
for a ban on these big donations from unions, corporations and 
individuals. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic committees took in $26.4 million in unlimited soft  
money contributions in the first half of this year, up from $13.7 
million during the last comparable period, the first six months of 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think it shows the hypocrisy,'' said Marit Babin, a  
spokeswoman for the National Republican Congressional Committee. 
``They think it's a good campaign issue, yet they haven't turned 
down any checks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans raised even more soft money -- $30.9 million during  
the first six months of the year, a 42 percent increase over 1997, 
when they raised $21.7 million. Most congressional Republicans 
oppose the soft money ban, however. 
</P>
<P>
	At a closed-door meeting of the House GOP in August, Republican  
Chairman Jim Nicholson and NRCC Chairman Thomas Davis of Virginia 
argued that a ban on soft money would leave the party's candidates 
vulnerable to unlimited expenditures by labor unions and other 
groups that back Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican-controlled House approved a ban on soft money,  
nonetheless, in a 252-177 vote Sept. 14. Of 210 Democrats, 197 
voted for the measure. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats say they can't afford to give up soft money while  
the Republicans are still raking it in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we should make it illegal, but we should make it  
illegal for everyone,'' said Rep. Martin Meehan of Massachusetts, 
the lead Democratic sponsor of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Simon, executive vice president of Common Cause, a group  
advocating for campaign reform, said it doesn't bother him that the 
Democrats continue to raise soft money while calling for its 
abolition. 
</P>
<P>
	``This issue should not be played for partisan advantage by one  
side or another,'' Simon said. ``There needs to be a law banning 
soft money that applies to both parties. Voluntary limits tend not 
to work because one party or the other always feels aggrieved by 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parties can raise soft money for get-out-the-vote drives and  
other party-building activities. Since the money is not raised 
under federal rules, it cannot be used to directly help elect 
candidates. Increasingly, however, the Democrats and Republicans 
spend millions of dollars of soft money on issue advertisements 
designed to help their nominees without specifically urging a vote 
for or against a particular candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee more than  
quadrupled its soft money contributions over the first half of 1997 
-- nearly closing a historic gap with its Republican counterpart. 
The DCCC took in $9 million during the first six months of 1999, 
compared with $1.9 million during the same period two years 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Republican Congressional Committee took in $9.4  
million in soft money during the first six months of 1999, a 79 
percent increase over the same period in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	DCCC Chairman Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island said his committee  
has been making two pitches to potential donors, criticizing House 
Republican policies and arguing that the Democrats will recapture 
the majority next fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be back in the majority. Are you going to be  
with us or not?'' Kennedy said he tells prospective contributors. 
``All we need to do is get a fraction of what these people are 
giving to Republicans. They don't want the balance sheets to be so 
unbalanced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ironically, he said prospective soft money donors agree that the  
contributions should be prohibited. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people we're raising money from are just as interested in  
anyone else in not being hit up for these large checks,'' Kennedy 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also topped Democrats in raising money under federal  
contribution limits. GOP committees took in $66.4 million, compared 
with $38.1 million for the Democrats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
