<DOCNO> APW19990924.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 19:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Treasury Sec. Facing First Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence Summers, Robert Rubin's brainy  
understudy, is facing his first real tests as treasury secretary. A 
dollar weakening against the Japanese yen is roiling Wall Street 
and a widening Russian corruption scandal has Republicans looking 
for scapegoats. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, he is weathering the storms, facing down critics of the  
administration's Russia policies as the lead-off witness at 
congressional hearings and keeping the pressure on Japan to get its 
economic house in order. 
</P>
<P>
	The pudgy, boyish-looking Summers, 44, whose suits were once  
described in a New Yorker magazine profile as looking like they had 
``spent the day wrapped around a mating seal,'' certainly does not 
present the same style and flair as the ever-trim and unflappable 
Rubin, 61, whom he succeeded on July 2. 
</P>
<P>
	But in terms of policy, analysts say the youngest tenured  
professor in Harvard's history stacks up very well against Rubin, 
the savvy veteran of 26 years on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``Summers may not be a Rubin. But he is a perfectly adequate  
Summers,'' said Everett Ehrlich, a former top Clinton 
administration economist and now head of a Washington consulting 
firm. ``Few people have Rubin's charm, but few people have Summers' 
understanding of how the world economy works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, while Rubin was the seasoned front man chosen to walk  
down the Treasury steps and deliver words of assurance on bad 
market days, it was Summers working behind the scenes as Rubin's 
top deputy who was the architect of much of the policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin and President Clinton both relied on Summers' advice to  
craft administration responses to a string of foreign economic 
crises, from the meltdown of the Mexican peso in 1995 to the 
cascading collapse of Asian currencies over the past two years and 
the dark days of last fall when Russia's troubles looked as if they 
might drag the whole world into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	After recent allegations of massive money laundering in Russia  
brought cries of outrage from Republicans in Congress, it was 
Summers who marched to Capitol Hill to defend the administration's 
actions in supporting billions of dollars of Western support to 
Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	``To quarantine, contain or write off Russia as too corrupt  
would ill serve our national interest,'' Summers told Congress 
while at the same time promising that the administration will move 
swiftly to crack down on any illegal activities uncovered by the 
investigations. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, as the dollar fell to its lowest levels against  
the Japanese yen in more than three years, Summers has repeated 
virtually word-for-word the same response Rubin always gave to 
currency questions -- ``A strong dollar is in the national interest 
of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But repeating the Rubin mantra so far has not halted the  
dollar's slide. And as the American currency tumbles further, it 
has raised concerns about inflation threats coming from higher 
prices for imported goods and possibly a stock market collapse if 
foreigners panic and cash in their sizable holdings of U.S. stocks 
and bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell another 32  
points, ending a dismal week in which stocks fell by 524 points and 
now stand 1,047 points below their record close on Aug. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is also worried about the yen's strength against the  
dollar, fearing it could derail Japan's fledgling recovery by 
cutting into exports. Japanese officials had been hoping that the 
Group of Seven finance ministers meeting on Saturday would support 
a coordinated government intervention effort to buy dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	But Summers has let it be known going into those sessions that  
Japan should be worrying less about its currency's appreciation and 
focus more on stimulating domestic demand to make sure it doesn't 
topple back into recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Private economists generally applaud Summers for this stance,  
saying government intervention has little long-lasting effect on a 
currency's value. 
</P>
<P>
	``Summers is absolutely correct. We want a strong dollar but we  
want to achieve it through focusing on getting the economic 
fundamentals right,'' said Sung Won Sohn, chief economist at Wells 
Fargo in Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	And a weaker dollar, while posing a risk of higher inflation,  
could end up helping the U.S. economy by narrowing America's record 
trade deficit as U.S. exporters gain competitive advantages 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts also caution that there could be more bumpy days  
ahead for the U.S. stock market as investors watch to see how much 
farther the dollar may have to fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think currency speculators are going to do some more testing  
to try to find out just how far down they can push the dollar,'' 
said David Jones, chief economist at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co. in New 
York. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
