<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 03:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rookie Montoya Close to CART Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Paul Tracy is the longest of long shot contenders  
heading into the Texaco Grand Prix of Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-year-old Canadian driver is third in the CART FedEx  
Series standings. To win the title this season, he would have to 
score the maximum 66 points in the final three races of the season 
-- sweeping the pole, leading the most laps and winning at each of 
those events -- while series leader Juan Montoya went scoreless. 
</P>
<P>
	But Tracy isn't concerned about that. Right now, he's just happy  
to be on a team that's involved in the championship chase this late 
in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, not only is Tracy still in contention, but Team Kool  
Green teammate Dario Franchitti is second in the standings, 
trailing Montoya by 28 points heading into today's opening of 
practice and qualifying for Sunday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	``What a difference a year makes,'' said Tracy, who struggled  
through a miserable 1998 season that included an embarrassing 
incident during the inaugural Houston race. 
</P>
<P>
	The teammates were running 1-2 midway through the rain-soaked  
race when Tracy tried an inadvisable pass on Franchitti. The cars 
banged together and Tracy was knocked out of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti was able to continue and wound up winning the  
rain-shortened race after leading each of the 70 laps on the 
1.527-mile temporary street circuit winding around Houston's 
downtown convention center. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, he has posted four of his five career victories on  
temporary street circuits. That includes wins earlier this year in 
Toronto and Detroit, races in which Tracy finished second. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the dominant team on street courses, which certainly  
gives us a lot of confidence going into Houston,'' Tracy said. 
``Dario and I have run real close on the streets this year, but 
we'll try to avoid getting as close in Houston as we did last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody remembers who Dario and I made contact. We're both  
fierce competitors and neither of us wanted to give ground that 
day. It was a mistake and an unfortunate thing to have happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make matters worse, Tracy and team owner Barry Green got into  
a momentary shoving match after the driver returned to the pits. 
But both brushed shrugged off the incident as simply a 
heat-of-the-moment thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barry and I are fine. We never have had a harsh word about  
anything on the track,'' Tracy said. ``Sometimes, these things just 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti remembers last year's race very clearly.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very interesting race, to say the least,'' the  
26-year-old Scotsman said. ``The incident with the two cars 
touching stirred it up a bit, but there's no problem between Paul 
and myself. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact is we have equally fast cars and we are both capable  
of winning. It's only natural that at some point in a race, we'll 
find ourselves trying to pass each other. We just need to use our 
heads in doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Franchitti certainly cannot afford to have any kind of incident  
as he chases Montoya, the sensational 23-year-old Colombian rookie. 
</P>
<P>
	Montoya has taken the CART series by storm, driving to six poles  
and seven wins in his first 17 races. With only two events left 
after Sunday, Montoya could wrap up the title this week. 
</P>
<P>
	If he comes away with a 44-point lead, the elite Target/Chip  
Ganassi Racing team will have a record fourth consecutive series 
championship -- added to those won by Jimmy Vasser and two-time 
champ Alex Zanardi, Montoya's predecessor. 
</P>
<P>
	Some youngsters might feel pressured in this situation, but  
Montoya appears totally comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kid has nerves of steel,'' Vasser said. ``Maybe someone  
should remind him that he's 23 and on the brink of winning a PPG 
Cup. He really has the right attitude. He hasn't changed a thing 
about how he's approaching races.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
