<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Supports Stock Market Overseer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman  
Arthur Levitt said he would support creation of a single, 
independent agency to police the nation's stock markets. 
</P>
<P>
	In speech delivered at Columbia University on Thursday night,  
Levitt gave mild support to a plan in which each exchange would 
police its own trading, but an umbrella agency would monitor member 
activities, sales practices and trading between the various 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``While I certainly am not wedded to any particular model at  
this point -- a great deal more thinking needs to be done -- this 
latter approach is intriguing,'' Levitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	The idea of a single, independent agency has been gaining steam  
amid a proliferation of smaller alternative markets and the 
likelihood that the self-regulating New York Stock Exchange and 
Nasdaq Stock Market may change into for-profit businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Competition from new ECNs, or electronic communications  
networks, has pressured more traditional, non-for-profit exchanges 
like the NYSE and Nasdaq to consider selling stock to the public to 
raise money and allow for greater flexibility in their operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Both, however, would need SEC approval for changes to their  
business or regulatory units. And concerns have been raised that 
the NYSE's and Nasdaq's regulatory units would face endless 
conflicts of interest if the two exchanges became profit-driven 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how that would change the SEC's role, Levitt said the  
agency would act not as an enforcer, but rather as a sort of 
arbitrator, getting the various exchanges to remove 
anti-competitive practices and put in place measures that protect 
the public. 
</P>
<P>
	Levitt said the new ECNs provide needed competition in the  
markets, calling them ``one of the most important developments in 
our markets in years -- perhaps decades.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the SEC chairman also said the growing rivalry among markets  
has heightened the need to find a compromise between the benefits 
of competition and the problems created by fragmented markets, 
which can make it hard for investors to obtain information and find 
the best stock price. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the securities industry also expressed support  
Thursday for an umbrella regulatory body. 
</P>
<P>
	``The securities industry would like to see one regulator for  
the entire industry,'' said Bernard Madoff, president of Madoff 
Securities in New York, asserting that the SEC would need to ensure 
that such a body remains independent from any of the dozen or so 
stock markets now operating in this country. 
</P>
<P>
	Trading firms such as Madoff's would save money under a single  
regulatory body because they are currently required to help pay 
regulatory costs at each of the exchanges where they are members. 
</P>
<P>
	Madoff said the industry needs Levitt's leadership on the issue  
because neither the NYSE or the Nasdaq has provided any details on 
how they plan to police their markets should they become for-profit 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Some were critical of Levitt Thursday for not moving fast enough  
to address the rapid changes washing over the markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been way behind the curve on this,'' said Junius Peake,  
an economics professor at the University of Northern Colorado and a 
former member of the board of governors at the National Association 
of Securities Dealers, which oversees the Nasdaq market. 
</P>
<P>
	Peake said support for a single, independent regulator has been  
building for 25 years. Such an agency should regulate any aspect of 
an exchange that produces income because, ``That's where everybody 
gets caught up and everybody has a terrible time staying neutral.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
