<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Bank Execs Face Penalties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Parliament recommended Friday the  
suspension of some of Indonesia's leading financial officials in a 
banking scandal that has implicated some of President B.J. 
Habibie's associates. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal involves the channeling of government funds through  
Bank Bali, allegedly for Habibie's re-election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie vowed that he would not block any investigations into  
the case, even if they led to prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let the court proceed with the case. I have no plans or  
intentions to hamper the process,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	A special parliamentary investigation team said that Habibie  
should suspend Finance Minister Bambang Subianto, Bank Indonesia 
Governor Sjahril Sabirin and the entire board of governors of the 
central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Habibie ``should take immediate legal action against government  
officials who are strongly suspected of being involved, directly or 
indirectly'' in the Bank Bali scandal, the team said in a report. 
They should be suspended pending court verdicts, the report added. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have ordered a thorough investigation of anybody who was  
allegedly involved in the case,'' Habibie said Friday in a speech 
to members of parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Parliament also recommended the suspension of senior Habibie  
adviser A.A. Baramuli, former Bank Bali chief executive Rudy Ramli, 
and a number of other officials and executives. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers said the scandal was tarnishing Indonesia's image  
abroad, and called for a complete resolution of the case within one 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank Bali scandal centers around the transfer of $105  
million to Bank Bali as repayment for funds owed by a closed bank, 
under a government guarantee program. 
</P>
<P>
	Of this, $63 million was then transferred to a company  
controlled a senior official in the ruling Golkar party. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar opponents claim the funds were meant to finance Habibie's  
re-election campaign. The election, to be conducted by an assembly 
of legislators and government appointees, is set for November. 
</P>
<P>
	The scandal threatens to derail International Monetary Fund,  
World Bank and Asian Development Bank loans meant to help Indonesia 
emerge from economic turmoil. Private investors have also been 
spooked by the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has refused to publish a PriceWaterhouseCoopers  
investigation into the case, saying that banking security laws 
prevent it from being made public. 
</P>
<P>
	IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus on Thursday said  
Indonesia should publish the audit if it wants the IMF to consider 
resuming aid. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
