<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Timber Bill Makes Congressional Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A proposal that would sharply boost federal  
timber payments to counties and encourage the Forest Service to cut 
more trees cleared its first hurdle Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Agriculture Committee unanimously approved a bill by  
Rep. Nathan Deal, R-Ga., that would continue to give counties 25 
percent of forest revenues -- mostly logging receipts -- that come 
from federal land within counties' borders. 
</P>
<P>
	But Deal's bill requires the Forest Service to pay counties from  
the agency's budget when timber harvests fall below the average of 
the three peak years since 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a recognition... the revenue stream has been  
substantially declining,'' Deal said. 
</P>
<P>
	As logging on federal land has declined 70 percent in the last  
decade, average payments to many rural counties have fallen by an 
equal percentage. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop has forced some rural schools to lay off workers,  
reduce class offerings and delay equipment purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Deal bill boosts county payments by more than 80 percent to  
nearly $500 million. They would continue at that level for five 
years while an advisory group researches a long-term solution to 
the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management shipped about  
$273 million to about 800 counties in 41 states last year to pay 
for roads and schools in communities that have lost tax base to 
federal forest land. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 75 percent of the payments went to five states --  
Washington, Oregon, California, Idaho and Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials have threatened to veto the  
Deal bill, saying it is time to end the 91-year practice of linking 
children's education with fluctuating timber harvests. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
