<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	IMF To Give Colombia $2B in Aid  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Colombia and the International Monetary Fund  
reached agreement tonight on a three-year aid package worth between 
$2 billion and $3 billion, Finance Minister Juan Camilo Restrepo 
said. Colombia is suffering through its worst recession since the 
1930s. Details would be announced Monday, Restrepo said. A 
statement from the IMF said the two sides had reached an 
understanding on key elements that would support Colombia's 
economic program for 2000-2002. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Rebuked for Civil Rights Proposal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Democratic National Committee's black  
caucus rebuked Bill Bradley's suggestion that the 1964 Civil Rights 
Act be expanded to include sexual orientation, calling the 
suggestion ``ill-advised''. Texas state Rep. Al Edwards of Houston, 
head of the DNC caucus, asked the party's executive committee to 
pass a resolution against reopening the 1964 law, and they did so 
unanimously late today. The full Democratic National Committee 
could consider the resolution tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Ariz. Gov. Will Not Endorse McCain  
</P>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Arizona Sen. John McCain said today his home  
state's governor, Jane Hull, told him she will endorse his rival 
for the Republican presidential nomination, Texas Gov. George W. 
Bush. McCain has been counting on Arizona's early GOP primary Feb. 
22 to boost his chances three weeks later in California, where he 
is campaigning with fervor. McCain said he was disappointed by Mrs. 
Hull's decision but remained confident he could carry his home 
state, where he recently won his third Senate term by a wide 
margin. 

</P>
<P>
	Teen Pleads Guilty to Killing Parents  
</P>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Kip Kinkel, who killed his parents and  
gunned down two classmates at school, abandoned an insanity defense 
today and pleaded guilty to murder in a deal that could someday let 
him go free. The plea bargain came three days before Kinkel, 17, 
was to go on trial in the 1998 attack at Springfield's Thurston 
High School. He could get as little as 25 years in jail. 

</P>
<P>
	NASA Abandons Search for Mars Craft  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mission controllers gave up hope today of  
finding the Mars Climate Orbiter and were trying to determine what 
caused the $125 million NASA spacecraft to disappear. Data received 
from the craft early yesterday indicated it had come within about 
37 miles of the surface of the red planet and probably burned up, 
broke up or crashed. 

</P>
<P>
	Peacekeepers Root Out Militiamen in E. Timor  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Multinational troops searched  
house-to-house for suspected militiamen in East Timor's pillaged 
capital Friday, as new reports emerged that entire towns have been 
emptied of people and torched. The commander of Indonesian forces 
in East Timor said he will formally hand over responsibility for 
the territory on Monday. Still, in Geneva, the U.N. Human Rights 
Commission met in a special session to discuss sending a 
fact-finding mission to East Timor, which could lead to war crimes 
trials. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Intensifies Strikes on Chechnya  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian airstrikes around Chechnya's  
capital killed at least five people today and sent thousands 
fleeing as the intensifying campaign heightened fears of another 
war in the breakaway republic. Chechnya's envoy to Moscow, Mairbek 
Vachagaev, said Chechnya has warned Russia that hostilities could 
escalate into a tragedy of ``global proportions.'' Since the 
bombing campaign began, Vachagaev said nearly 300 people have died 
and thousands more have been injured. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 39.26; Nasdaq Falls 9.42  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rounded out a dismal week with a volatile  
session but generally modest losses today. The Dow Jones industrial 
average fell 39.26, closing at 10,279.33. Decliners on the New York 
Stock Exchange lead advancers 1,824-1,172. The Nasdaq was down 9.42 
at 2,740.41. 

</P>
<P>
	Phillies Beat Mets 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mike Lieberthal's RBI single off Armando  
Benitez capped a two-run eighth-inning rally that gave the 
Philadelphia Phillies a 3-2 victory over the Mets tonight, New 
York's fourth straight loss. The Mets began the night four games 
behind the Braves in the division and two ahead of Cincinnati for 
the wild card. The Braves were in Montreal on tonight, while 
Cincinnati played host to St. Louis. 

</P>
<P>
	Fan Attacks Astros' Spiers on Field  
</P>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- A fan came on to the field along the right  
field line and attacked Houston Astros right fielder Bill Spiers in 
the bottom of the sixth inning of their game against the Milwaukee 
Brewers. As the Brewers came to bat, the spectator jumped Spiers 
from behind and knocked him to the ground. The entire Astros bench 
came to Spiers defense. The unidentified attacker was handcuffed 
and led off the field by police. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by KELLY GRUEL  
  	   	
