<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New System Finds Delinquent Parents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly 3 million parents owing child support  
have been found since last October using an automated system 
Congress mandated to help locate such people, the government said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the 1996 welfare overhaul, Congress required that  
state-supplied information on employees be matched against a 
federal database of individuals owing child support. The directory 
was one of several measures that lawmakers required states to adopt 
in an effort to increase child support collections. 
</P>
<P>
	The system helped find 2.8 million delinquent payers in fiscal  
1999, said Olivia Golden, assistant secretary for children and 
families at the Department of Health and Human Services. The figure 
was more than twice the 1.2 million parents located in fiscal 1998, 
the first year of the system, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	All 50 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico and 146  
federal agencies report employment data to the national directory. 
Matches are reported back to the states, which automatically deduct 
payments from an individual's wages. 
</P>
<P>
	The department could not say how much child support had been  
collected from the 2.8 million people found since October. 
</P>
<P>
	Golden, who testified at a House Ways and Means subcommittee  
hearing on the child support enforcement program, said overall 
federal and state collections climbed to a record $14.3 billion in 
fiscal 1998 -- an increase of $6.3 billion since 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of cases in which collections were made also  
increased, to 4.5 million last fiscal year, compared with 2.8 
million cases in 1992, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal database contains more than 12 million child support  
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of fathers identified or acknowledging paternity also  
hit a high of 1.5 million last year -- almost three times the 1992 
figure of 512,000, Golden said. 
</P>
<P>
	A joint program with the State Department that denies U.S.  
passports to parents owing at least $5,000 in support has netted 
more than $2.2 million in lump sum payments since its June 1998 
launch, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	States also are being required to match delinquent parents  
against records from every financial institution operating within 
their borders. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials testifying before the human resources  
subcommittee praised the new measures. Lawmakers praised the 
effort, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Laura Kadwell, Minnesota's child support enforcement director  
and president-elect of the National Child Support Enforcement 
Association, said the employment database was increasing 
collections and getting money to children faster. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is encouraging to know that when we pass legislation ...  
something happens in people's lives,'' said Rep. Nancy Johnson, 
R-Conn., the panel's chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Health and Human Services Secretary Donna Shalala  
also announced that five states -- Colorado, Maryland, 
Massachusetts, Virginia and Washington -- several tribal and 
nonprofit groups and the University of New Hampshire will share 
more than $2.2 million in grants to test new ways of increasing 
collections. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
