<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unearthed Coffins Collected in N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Coast Guardsmen plied the 20-foot  
floodwaters of eastern North Carolina on Friday, trying to snag 
scores of coffins that popped out of the ground after Hurricane 
Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, a team of funeral home directors will begin  
identifying the wayward caskets to help get them back to what were 
supposed to be their final resting places. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're doing this to ensure that all the caskets are identified  
so that we can notify their loved ones,'' said Coast Guard Lt. 
Scott Bates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard crews spent the day in Princeville, across the  
Tar River from Tarboro, trying to round up as many as 100 airtight 
caskets that was forced from the ground by the river's floodwaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Too heavy to pull onto boats, the caskets were either towed to  
shore or tied to trees as Coast Guard crews recorded their 
locations. All appeared to be sealed and intact. 
</P>
<P>
	The manufacturer's ID numbers on the caskets can be traced to  
funeral homes and ultimately the families who bought them, said 
Andrew Ritter, executive director of the North Carolina Board of 
Mortuary Science. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a terrible thing, but when you're talking about 4,000  
caskets in Edgecombe County and 100 pop up, it's bad that those 100 
popped up, but it's good that 3,900 others didn't,'' Ritter said. 
He said they posed no health risk. 
</P>
<P>
	Search crews, meanwhile, used dogs trained to detect bodies to  
look for victims of the floodwaters that swallowed Princeville, a 
town of 1,900, a week ago. At least 42 deaths have been blamed on 
Hurricane Floyd in eastern North Carolina alone, and the numbers 
could rise as floodwaters recede. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the river in downtown Tarboro, some business owners were  
finally able to get into their stores for the first time since 
floodwaters forced them to evacuate Sept. 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Rex Browning, 66, remained upbeat as he cleaned up his jewelry  
store five blocks from the river. The paneling was wilted 4 feet up 
the wall, marking the floodwaters' high point. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started here 42 years ago with nothing, so I guess I have  
more than that now,'' Browning said as he examined broken watches. 
</P>
<P>
	A stench filled the air and some people wore masks over their  
mouths and noses. Murky water poured into the streets from whirring 
pumps emptying businesses. Wet carpeting, twisted furniture and 
other items littered the sidewalks. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the day, dump trucks and other heavy construction  
equipment rumbled down the muddy streets. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Webb's office supply store was open again, thanks to a  
4-foot-high concrete dam she had built a week ago in front of the 
place. ``It was almost as hard to tear down as it was to build,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a week after 20 inches of rain fell on parts of the  
state, emergency management officials said 2,700 people remained in 
24 shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	Utility crews have restored power to nearly all the 1.5 million  
people who lost electricity. But it could be at least two weeks 
before classes resume in all the school districts affected by the 
flooding. Eleven districts with about 176,000 students remained 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In some cases the schools are OK, but the communities are  
gone,'' said Ben Matthews, state director of school support. ``In 
other cases, the community is all right, but the road to the school 
is washed out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During a visit to Greenville, Gov. Jim Hunt pledged to find the  
money for repairs and improvements so the region isn't ravaged by 
flooding again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to fix up something and have it happen again two  
years from now,'' he said. ``This time, fix it right.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
