<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Station May Go to Private Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- NASA is willing to turn over operation of the  
new international space station to private enterprise, perhaps 
within the next decade, space agency Administrator Daniel Goldin 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldin told members of the Space Frontier Foundation that  
private control of the station would allow NASA to concentrate on 
its preferred mission of exploring the solar system. 
</P>
<P>
	In an age of shrinking budgets NASA can no longer afford to  
manage orbiting operations, such as the space station now under 
construction, and also reach out to explore the planets, Goldin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	After five or 10 years of steady operation, NASA would be  
willing to let private industry operate the station, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our hope is to turn the keys of the station over to an  
entrepreneur, if the private sector sees opportunity'' Goldin said. 
``The government would become just one of many tenants and users of 
the station. The entrepreneurs could make money as we wave good-bye 
to low-earth orbit to explore the far frontier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview following his speech, Goldin said any private  
company that wants the job must demonstrate that it has the 
necessary expertise and financial clout necessary for such an 
undertaking. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've made the offer,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Goldin spoke to about 400 engineers, scientists and aspiring  
space entrepreneurs attending the foundation's annual conference. 
The group is among several private organizations that has been 
lobbying the National Aeronautics and Space Administration and 
Congress for greater opportunity for private companies to pursue 
commercial ventures in space. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our NASA people want to design missions that open up the space  
frontier. They don't want to sit holding the hands of customers, 
watching dials and turning knobs,'' Goldin said. 
</P>
<P>
	For years, space exploration was considered the exclusive domain  
of NASA and a few big contractors such as Boeing Co. and Lockheed 
Martin Corp. that built spacecraft and provided services to the 
agency. 
</P>
<P>
	That has changed in recent years as the demand for commercial  
satellite launches have far exceeded NASA's launch capability. 
French, Russian and Chinese entitites have become strong 
competitors in the launch market. U.S. aerospace companies are 
working to develop inexpensive launch vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the satellite market has softened in recent months, it  
is expected to remain a key aerospace market. 
</P>
<P>
	The prospect of turning the station entirely over to private  
management goes far beyond a plan NASA has adopted that would allow 
private companies to share the space station. Goldin said the 
existing plan would make 30 percent or more of the station 
available to companies while NASA retains control. Several 
companies have submitted proposals that are under study. Goldin 
declined to name them or describe their proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a chance for the private sector to own a piece of the  
rock, make money from it and show there is life in the commercial 
sector, not just talk,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the conference attendees represented small startup  
companies trying to attract venture capital for low-cost launch 
vehicles or communications ventures. Many have complained in the 
past that NASA's vision of space commercialization was limited to 
big companies such as Boeing, said Rick Tumlinson, the foundation's 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Goldin's remarks came as a welcome surprise, he  
said. The group has argued for several years for creation of a 
quasi-public agency, such as the port authorities that control the 
nation's harbors, to operate the space station. 
</P>
<P>
	Sessions at the three-day convention dealt with potential space  
ventures ranging from space tourism to asteroid mining. But some 
who attended had more practical ventures in mind. 
</P>
<P>
	Like many at the conference, Gregory Allison, president of High  
Altitude Research Corp., dreams of the day when tourists will board 
spaceships for vacations in orbit or to the moon. But for now, his 
company is focused on providing cheap launch services for small 
communications satellites and university research projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, based in Huntsville, Ala., has had two paying  
customers so far, including NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory. 
</P>
<P>
	The company uses balloons to launch small rockets from an  
altitude of about 100,000 feet. He believes the company can break 
even by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	If the company is successful with small rockets, it will build  
larger vehicles to carry more ambitious payloads, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're promoting something we can finance, that there is an  
established market for,'' he said. ``Investors want a fast return 
on their investment, and they want a good return on their 
investment.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
