<HEADLINE> Author Accused of Stealing Ideas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A woman claims that Richard Paul Evans  
stole ideas from her manuscript for his 1998 best-selling novel, 
``The Locket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed by Leisa Hancock accuses Evans of using  
``distinctive sequences of events, distinctive locale, similarity 
of characters, similar plot and other original ideas'' in 
``Laurel,'' her unpublished novel. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans denied stealing Ms. Hancock's ideas or ever meeting her.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't see any infringement here. What I would suggest is  
that you read both books and you will reach the same conclusion,'' 
said Thomas Vuksinick, Evans' attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hancock said she gave Evans a copy of her manuscript at a  
1995 writers conference in Provo and asked him to read it. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans' books included ``The Letter'' and ``The Timepiece.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
