<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ryder Cup Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Mark O'Meara has gone from nearly  
invincible in major tournaments to virtually invisible in golf's 
top team event, the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Meara, winner of last year's Masters and British Open, was one  
of two Americans on the 12-member team who were not chosen by 
captain Ben Crenshaw to play in Friday's opening matches -- an 
alternate-shot competition in the morning and a best-ball round in 
the afternoon. Steve Pate, one of two picks made by Crenshaw, was 
the other. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always frustrating when you can't get out and play,''  
said O'Meara, whose No. 11 world ranking is the sixth highest among 
U.S. golfers. ``No. I'm not angry. I'm disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He dismissed the idea that his differences with Crenshaw on  
compensation for Ryder Cup golfers led to his inactivity. O'Meara, 
Tiger Woods, David Duval and Phil Mickelson were mentioned by the 
captain as perpetuating the controversy over how the PGA of America 
distributes Ryder Cup revenue to charities. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've taken a pretty heavy hit on the issue,'' O'Meara said.  
``I just feel bad that my name's been thrown so heavily into that 
controversy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While his teammates played their afternoon round, an idle  
O'Meara said he didn't play well in practice Wednesday but hit the 
ball OK on Thursday. There's still a chance for O'Meara to play 
Saturday or Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ben's trying to do the best he can as a captain. It's not  
easy,'' O'Meara said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MONTY'S COMPLAINTS:* Colin Montgomerie complained about the  
size of the driving range when he arrived at The Country Club. It 
didn't take him long to take issue with something else when the 
Ryder Cup matches began. 
</P>
<P>
	Mickelson and Duval took an early lead in their alternate-shot  
match against Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie when Mickelson played a 
flop shot to within a foot for birdie at No. 6, and Montgomerie 
missed a 10-footer. 
</P>
<P>
	PGA official Bill Clarke announced the score incorrectly --  
``Europe 3, United States 4, Europe is plus-1'' -- and Montgomerie 
tried to correct him. 
</P>
<P>
	After Europe won the next hole to tie the match, Montgomerie  
approached another PGA official. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got it all wrong, and he's walked in my line twice,''  
Montgomerie said. The Scotsman said when he tried to point out the 
errors to Clarke, the official told him, ``I'm too old and too 
decrepit. There's nothing I can do about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't seem to matter. Europe won the opening match, 3 and 2.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE SAME IN ANY LANGUAGE:* When Payne Stewart hit a shot into a  
bunker to the left of the 17th green Friday morning, one spectator 
to the right of the green apparently didn't see where the ball 
landed. 
</P>
<P>
	Emma Villacieros, the chairman of the Spanish golf federation,  
tapped Sergio Garcia's mother on the shoulder and asked, ``El 
bunker?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Si,'' Garcia's mother said. ``Bunker.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MEDICAL REPORT:* A 49-year-old man was revived after suffering  
a heart attack at the Ryder Cup. He was one of more than a 
half-dozen spectators with possible heart attacks at The Country 
Club by noon Friday, according to Dr. Charles Tracy, a club member 
and part of the event's medical team. 
</P>
<P>
	The man was standing near the 13th green during practice  
Thursday as Woods was approaching. The man collapsed and paramedics 
who arrived quickly found him unconscious and with no pulse. 
</P>
<P>
	``They shocked him once and he woke up. I have to believe we  
saved one man,'' Tracy said. He also said another person collapsed 
from a possible heart attack behind the staging during Thursday's 
opening ceremonies. 
</P>
<P>
	There was an ankle fracture, two epileptic seizures and a  
possible heart attack victim taken to the hospital, said Tracy, who 
practices at the Wellesley Center of Harvard Vanguard Medical 
Associates. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the presence of 20 portable defibrillators with  
personnel around the course was a key to responding rapidly to 
medical emergencies. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OPENING JITTERS:* Jesper Parnevik had played in a Ryder Cup  
before. He was part of the European team that won in 1997 at 
Valderrama. But he admitted to having some jitters when he went to 
the first tee of Friday's alternate-shot opening round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was nervous,'' the Swede said. ``I couldn't make my mind up  
whether I was going to cut it or draw it off the first tee. I had 
about 50 thoughts going through my head on the downswing and I was 
just glad to see it go straight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parnevik and Garcia won the match over Woods and Tom Lehman, 2  
and 1. 
</P>
<P>
	British Open winner Paul Lawrie of Scotland also was feeling the  
heat as he hit the first tee shot of the entire tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't feel cool inside,'' the Ryder Cup rookie said. ``But,  
after that first drive, it wasn't that bad, really. After that, I 
think we played pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and Montgomerie beat Duval and Mickelson 3 and 2.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DIVOTS:*Former President George Bush and his wife Barbara  
followed the first group in Friday morning's foursome. So did 
Britain's Prince Andrew, who was walking inside the ropes with the 
gallery packed on the other side. One marshal, apparently unaware 
of his identity, told him: ``Other side of the ropes.'' ... 
Parnevik on the maturity of Garcia: ``He might be 19 on his birth 
certificate, but he isn't, really.'' ... The three Europeans who 
didn't play Friday were Andrew Coltart of Scotland, Jarmo Sandelin 
of Sweden and Jean Van de Velde of France. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
