<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reuters Shares Drop 15 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Shares in Reuters Group PLC tumbled 15 percent in  
heavy trading Thursday in fallout from briefings to British and 
American analysts a day earlier by the media and financial 
information company. 
</P>
<P>
	The selloff continued even after the company denied it had  
disclosed any profit warnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Reuters ended a volatile session down the equivalent of $2.09 to  
close at $11.90 a share. With more than 55 million shares changing 
hands, it was the most active issue on the London Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Reuters U.S. shares were down nearly 11 percent Thursday on the  
Nasdaq Stock Market, dropping $8.75 to $71. 
</P>
<P>
	The slide followed company briefings to analysts on Wednesday.  
Some analysts reduced their forecasts for Reuters earnings 
following the session and HSBC Securities downgraded its rating of 
the stock. 
</P>
<P>
	One New York analyst cited by Dow Jones Newswires said Reuters  
told investors that orders for some financial information services 
had been deferred in recent months over concerns about the Year 
2000 bug. 
</P>
<P>
	Reuters also reportedly said Instinet, its electronic  
stock-trading service, was hindered by low trading volume at Nasdaq 
during July and August. Instinet handles around 15 percent of 
Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	``The background briefings were on subjects including Internet  
strategy, the plans of our Instinet electronic broker and the 
progress of the joint venture with Dow Jones,'' said a statement 
issued by Reuters on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	There was nothing in the briefings that could be construed as a  
profit forecast or as a profit-warning, the Reuters statement also 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
