<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mosley To Fight As a Welterweight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMECULA, Calif. (AP) -- Sugar Shane Mosley, dominant as a  
lightweight, is moving up in class and, he hopes, into matches that 
will gain him more attention and bigger purses. 
</P>
<P>
	The unbeaten Mosley, who has stopped 30 of his 32 opponents, has  
jumped two weight classes and will fight for the first time as a 
welterweight. 
</P>
<P>
	Saying he would welcome a bout against either Felix Trinidad or  
Oscar De La Hoya, Mosley first must get past Wilfredo Rivera. They 
meet Saturday night in a non-title bout at the Pechanga 
Entertainment Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Mosley, who took the IBF lightweight title from Philip Holiday  
in 1997 and won all eight of his title defenses by knockout, 
believes he actually will benefit from gaining 12 pounds up to the 
welterweight limit of 147. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel a lot stronger, I feel a lot faster, and I'm more  
sure-footed,'' he said. ``I think people wonder if I'll struggle. 
</P>
<P>
	``They expect me to not hit as hard and to be a little slower,  
but that won't be the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Mosley, his father and trainer, agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think Shane will have even more power because he hasn't had  
to worry so much about making the weight,'' Jack Mosley said. His 
son is moving from the 135-pound division to the 147-pound division 
and is by-passing the 140-pound junior welterweight class. 
</P>
<P>
	Shane Mosley, coming off an eighth-round knockout of John Brown  
on April 17, said he had difficulty making the 135-pound limit for 
that bout. 
</P>
<P>
	He believes fighting as a welterweight, a glamour class now with  
De La Hoya and Trinidad, will finally put him in the limelight. 
</P>
<P>
	While Trinidad holds the IBF and WBC welterweight titles, having  
beaten De La Hoya last Saturday, a match with De La Hoya could be 
the more lucrative one. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in a perfect place to show what I can do,'' Mosley said.  
``I want to put on a show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Jack Mosley: ``Shane is a star in his own right. We just  
want to make that star brighter. Sure, a fight with Oscar would do 
that. It would be great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mosley faces an accomplished foe in Rivera is (30-3-1). One of  
the losses was to De La Hoya, and the other two were to Pernell 
Whitaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera lost to De La Hoya when the fight was stopped after eight  
rounds because of a severe cut. Whitaker outpointed Rivera in each 
of their two meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	Rivera is coming off a first-round knockout of Jimmy Morgan on  
July 16. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
