<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid Announces Job Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp. cut 330 jobs on Friday,  
about half of them near its Pennsylvania headquarters, in a move 
the drug store chain said would save $31.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The layoffs, which involve administrative and field staff  
positions, come just a day after the company revealed plans to 
close a distribution center in Utah and eliminate 500 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The cuts won't affect staffing levels at Rite Aid stores, where  
the company hopes to place some of the employees losing their jobs, 
said spokeswoman Karen Rugen. 
</P>
<P>
	No more large reductions are planned, but it is possible that  
additional positions could be eliminated if the company sells some 
stores or other assets, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid, based in Camp Hill, Pa., employs about 85,000 people  
overall, including 2,000 in administrative positions. The company 
has struggled over the past year, reporting a 39-percent drop in 
fourth-quarter earnings in March. Rite Aid attributed the decrease 
to new store openings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our staff overhead expenses have started to grow at a rate  
faster than our business can support,'' Chairman and Chief 
Executive Officer Martin Grass said Friday in a statement. ``While 
we would prefer to not dislocate these fine hardworking employees, 
these cuts are necessary to make us more competitive and to help 
reenergize our financial growth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The savings from the layoffs announced Friday will amount to  
about $20 million after taxes, or 7 cents per share. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's financial ``results haven't been quite as good as  
it hoped, and it has cash flow problems,'' said Mark Husson, an 
analyst with Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the company announced it would shut a distribution  
center in Ogden, Utah, as it shifts its West Coast distribution 
network to a new facility in Lancaster, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Company spokeswoman Karen Rugen said Friday's announcement was  
unrelated to the company's actions in Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts have predicted Rite Aid will sell several hundred  
West Coast stores which, along with the Ogden distribution center, 
were acquired from Thrifty Payless in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Rite Aid  
slid 8 percent, falling $1 per share to $11. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid operates 3,800 stores in 30 states and the District of  
Columbia and has annual revenues of nearly $13 billion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 02:40:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scott Had a Curmudgeon Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- On screen and off, George C. Scott had such a  
curmudgeonly presence that his considerable acting talents seemed 
overshadowed by the force of his personality. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the fact that remains is whether Scott was on stage, in  
films or on television, he was among the most dynamic actors of his 
generation. 
</P>
<P>
	His performances reflected his personal life; he conducted both  
fearlessly and without quarter. Scott was 71 when he died 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a 1971 Associated Press interview, he reflected on his  
profession: 
</P>
<P>
	``There are only two kinds of actors, in my opinion: risk actors  
and safe actors. Safe actors hold back, experiment not, dare not, 
change nothing and have no artistic courage. I call them `walkers.' 
</P>
<P>
	``One of my professional faults has been never to walk. I may  
stagger a little now and then, but I have never been accused of 
walking. I would rather go out there and scream to the housetops 
than play it cool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such an attitude took its toll: stormy marriages, estrangement  
from his children, a long record of alcoholism, clashes with 
directors, producers, other actors and yes, the Academy of Motion 
Picture Arts and Sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott had no respect whatsoever for the Academy Awards, which he  
dubbed ``a meat parade.'' He ignored his first Academy nomination 
as supporting actor for his second film, ``Anatomy of a Murder'' in 
1959. He tried unsuccessfully to decline his second nomination, for 
``The Hustler'' in 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	Then came the inevitable Oscar.  
</P>
<P>
	If ever an actor was born to play a role, it was George C. Scott  
as Gen. George (Blood and Guts) Patton. Scott's opening harangue to 
the troops before a mammoth U.S. flag in the 1970 movie ``Patton'' 
proved one of the great scenes in film history. 
</P>
<P>
	And Scott's refusal to attend the ceremony or accept the award  
confirmed his Pattonesque reputation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided to speak my piece,'' he remarked in 1977. ``I sent  
the Academy a telegram which said, `Include me out.' They replied 
negatively, saying it was against policy. Whatever the hell policy 
means. It's all absolute b.s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next year when he was nominated for an Emmy for ``The  
Price,'' he tried to avoid another brouhaha by asking his friend 
Jack Cassidy to accept for him if he won. He did. 
</P>
<P>
	And when another Oscar nomination came in 1971 for ``The  
Hospital,'' Scott kept his mouth shut this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ah, it was so much nicer that way,'' he said later. ``I have  
finally found out how to handle these things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scott's first three marriages ended in divorce. The first one,  
although brief, resulted in the birth of a daughter. His second 
wife was pregnant with their second child when he left her for his 
co-star, Colleen Dewhurst. The union of two such strong-willed 
figures seemed doomed, although they wound up marrying each other 
twice. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1972, he married a fourth actress, Trish Van Devere. That  
union would survive numerous co-starrings and separations. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the actor's early years were marked by alcohol-fueled  
escapades. 
</P>
<P>
	``I drank that stuff for 30 years,'' he said in 1978, ``and I've  
given up on it. I got tired of feeling bad. I tried so hard to 
drink everything they make, but they won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With or without booze, he was an intimidating figure, so much so  
that when Maureen Stapleton was rehearsing the play ``Plaza Suite'' 
with Scott, she wailed to director Mike Nichols: ``I'm so 
frightened of George, I don't know what to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My dear,'' Nichols replied, ``the whole world is frightened of  
George.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Bob Thomas has been covering Hollywood for The  
Associated Press for nearly 60 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 14:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Whole Foods To Spin Off Internet Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, (AP) -- Whole Foods Inc. said Thursday it will spin off  
its Internet grocery business and sell shares of the Web venture to 
the public within a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Austin-based natural foods store chain said it wants to  
build a ``healthy-living'' Web site where consumers can get 
information as well as groceries. 
</P>
<P>
	John P. Mackey, the company's founder and chief executive, will  
lead the new company, to be called WholePeople.com. The store chain 
sold a 13.5 percent stake in the new company to venture 
capitalists, whom Mackey would not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	Whole Foods' stock lost more than 9 percent in trading Friday on  
the NASDAQ stock market, down 3 15/32 to 33 3/32. 
</P>
<P>
	Whole Foods is the nation's largest natural foods chain, with  
more than 90 stores in more than 20 states and Washington, D.C. It 
stresses food free of pesticides, preservatives and sweeteners. Its 
stores include Whole Foods Market, Bread &AMP; Circus, Bread of Life, 
Fresh Fields, Merchant of Vino and Wellspring Grocery. The company 
has also moved into the coffee roasting and nutritional-supplements 
lines. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, with 14,200 employees, reported sales last year of  
nearly $1.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The new online company will include Amrion Inc., a mail-order  
vitamin-sales firm that Whole Foods bought in 1997, and American 
WholeHealth Inc., a holistic-medicine company. 
</P>
<P>
	An analyst said the spin-off indicates that selling groceries  
over the Internet, which Whole Foods started to do in March, isn't 
a profitable business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you're going to see an explosion of people  
buying broccoli over the Internet, but you will see an explosion in 
people looking for information or easier-to-ship products,'' 
Matthew Patsky of Adams Harkness in Boston told the Austin 
American-Statesman. His company helped find investors for the new 
Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	Online grocery sales last year were just $148 million, according  
to Jupiter Communications, an online research company in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Whole Foods is taking a non-recurring charge of $3.5 million to  
close two Amrion divisions. The company also said it would take a 
$6 million charge this quarter for software and hardware purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	Removing Amrion and WholeFoods.com from Whole Foods' balance  
sheet takes away $1.1 billion in revenue and about $34.7 million in 
net income, the company said. That means Whole Foods' fiscal year 
2000 earnings will likely be 18 to 26 cents below analysts' 
estimates of $2.13 per share, Mackey said. 
</P>
<P>
	He predicted that Whole Foods' traditional business will grow 15  
to 20 percent next year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 03:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bush Emphasizes Defense, Weaponry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush's defense policy priorities are  
similar in many ways to those of the current administration. The 
Republican presidential candidate wants the military transformed 
into a more agile, mobile force, and he sees a growing threat to 
the American homeland from terrorists with weapons of mass 
destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Where Bush differs with President Clinton's approach is mainly  
on the pace of military change and the extent of U.S. troop 
deployments on open-ended peacekeeping missions like Bosnia and 
Kosovo. The Texas governor said in a policy speech Thursday that if 
elected to the White House he would order an immediate review of 
overseas commitments, though not to NATO or in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not be permanent peacekeepers, dividing warring  
parties,'' he said in an address to the Citadel military academy in 
Charleston, S.C. ``This is not our strength or our calling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of Bush's prescriptions for a healthier military are  
similar to those pursued by Clinton, including pay raises for 
troops and innovations to make U.S. forces more adaptable and 
easier to deploy on short notice. Bush would spend $5 billion more 
on pay raises over the next five years than the administration 
currently proposes, and he would commit an extra $20 billion over 
five years on research and development of next-generation weaponry. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Kosiak, an analyst at the private Center for Strategic  
and Budget Assessments, said Bush's proposals were ``positive,'' 
but raised questions about how he would pay the bill while also 
pushing large tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	In his speech, Bush did not say how much he would add to defense  
spending overall, but Condoleeza Rice, his top foreign policy 
adviser, told reporters that he would propose ``significant 
increases'' to the $270 billion now spent on defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice said Bush would not attempt to change the current policy on  
gays in the military, which allows homosexuals to serve as long as 
they don't acknowledge their sexual preference. He also supports 
the current policy on roles for women in the military, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Cheney, who served as defense secretary in Bush's  
father's administration, said the Texas governor's defense policy 
``is on the right track.'' He said the special emphasis on military 
research and development was particularly important for maintaining 
the American military's global dominance well into the 21st 
century. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, who holds a large lead in the polls over all Republican  
and Democratic contenders, said the Clinton administration had 
weakened the nation's defenses by embarking on ``vague, endless and 
aimless'' missions abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	As president, Bush said, he would order a top-to-bottom review  
of the military -- its structure, strategy and spending priorities -- 
and give his secretary of defense a mandate: ``Challenge the status 
quo and envision a new architecture of American defense for decades 
to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``At the earliest possible date'' Bush said his administration  
would deploy anti-missile systems to protect not only U.S. troops 
abroad and allies but also to shield the U.S. homeland from 
``attack and blackmail.'' He did not spell out how extensive the 
national system would be, but aides said it would be more complete 
than Clinton envisions. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration plans to decide as early as June 2000  
whether to deploy a limited national defense system. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he would have the United States withdraw from the 1972  
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty with Russia if Moscow refused to 
accept amendments allowing the testing and deployment of a national 
missile defense. The Clinton administration is pressing Moscow to 
accept such changes and has said withdrawal from the treaty remains 
an option. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he would earmark at least 20 percent of the Pentagon's  
weapons procurement budget for programs that propel America 
``generations ahead'' in military technology. He mentioned such 
possibilities as a ``stealthy ship'' packed with long-range 
missiles and unmanned aircraft capable of long-range missile 
strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he would commit an extra $20 billion to defense  
research and development between 2001 and 2006. That would be in 
addition to the approximately $173 billion the Clinton 
administration has proposed over a similar period. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
