<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 17:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olazabal Comes Back at Ryder Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- From the solitude of a morning practice  
round to the cheers of the gallery at dusk, Jose Maria Olazabal 
returned to the Ryder Cup on Friday afternoon from a short, and 
self-imposed, sabbatical. 
</P>
<P>
	After benching himself in the morning alternate shot matches --  
snapping a perfect attendance record spanning five previous Ryder 
Cup appearances -- Olazabal paired with Miguel Angel Jimenez in the 
afternoon fourball to beat Hal Sutton and Jeff Maggert 2 and 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, it was a difficult decision for me not to play in  
the morning,'' Olazabal said after the European pair clinched a 
point with a par 4 on No. 17. ``But I think it was the right thing 
to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Olazabal spent the time on the course, trying to rescue  
a swing that has caused him to miss the cut in two majors -- he 
withdrew in the third, the U.S. Open, when he broke his hand 
punching a wall -- since winning the Masters in April. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, he was criss-crossing the fairways through his round,  
putting him between an access road and the gallery on No. 15 before 
he saved par with a 4. ``I still missed some tee shots that I was 
not pleased with,'' he said before trying to beat the sunset with a 
few more practice holes. 
</P>
<P>
	Sutton and Maggert were the only Americans to win their morning  
foursome match as the Europeans took a 6-2 lead after the first 
day. But Olazabal and Jimenez outplayed them, winning the first 
hole on Jimenez' birdie and holding a two-hole lead for 14 of the 
last 15 holes. 
</P>
<P>
	Golfers can play a minimum of one and a maximum of five matches  
in a Ryder Cup. For the first two days, in both morning and 
afternoon, the captain must choose eight members of the 12-man team 
to play and four to sit; all 12 play singles on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Olazabal had never sat out in five previous Ryder Cups  
-- that's 25 of a possible 25 matches, with a 14-8-3 record -- he 
went to European captain Mark James on Thursday and said his 
driving was too erratic to play in the alternate shot format. James 
obliged by leaving him out of the draw. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm quite happy with what Jose tells me,'' said James, who as  
captain has kept close tabs on all of his players' progress. 
``There's no secrets in that team room. It's an open book.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nor was it a difficult decision to play Olazabal in the  
afternoon, when the players each play the hole but count only the 
best score. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a very good fourball player,'' James said. ``Even if he  
isn't driving the ball well,'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olazabal began playing at age 6, when his mother -- who worked at  
the same course in Spain where his father was the greenskeeper -- 
would take him out in the afternoon after everyone else had 
finished playing. 
</P>
<P>
	But with 35,000 people crowding into the The Country Club for  
the first day of matches on Friday, it wasn't quite so easy to find 
a moment of solitude on the course. Fans lined up five and 10 deep 
around the greens, and the grandstands located throughout the 
course were full whenever the golfers came near. 
</P>
<P>
	The foursomes were on the back nine and the crowds had followed  
them when Olazabal teed off No. 1 for some practice at 10:50 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Crickets chirped.  
</P>
<P>
	The wind rustled through the trees.  
</P>
<P>
	``Go get 'em, Jose,'' one man yelled to Olazabal as he and his  
caddie trudged down the first fairway. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was no one for Olazabal to ``get.''  
</P>
<P>
	Not yet, anyway.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
