<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> London Stages Fashion Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Shrugging off the absence of several of its stars,  
London Fashion Week again proved it deserves its reputation for 
exciting, cutting-edge design. 
</P>
<P>
	From Hussein Chalayan's remote-controlled glass-fiber dress over  
a fluffy pink tutu, to Amanda Wakeley's sleekly classic evening 
sheaths, London has not lost its wow factor -- or its claim to be a 
fashion capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, it's been what people love London about: very  
extreme, very bold, very exciting,'' said designer Paul Costelloe, 
who opened proceedings Monday night with a collection of long 
tunics and fluid trousers in the brightest pinks. 
</P>
<P>
	While fashion ``may grow up elsewhere,'' said Daily Telegraph  
fashion editor Hilary Alexander, ``London is where you see fashion 
being born.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More than 40 designers held catwalk shows over four days and  
more than 200 others exhibited accessories and jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
	The look for spring/summer 2000 is ruched, ruffled and ridged,  
in layers of buttery leather, delicate lace or wisps of chiffon 
printed with florals, spots and stripes or scattered with sequins. 
The palette is white, moss, flesh tones and pastels. Look for 
blouson tops, the tiniest hot pants and daring backless dresses 
with this season's new neckline, the halter. 
</P>
<P>
	Alexander McQueen, Vivienne Westwood and Nicole Farhi opted out  
of the London scene after unveiling their collections in New York 
last week. And once again, Antonio Berardi will stage his show in 
Milan. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chalayan, the British Designer of the Year, was there with  
an array of his trademark precision-cut garments. 
</P>
<P>
	In keeping with the season's very feminine look, he showed  
concertina frills and fluted hems on tutus and ballerina dresses. 
Some had cutaway backs with intricately scrolled petticoats that 
resembled rosebuds. 
</P>
<P>
	A child used a remote control device to open the glass-fiber  
panels of one dress, revealing a confection of tulle petticoats. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Smith produced trouser suits and shirts in candy stripes  
that evoked gracious 1920s tennis parties, and embroidered velvets 
inspired by India. Owen Gaster shone with skirts in skin-tight 
snakeskin, tailored pink tweed and leather printed with holograms. 
</P>
<P>
	Red or Dead's Wayne Hemingway sent ``real people'' down the  
catwalk in African prints and outfits in batik, cheesecloth and 
crushed linen, hessian, muslin and leather. He said he decided not 
to use models to give ``a sense of an egalitarian future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Welsh designer Julien Macdonald, known for his glorious knits,  
injected a note of glamour by having Mel G -- Scary Spice to her 
fans -- model a translucent pink beaded dress with slim jeweled 
straps. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Macdonald creations included vivid PVC bomber jackets  
printed with computer graphics, tie-dye jackets and fluorescent 
miniskirts and mirrored halter dresses. 
</P>
<P>
	Another up-and-coming designer, Matthew Williamson, produced  
sequin-studded camisoles and low-slung ``harem'' skirts studded 
with jewels, inspired by India's exotic Kathkali dancers. 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, most shows were held in marquees erected at the main  
venue, the Natural History Museum. But this year many designers 
opted for the battered warehouses that line Brick Lane in east 
London, the historical home of Britain's garment industry. 
</P>
<P>
	They included Preen, which showed dramatically draped leather  
tunics with halter tops and torn hems and Clements Ribeiro, who 
produced dresses, blouson tops, skirts and micro shorts in 
transparent chiffon scattered with flowers or sequins in pink, 
plum, brown and yellow. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonja Nuttall displayed her pleated and ruched outfits in stone,  
black and honey on racks in the back of a parked truck. 
</P>
<P>
	The $28 billion a year British fashion industry now employs  
300,000 people. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 02:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Conn. Treasurer Guilty in Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A former state treasurer faces up to 40  
years in prison after he pleaded guilty to federal corruption 
charges of accepting over $100,000 in kickbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Paul Silvester was paid thousands of dollars by  
middlemen who get states to invest their pension money with certain 
financial firms. Some of the money turned up in his failed election 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``He used his authority as state treasurer to invest money not  
solely in the best interest of the funds, but to guarantee wealth 
for himself, his friends and his colleagues,'' U.S. Attorney 
Stephen Robinson said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Silvester, 37, pleaded guilty Thursday to racketeering and money  
laundering charges. He also faces a $750,000 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The scheme included Silvester's brother and brother-in-law, who  
also pleaded guilty Thursday to federal corruption charges and face 
prison time. 
</P>
<P>
	Silvester was hustled out of the courthouse and away from  
reporters without answering questions. His attorney, Hubert Santos, 
said his client would have no comment, and said the pension fund 
had not been jeopardized. 
</P>
<P>
	Silvester, a Republican, was deputy state treasurer when he was  
appointed by Gov. John G. Rowland to finish the term of Christopher 
Burnham in July 1997. Burnham resigned to take a private-sector 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	Silvester lost the November 1998 election to Denise Nappier, who  
assured residents Thursday that the state pension fund was in good 
hands and that no one in her office is being investigated in the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund actually grew from $16.8 billion to $18.5 billion  
during Silvester's tenure between September 1997 and February 1999, 
a month after he left office. 
</P>
<P>
	Silvester had been under investigation for several months for  
investments made during his final months in office. Most of the 
investments were made after the election but before his term ended 
Jan. 6. 
</P>
<P>
	His 50-year-old brother, Mark, could get five years in jail and  
be ordered to pay a $250,000 fine after pleading guilty to 
conspiracy to solicit and accept corrupt payments. Their 
brother-in-law, Peter Hirschl, 43, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to 
launder money and faces up to 10 years in prison and a $250,000 
fine. 
</P>
<P>
	All three were released on $10,000 bond and are scheduled to be  
sentenced March 20. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 19:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fan Attacks Astros' Spiers on Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- A fan came on to the field along the right  
field line and attacked Houston Astros right fielder Bill Spiers in 
the bottom of the sixth inning of Friday night's game against the 
Milwaukee Brewers. 
</P>
<P>
	As the Brewers came to bat, the spectator jumped Spiers from  
behind and knocked him to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	The entire Astros bench came to Spiers defense. Mike Hampton,  
the starting pitcher, raced out and pummeled the spectator as other 
teammates tried to separate Hampton from the attacker. Astros 
relievers jumped over the bullpen wall in center field and joined 
the melee. 
</P>
<P>
	Spiers left momentarily with a welt under his left eye and a  
bloody nose, but stayed in the game. Hampton was visibly upset by 
the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	The unidentified attacker was handcuffed and led off the field  
by Milwaukee County sheriffs deputies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 08:03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grizzlies Sold for $200 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The Vancouver Grizzlies have  
been sold to the owner of the NHL's St. Louis Blues for $200 
million, and the new owner refuses to say what his long-term plans 
are for the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no current plan to move the Grizzlies,'' said Bill  
Laurie, who nonetheless refused to give any assurances to local 
fans that he won't try to move the team in the next year or two. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie, along with his wife, Nancy, earlier this year tried  
unsuccessfully to purchase the Denver Nuggets. They own the new 
Kiel Center in downtown St. Louis -- an arena that all too often 
sits empty. That could change if Laurie decides to move the team, 
but such a scenario is at least a year or two away. 
</P>
<P>
	Franchises wanting to relocate must submit a petition to the  
league before March 1 in order to move for the following season. 
But the Grizzlies are prohibited by their expansion agreement from 
making such an application before May 15, 2000 -- a rule that, 
although it could be amended, would seem to ensure the team will 
continue to be based in Vancouver for the next two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchase price of $200 million was confirmed to The  
Associated Press by two league sources speaking on condition of 
anonymity. Former owner John McCaw would only say that he sold the 
team for a profit. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago, the New Jersey Nets sold for $150 million --  
meaning the Laurie purchase has driven up the value of the other 28 
teams substantially. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie, an avid basketball fan and a former point guard for  
Memphis State, agreed in April to buy the Colorado Avalanche of the 
NHL, the Denver Nuggets of the NBA and Denver's new Pepsi Center 
for $400 million. But he lost out when a rival group, given a 
second chance to bid, offered $461 million. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the Grizzlies sale came just as league officials, from  
coaches to general managers to support staff, were arriving in 
Vancouver to attend the league meetings held every other year. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner David Stern voiced his personal opposition to a  
relocation, citing the league's record of not having any franchise 
migrations since the Clippers moved from San Diego to Los Angeles 
in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my goal to see the Grizzlies stay and succeed in  
Vancouver,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision on whether to allow the team to move, however,  
would ultimately be made by the league's Board of Governors. Of the 
league's 29 owners, only 15 would be needed to approve a 
relocation. A three-quarters majority would be needed to approve 
the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not unprecedented for an NBA team to move, but on the  
other hand when you place a franchise someplace, you ask the fans 
to make a certain commitment to the team,'' Stern said. ``And it's 
not inappropriate for the fans to expect the team to have some 
commitment to them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie, asked repeatedly if he would give the fans of Vancouver  
some kind of commitment or reassurance, refused to say anything of 
substance regarding his long-term plans for the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really feel uncomfortable with the skepticism, only because  
this is a big day for our family,'' Laurie said. ``This is a big 
step for us, and somehow some of the excitement and fun is being 
taken away by the cloud hanging over us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCaw also owns the NHL Vancouver Canucks and GM Place, the  
team's 19,000-seat arena. Both had been for sale, but McCaw said 
they are now off the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation has swirled about the future of the Grizzlies  
franchise since McCaw said last month he was willing to sell part 
or all of his Orca Bay sports empire. 
</P>
<P>
	The Grizzlies have met with limited success since joining the  
NBA, never winning more than 19 games. Vancouver was 8-42 in the 
lockout-shortened 1999 season, the worst record in the 29-team 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareef Abdur-Rahim, the Grizzlies' best player, reacted  
cautiously to the sale announcement. 
</P>
<P>
	``With everything happening as fast as it has, the reassuring  
thing is that the people I trust and the people I believe in are 
still there,'' Abdur-Rahim said. ``I believe in (general manager) 
Stu (Jackson) and the people up there, and as long as that 
situation is the same, it's cool. That was the determining factor 
in me signing (a contract extension last season) -- Stu being there 
and making me believe in his vision of what we need to do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 03:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bush Emphasizes Defense, Weaponry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George W. Bush's defense policy priorities are  
similar in many ways to those of the current administration. The 
Republican presidential candidate wants the military transformed 
into a more agile, mobile force, and he sees a growing threat to 
the American homeland from terrorists with weapons of mass 
destruction. 
</P>
