<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> F-22 Compromise Still Elusive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Negotiators on defense spending continued to  
seek middle ground Friday on the new F-22 stealth jet fighter, 
which the House voted in July to terminate. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate negotiators offered a plan to fund $1.2 billion of the  
original $1.8 billion that the Pentagon had requested for the 
program for the fiscal year that begins on Oct 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of being used to buy six of the new aircraft as the  
administration had requested, however, the proposal would put the 
bulk of the money into research, development and testing. 
</P>
<P>
	That could, in effect, delay production of the new sophisticated  
fighter for at least a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate earlier had voted to provide the full $1.8 billion  
for fiscal 2000 requested by the administration for the $65 billion 
aircraft being produced by Lockheed Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate offer, made by Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman  
of the Senate Appropriations Committee, was a refinement on an 
informal proposal he made earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	House negotiators had voiced preliminary support for such a  
plan. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
