<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Financier May Need Public Defender </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Authorities say rogue financier Martin  
Frankel masterminded one of the largest insurance scams in U.S. 
history, but now he doesn't even have enough money to pay his legal 
bills, according to his lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	New Haven defense attorney Hugh Keefe said Friday he will  
withdraw as Frankel's lawyer because federal officials have frozen 
all of Frankel's assets and rejected requests to release a portion 
of the funds. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you were to believe the government, he's allegedly one of  
the great white-collar criminals of our time, but if he is, he 
certainly doesn't have any funds to hire a private lawyer,'' Keefe 
told The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``He can't very well mount a defense unless he gets some of the  
money they seized from him,'' Keefe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Keefe said the money was needed both to pay his bill and hire  
experts to work for the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Delcie Thibault, a spokesman for the U.S. Attorney's Office in  
Connecticut, declined to say how much the government had seized or 
comment on Keefe's claims. A message was left seeking comment from 
a spokeswoman for the FBI in Connecticut. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel, a 44-year-old money manager from Greenwich, fled the  
United States in May after allegedly bilking insurance companies in 
five states out of hundreds of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	When Frankel was arrested in a hotel room in Hamburg, Germany,  
on Sept. 4, authorities seized more than $1 million in cash and 
diamonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, the FBI seized one of the two mansions Frankel kept in  
Greenwich. The IRS seized the second estate earlier this month, 
alleging it was bought with money from a Swiss bank account into 
which Frankel had deposited $44 million he stole from the insurance 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	State regulators have seized $57.5 million and were seeking  
another $26.5 million in a frozen Swiss bank account linked to 
Frankel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we're working with other states toward whatever  
other asset recovery will be possible,'' said Marilyn Elam, a 
spokeswoman for the Tennessee Department of Commerce and Insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	Keefe said defending Frankel will require an array of  
high-priced experts, including forensic accountants to help 
decipher the wildly varying estimates of the loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators say Frankel's unlicensed brokerage siphoned at least  
$218 million from insurers in Arkansas, Mississippi, Missouri, 
Oklahoma and Tennessee. A lawsuit filed by some of the companies 
puts the loss much higher, at $915 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators originally thought Frankel may have stolen as much  
as $1.98 billion from the St. Francis of Assisi Foundation, a bogus 
charity Frankel established last year in the British Virgin 
Islands. But it's now unclear whether much -- if any -- of that money 
ever existed. 
</P>
<P>
	Keefe said he has notified the federal public defender's office  
in Connecticut that they may have to appoint someone to defend 
Frankel. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas G. Dennis, chief federal public defender, could not be  
reached for comment Friday. Two messages were left at his Hartford 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	Keefe said he has been unable to speak to Frankel since he was  
arrested because officials at the Hamburg prison where Frankel is 
being held will not allow Frankel to use the telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he will remain as Frankel's lawyer for several more days  
as he waits to hear whether German officials will allow him to 
speak to Frankel to explain the process for appointing a new 
attorney. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
