<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Announces Organ Donation Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration announced a series  
of initiatives aimed at increasing organ donation, including a $13 
million grant to educate people. 
</P>
<P>
	``The steps we are taking today will not only highlight the need  
for organ donation, it will make organ donation more possible and 
will help more of America's families to share the gift of health 
and life,'' said Vice President Al Gore. Gore was joined at 
Friday's announcement by both organ donors and recipients. 
</P>
<P>
	The initiatives include a $13 million grant to community  
organizations to improve the donation request process, increase 
outreach to minority communities and implement school-based and 
workplace donor education programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also released new public service announcements to educate  
the public about organ donation and announced plans for a series of 
regional conferences with health care providers and transplant 
professionals to share strategies. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, President Clinton signed the Organ Donor Leave Act,  
which expands the current seven-day limit on leave for federal 
employees for organ donation. 
</P>
<P>
	The act was designed to encourage more people to become donors.  
Currently more than 65,000 Americans are awaiting a transplant. 
Last year, almost 5,000 died while waiting for donors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of these deaths could have been prevented if there were a  
sufficient supply of donor organs,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new law, federal employees serving as organ donors  
would receive up to 30 days of paid leave in addition to sick or 
annual leave. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
