<DOCNO> APW19990924.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 03:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vikings Dare Teams To Keep Blitzing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. (AP) -- Randy Moss wanted to work on beating  
the blitz, but he couldn't outrun the flu bug. 
</P>
<P>
	Moss was sent home sick Thursday and was added to the Minnesota  
Vikings' injury report as probable for Sunday's showdown at Green 
Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Before he felt queasy, Moss said the Vikings were going to have  
to start focusing more on making teams pay for blitzing them silly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once defensive coordinators saw a lot of the teams during the  
preseason blitz us, I think they felt that it might be a weak spot, 
a weak link in our offense,'' Moss said. ``And hopefully we'll pick 
it up, so I think we just got to ... practice better week in and 
week out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings are actually daring teams to keep it up, however.  
</P>
<P>
	``We like people to blitz,'' coach Dennis Green insisted. ``I  
think if you have the right receivers and you're on your game, then 
that's a way that you can strike very quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The problem for the Vikings (1-1) is they haven't been on top of  
their game yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, they set an NFL scoring record with a quick-strike  
offense that forced teams to respect the deep ball and not risk 
sending defensive backs and linebackers after the quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	Randall Cunningham had all day to throw the deep jump ball to  
Moss or Cris Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Minnesota is struggling to score points and run the ball  
effectively. Cunningham is spending too much time on the turf 
because his Pro Bowl-studded offensive line is getting beaten 
repeatedly, and Moss hasn't gotten into the end zone. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings expect to see plenty of blitzes Sunday at Green Bay,  
especially with new coach Ray Rhodes much more willing to send 
LeRoy Butler, the best blitzing safety in the NFL, after 
Cunningham. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are going to blitz,'' Green said. ``They're going to  
take their chances on whether or not they can cover Randy Moss and 
Cris Carter one-on-one. It helps to shut down the run game. And 
we've just got to do a better job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teams plotted ways to stop the Vikings all offseason and so far  
the blueprint is this: blitz more often and send defensive backs 
into deep coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	That's deprived Cunningham of the time and Moss of the room that  
allowed them to hook up for 10 touchdowns of 40 yards or more last 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams are going to do that, but we'll adjust pretty quick,''  
promised Cunningham, who also said he's going to get rid of the 
ball more quickly. ``I don't know what coach Green is going to do 
offensively, but I think we'll get to a point where we're 
outsmarting teams, because we know what teams are going to do 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the Vikings having scored just 17 points in each of their  
games so far after averaging 35 last year, Moss said he expects 
opponents to stick to what's working. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they'll approach the game as far as not letting me  
explode or have a career day. I think teams on down the line are 
going to take the same approach,'' Moss said. ``When you're 
doubling, tripling me, we've just got to find a way to make it 
happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Complicating matters is the knee injury to Pro Bowl right tackle  
Korey Stringer, who will play half the snaps at best with 
second-year pro Matt Birk getting the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	The Vikings didn't allow more than three sacks in any game last  
year, but yielded six against Oakland last Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If anything, it's going to make everyone concentrate that much  
more,'' center Jeff Christy said. ``Everyone's going to re-evaluate 
where they're at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive line coach Mike Tice said he had full confidence in  
Birk and agreed with Green that he'd love to see the steady diet of 
blitzes continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``We love the blitz,'' Tice said. ``I hate to say it, but we  
love the blitz because we've had a lot of big plays against the 
blitz. We used to beg for the blitz. Yeah, they're blitzing us, who 
cares? If we hit a couple big plays, they're not going to blitz us, 
you know? They'll be petrified.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
