<HEADLINE> F-22 Compromise Still Elusive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional negotiators are working toward a  
middle ground on the F-22 stealth fighter that will keep the 
program alive, but at a slower pace of production. 
</P>
<P>
	Talks were continuing behind the scenes over offers and  
counteroffers that were flying between the House and Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	One proposal on the table, offered by Senate negotiators, called  
for putting much of the $1.8 billion that had been earmarked by the 
Pentagon for buying the first six F-22s into more testing and 
research. 
</P>
<P>
	That could delay production by a year of a plane the Air Force  
hopes to have by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Jerry Lewis, R-Calif., chairman of the House Appropriations  
defense subcommittee suggested that House negotiators could accept 
a version of that proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	But not all Senate negotiators had signed on.  
</P>
<P>
	Since the House voted to halt the program in July as too costly,  
both the Pentagon and its prime contractor, Lockheed Martin Corp., 
have waged a furious lobbying campaign to save it. 
</P>
<P>
	But at the same time, ``the opposition has toughened in many  
ways,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., one of the negotiators. 
</P>
<P>
	Leahy said he expects the final compromise to at least save part  
of the program, which he likens to ``that second mortgage you never 
can quite get rid of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The F-22 debate comes as the House-Senate conference committee  
is working on a $267 billion military spending bill for the fiscal 
year that begins Oct. 1. Congressional still hope to have the 
measure completed by week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the House voted to halt the program in July as too costly,  
both the Pentagon and Lockheed have waged a furious lobbying 
campaign to save it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate had approved the full administration request for $1.8  
billion for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1 to buy six of the new 
planes. The House had voted to suspend production. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
