<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks-Suns Merger Is Mulled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Jerry Colangelo, the Phoenix sports entrepreneur  
who runs baseball's Diamondbacks and the NBA's Suns, is exploring 
the possibility of merging the teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a move would pair a young baseball franchise that is having  
record-setting success on the field but faces major debts with a 
basketball franchise that is one of the most successful financially 
in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners have been using such mergers recently to help them in  
negotiating broadcast and naming rights deals, streamlining 
overhead and even starting up their own sports broadcast networks. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're seeing unique partnerships and bundlings taking place,  
and this is the future,'' Colangelo said Thursday from San 
Francisco, where the Diamondbacks will try to clinch the NL West 
title against the Giants on Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``But this has nothing to do with anything immediate. I'm just  
listening and talking with people more than anything else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any decision is at least a year away, he said. The mergers add  
value in an era when the key to successful sports franchises isn't 
in ticket sales but media revenue. 
</P>
<P>
	``The advantages are mainly in marketing -- local television and  
radio revenues,'' Colangelo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo is majority owner of the Suns. He is managing general  
partner of the Diamondbacks, but only owns about 1 percent of the 
team. The rest is owned by 28 other investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diamondbacks' owners have invested $350 million already, and  
Colangelo went back to them for another $24 million to meet cash 
flow needs over the next year or so. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts describe the concept of combining franchises into one  
business as the ownership model of the future. The New York Yankees 
and New Jersey Nets are almost finished with just such a move. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about building sports conglomerates from the ground floor  
up, rather than a conglomerate buying a sports franchise and 
fitting it into the conglomerate,'' Dean Bonham, president of the 
Bonham Group, a Denver-based sports-business consulting firm, told 
The Arizona Republic. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo said the merger is just one of the options he is  
considering. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may seem very complicated on the outside, but basically  
when you merge assets, it's a matter of allocating values,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other words, the owners of the franchise with the most value  
would have the bigger percentage of ownership of the combined 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Any merger of the Diamondbacks and Suns ``would be heavily  
weighted toward the Suns because of our strong financial 
situation,'' Colangelo said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Colangelo did pursue the option of bundling the teams, his  
partners in both ventures would have to agree. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo spent $118.9 million on free agents in the  
Diamondbacks' offseason, although much of those salaries are 
deferred well into the future. He said the investment was necessary 
to make the team competitive in a hurry in order to keep attendance 
from falling off too much. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, season ticket sales declined by about 9,000. On the  
field, though, the tactic worked. The Diamondbacks are on the brink 
of being the first team to make the playoffs in just its second 
year of existence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
