<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Trying To Regroup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The New York Mets staggered into Veterans  
Stadium on Friday after being swept in their NL East showdown with 
Atlanta. Manager Bobby Valentine tried everything he could to help 
them forget the Disaster in Dixie. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team has been addressed,'' Valentine said before the Mets  
lost their fourth straight, 3-2 to the Philadelphia Phillies. ``It 
was succinct, I thought. I looked around and I didn't see anybody 
frowning and I didn't see anybody looking down about what I said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine addressed the team after Thursday's 6-3 loss in  
Atlanta. One of the Mets' sloppiest losses of the season came at 
the absolute worst time. The three-game sweep left New York four 
games behind the Braves in the NL East and only two games ahead of 
Cincinnati for the wild card. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Mets' seventh loss in nine games against their  
nemesis, and their 13th loss in 14 games at Turner Field. 
</P>
<P>
	So there was little doubt that Valentine sought to squelch any  
ideas in the minds of his players that they can't beat the Braves. 
They have three more games against Atlanta at Shea Stadium next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're good and they won,'' Valentine said he told his team.  
``We're good and we lost. They're not perfect, and neither are we. 
</P>
<P>
	``Luckily, they haven't beaten us thoroughly this year. They  
have beaten us more than we've beaten them. Luckily, we play them a 
lot more times this year. We'll see if there's doubt, won't we? 
That's what this is all about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Piazza, who hit his 38th homer off Greg Maddux on Thursday  
to set a club record with 118 RBIs, was cautious when asked about 
Valentine's talk. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think it was any different than any other postgame  
talk,'' Piazza said. ``Aside from anything that he said, as a team 
we've always felt like we need to improve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets were trying to regroup Friday night after collapsing in  
Atlanta late in the season for the second straight year. New York 
lost its final five games, when only one victory would have put 
them in a playoff for the NL wild card. Three of those losses came 
in the season-ending series at Turner Field. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final game of this series, the usually sure-handed Mets  
were undone by sloppy play. The best-fielding team in the majors 
made two costly throwing errors, both allowing runs to score. First 
baseman John Olerud, who made one of the errors, also failed to 
complete a pickoff when he couldn't get the ball out of his glove 
in the fifth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know what about mistakes?'' Valentine asked. ``They blew a  
double play and got picked off three times, but you know what? They 
hit a three-run homer and they won. What can you do?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine was still defending Rickey Henderson on Friday, too.  
Henderson hurt the Mets when he tried to score from first on 
Edgardo Alfonzo's double in the fifth. Henderson, hobbled by a 
tight hamstring, hesitated twice and ran through third-base coach 
Cookie Rojas' stop sign and was out easily at the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems to me that with Rickey, similar plays have happened  
about four times,'' Valentine said. ``He was safe the other three 
times. He was not safe, so it looked bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Henderson tested his hamstring before the game and was in the  
lineup against the Phillies, leading off and playing left field. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
