<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Seeks Great Lakes Protections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- A proposal announced Friday by the  
Environmental Protection Agency would prohibit the dumping of 
certain chemicals in parts of the Great Lakes and surrounding 
wetlands. 
</P>
<P>
	Each year, about 90,000 pounds of the most toxic chemicals,  
including mercury and PCBs, are discharged and diluted with the 
water of certain areas of the Great Lakes called mixing zones, the 
EPA says. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that when we protect the environment of the Great  
Lakes, we are protecting the health of our families and our 
economies,'' EPA administrator Carol Browner said to the 
International Joint Commission, formed to help the United States 
and Canada in decisions regarding shared waterways. 
</P>
<P>
	Browner proposed banning new mixing zones and phasing out the  
existing ones over 10 years in the Great Lakes basin, an area that 
encompasses the lakes and surrounding wetlands in eight states. 
</P>
<P>
	The chemicals, called bioaccumulative chemicals of concern, or  
BCCs, can move up the food chain, and will eventually affect 
humans, said Chuck Fox, EPA assistant administrator for water. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox estimated that there are about 300 mixing zones for BCCs in  
the basin, in industrial sections of rivers and at least a mile off 
the shore. ``Generally, people don't swim in this stuff,'' Fox 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would reduce by about 91 percent the 22 BCCs  
flowing into the Great Lakes from industry and municipal sewage 
treatment plants, Fox said. 
</P>
<P>
	An environmentalist say that while the EPA's proposal is good,  
it's overdue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing it's taken them this long to do something when  
they've known about it for so long -- and they're still willing to 
give industry 10 years,'' Eric Uram, of the Sierra Club, said 
before Browner's speech. ``What happens in the meantime is more 
chemicals entering the Great Lakes and potentially affecting our 
health.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governors of Indiana, Michigan, Minnesota and Wisconsin  
already have started the process of eliminating mixing zones for 
BCCs in the basin, said Ken Wiesner, an assistant to the water 
division administrator for the state Department of Natural 
Resources. 
</P>
<P>
	The Great Lakes states also include Illinois, New York, Ohio,  
Pennslyvania. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
