<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Keep Raising 'Soft Money' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As Democrats pushed to ban unlimited political  
contributions from businesses, unions and individuals, the party 
almost doubled the amount of so-called soft money it raised in the 
first six months of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic committees took in $26.4 million in unrestricted soft  
money contributions from January through June, up from $13.7 
million during the last comparable period, the first six months of 
1997. Republicans raised even more soft money -- $30.9 million -- in 
the first six months of the year, a 42 percent boost over 1997's 
$21.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But while most congressional Republicans oppose banning soft  
money, most House and Senate Democrats have lined up behind 
legislation to prevent parties from raising such unlimited 
contributions. 
</P>
<P>
	To the GOP, it reeks of hypocrisy. ``Bill Clinton and the  
Democrats preach about the evils of soft money by day and act like 
vacuum cleaners by night, sucking it all up,'' Republican National 
Chairman Jim Nicholson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson has made no secret of his support for soft money. At a  
private meeting of the House GOP in August, Nicholson and Rep. Tom 
Davis of Virginia, chairman of the National Republican 
Congressional Committee, argued that such a ban would leave the 
party's candidates vulnerable to unlimited expenditures by labor 
unions and other groups that back Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Republican-controlled House passed a ban on soft  
money, 252-177, on Sept. 14. Of 210 Democrats, 197 voted for the 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats say they can't afford to give up soft money while the  
Republicans are raking it in. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we should make it illegal, but we should make it  
illegal for everyone,'' said Rep. Martin Meehan of Massachusetts, 
lead Democratic sponsor of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Parties can raise soft money for get-out-the-vote drives and  
other party-building activities. Since the money is not raised 
under federal rules, it cannot be used directly to help elect 
candidates. Increasingly, however, Democrats and Republicans spend 
millions of dollars of soft money on issue advertisements designed 
to help their nominees without specifically urging a vote for or 
against a particular candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee more than  
quadrupled its soft money contributions over the first half of 1997 
-- nearly closing a historic gap with its Republican counterpart. 
The DCCC took in $9 million during the first six months of 1999, 
compared with $1.9 million during the same period two years 
earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRCC took in $9.4 million in soft money during the first six  
months of 1999, a 79 percent increase over the same period in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	DCCC Chairman Patrick Kennedy of Rhode Island said his committee  
has been criticizing House Republican policies to potential donors, 
while arguing that the Democrats will recapture the majority next 
fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to be back in the majority. Are you going to be  
with us or not?'' Kennedy said he tells prospective contributors. 
``All we need to do is get a fraction of what these people are 
giving to Republicans. They don't want the balance sheets to be so 
unbalanced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also topped Democrats in raising money under federal  
contribution limits. GOP committees took in $66.4 million, compared 
with $38.1 million for the Democrats. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 19:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
