<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Davis Still In Hunt for NFL Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Billionaire Marvin Davis remained in the game  
for an NFL franchise Friday without having to ante up again. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, who has approached the league about building a stadium at  
Hollywood Park, received an extension on a deadline for retaining 
his option on some 100 acres adjacent to the horse racing track. 
</P>
<P>
	He initially paid Hollywood Park Inc. $100,000 for the option.  
Renewing it through next March would cost him another $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The first option period was to have expired Friday. A  
spokeswoman for Davis said the extension was granted but would not 
disclose how long it runs. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' interest in the expansion team isn't the first time he  
has considered buying a sports franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	In previous years, he expressed interest in the Denver Broncos,  
the Dallas Cowboys and the Oakland Athletics, without consummating 
a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, reportedly weighing whether he would spend more than $1  
billion for a stadium and franchise fee, has come to be regarded as 
a window shopper who often walks away from deals. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his sports franchise quests, he also was involved  
in dead-end attempts to buy such companies as Carter Wallace and 
Mesa Inc., and the Desert Inn in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 74-year-old Davis has completed enough deals to put him  
in a tie for 63rd, with $3.5 billion, on Forbes magazine's list of 
richest Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	A shrewd sense of timing apparently has keyed much of his  
success; he made a lot of his money by selling oil properties 
before prices dropped. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mid-1980s, Davis also reportedly made $325 million when  
he sold Twentieth Century Fox to Rupert Murdoch's News Corp., and 
millions more when he sold the Beverly Hills Hotel to the Sultan of 
Brunei for $200 million after buying it a year earlier for $135 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis moved into contention for an NFL team after the league,  
which had been dealing exclusively with a backers of the Los 
Angeles Coliseum, opened the door for other LA groups or 
individuals to make proposals for the expansion franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	Houston is still considered the favorite to get the expansion  
team, which may be decided at the league meetings that begin with a 
franchise committee meeting Oct. 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Any serious bid by Davis would face several hurdles, including  
gaining the NFL's approval of Hollywood Park as a suitable site for 
a stadium, and approval of him as a prospective owner. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the Coliseum backers, construction tycoon Eli Broad,  
actually ranks ahead of Davis on Forbes' list; Broad tied for 48th 
with $4 billion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
