<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 11:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Turner Revitalizes Downtown Atlanta </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- With a new sports arena and a redesigned CNN  
Center that puts the news network in a fishbowl, Ted Turner is 
opening up his corner of the city and helping to make downtown a 
livelier place after dark. 
</P>
<P>
	``In 20 years this will be sort of like the Rockefeller Plaza of  
Atlanta,'' said Chris Nelson, a professor of city planning and 
public policy at Georgia Tech. 
</P>
<P>
	Philips Arena opened Sept. 18 next to CNN Center, which is, in  
turn, across the street from Centennial Olympic Park, the 
centerpiece of the 1996 Summer Games. The arena is the home of 
hockey's Thrashers and basketball's Hawks, both of which are owned 
by Turner. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the year, the makeover of CNN Center will be  
complete, with the tower's concrete facade replaced with green 
glass. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the two projects cost $250 million.  
</P>
<P>
	Urban planners -- even those who are howling about the huge,  
six-story Philips Arena sign -- say the CNN Center redesign should 
help transform downtown Atlanta from a place that's abandoned at 
quitting time to one where people shop, eat, play and live after 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The CNN building was erected about 25 years ago. When the CNN  
founder moved his news operation there in 1987, there were only 
scruffy parking lots across the street. 
</P>
<P>
	Those lots have since been replaced by the 21-acre Centennial  
Olympic Park, which is emerging as downtown's No. 1 public 
gathering spot, with its open green spaces, brick walkways and a 
fountain in the shape of the Olympic rings. 
</P>
<P>
	``When this complex was built in the 1970s, it was meant to wall  
off downtown,'' said Janet Marie Smith, president of Turner Sports 
and Entertainment. ``We want you to be able to stand on the park 
and literally be able to look through CNN Center.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the CNN Center atrium, giant video screens have been hung  
to show off each of Turner's networks. Glass walls give visitors a 
better look inside the guts of the CNN studios. A giant world map 
is being built into the atrium floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every city needs some place you can show off to your  
Midwestern cousins when they come to town,'' Ms. Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Philips Arena, the main concourse will be open daily for  
tourists to browse its shops and restaurants. Turnstiles will be 
installed before concerts and sports events. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the Olympics, Turner -- who lives in an apartment  
atop CNN Center with wife Jane Fonda -- made his stand downtown 
while others were packing up and moving to the suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``He could've left a long time ago. So it's to his credit that  
he has helped in this whole revitalization effort,'' said Leon 
Eplan, Atlanta's planning commissioner for 10 years before the 1996 
Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	But such praise turns to scorn when it comes to the giant  
promotional sign Turner is erecting across from Centennial Park. 
</P>
<P>
	At 55 feet tall and 150 feet wide, the sign will include a  
Philips Arena logo, a giant video screen and a 25-foot clock on a 
silver background that spells ``ATLANTA.'' Editorials in the 
Atlanta newspapers have denounced it as a gimmicky electronic 
freak. 
</P>
<P>
	``To put such an outsized, commercial sign there cheapens that  
space,'' Eplan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Turner officials defend the sign by pointing out that its main  
purpose is to hide the big parking garage behind it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 19:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
