<HEADLINE> Nichols Seeks New Trial Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Bombing conspirator Terry Nichols has asked the  
10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to decide whether he deserves a 
new federal trial in the Oklahoma City bombing case. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Richard Matsch upheld the verdict last week,  
ruling that Nichols had not proven that the outcome of his trial 
would have been different if some additional information from the 
FBI had been turned over to defense attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	The notice of appeal, filed Wednesday, does not say what grounds  
Nichols will raise before the appeals court. 
</P>
<P>
	Nichols was sentenced to life in prison for conspiracy and eight  
counts of involuntary manslaughter in the April 19, 1995, bombing 
of the federal building. The bombing killed 168 people and injured 
more than 500 others. 
</P>
