<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Men executed in Delaware, N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SMYRNA, Del. (AP) -- A man described by his lawyers as mentally  
retarded was executed by injection early Friday for the stabbing 
and beating death of an elderly greenhouse worker. 
</P>
<P>
	Willie Sullivan, 28, was pronounced dead at 12:24 a.m. He became  
the 10th person executed in Delaware since the state resumed 
capital punishment in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Friday, in North Carolina, Harvey Lee Green was executed by  
injection at 2:16 a.m. for the beating deaths of two people. The 
38-year-old was the first black person executed in that state since 
it restored the death penalty in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	The Delaware Board of Pardons refused to recommend commuting his  
death sentence on Tuesday. Sullivan's lawyers and family had argued 
that death was not justifiable because he is mentally retarded, 
with an IQ of 70, and has brain damage from Fetal Alcohol Syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	Sullivan admitted he went to a Frederica, Del., nursery on Dec.  
17, 1991, to rob Maurice Dodd, 78. He said he used a metal potting 
soil scoop to beat the man and dropped a concrete block on his 
chest as he lay on the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sullivan later insisted that he never stabbed Dodd. He said  
it was the work of an accomplice -- a claim investigators found no 
evidence to support. 
</P>
<P>
	Green was sent to death row for the killings of Sheila Bland, a  
dry cleaning store clerk, and Michael Edmundson, a customer. 
</P>
<P>
	Green's supporters contend he was a victim of racism during his  
trial because only one black person was on the jury that 
recommended the death penalty. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
