<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Lyric, Met Swapping Operas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Staging the world premiere of an opera is hard  
enough. Keeping it alive after that first production can be even 
harder. 
</P>
<P>
	Now two of America's leading opera companies are helping to  
solve the problem -- by swapping operas. 
</P>
<P>
	William Bolcom's version of Arthur Miller's play ``A View From  
the Bridge'' will have its premiere at Chicago's Lyric Opera on 
Oct. 9. Then it will get a second production, at the Metropolitan 
Opera in New York, in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The Met has an opera premiere this season, too, an adaptation of  
F. Scott Fitzgerald's novel ``The Great Gatsby,'' by John Harbison, 
on Dec. 20. Next season, it will be presented at the Lyric. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, Bolcom's first opera for Lyric, ``McTeague,'' was  
widely praised at its premiere in 1992 but has since been presented 
just one other place, at Indiana University. And even that is one 
more production than most new American operas receive, because of 
the expense and the difficulties of attracting audiences to new 
works once the excitement of the premiere has worn off. 
</P>
<P>
	The new arrangement wasn't exactly entered into as a trade, said  
Susan Mathieson, director of marketing and communications for the 
Lyric. 
</P>
<P>
	``To my knowledge, we just decided we wanted to do this piece,''  
she said. ``You have to plan so far in advance with big companies 
these days. I'm sure this has been on the books at least three 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Clark, spokesman for the Met, said Thursday: ``I don't  
think there was a trade. They're doing ours and we're doing theirs. 
I don't know when it was decided here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mathieson, speaking by telephone from Chicago, said, ``We won't  
announce our complete next season until the beginning of December. 
We can't wait to see how it flies at the Met. We've signed a cast 
but it hasn't been announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our history of new works is seven to 10 performances in a  
season. Because we have a large subscription audience, we schedule 
so that everybody who has a full series -- eight operas is a full 
series -- gets to see the new work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lyric has presented the second production of a Met premiere  
opera once before, John Corigliano's ``The Ghosts of Versailles,'' 
which bowed at the Met in 1991, opened at Lyric in 1995 and then 
returned to the Met in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The Met has not previously performed an opera that had its world  
premiere in Chicago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 09:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dancer Mignon Garland Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN PABLO, Calif. (AP) -- Mignon Garland, a dancer who carried on  
the legacy of Isadora Duncan in the United States, has died at the 
age of 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Garland, who died Sept. 15, was founder and director of the  
Isadora Duncan Heritage Society. 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan helped pioneer modern dance by turning away from ballet  
and looking to ancient Greece for inspiration. She died in 1927. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Garland, born in Brooklyn, N.Y., decided to devote her life  
to dance that year after attending a performance by Duncan's 
disciples. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1930s and 40s, Ms. Garland toured with the Minneapolis  
Symphony, danced in Moscow and New York, founded several dance 
companies and was dance editor of New Theater magazine. Later, she 
lived for many years in the San Francisco home where Ms. Duncan was 
born. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Garland helped drive a Duncan revival that began with the  
1977 centenary of her birth. She also trained many Duncan dancers 
performing today, including her granddaughter, Amy Baird Garlin, 
and Lori Belilove. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Garland is survived by son Victor Garlin, a sister and two  
granddaughters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 10:50:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Backs Timor Rights Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The United States and other countries today threw  
their weight behind European demands for an international inquiry 
into atrocities committed in East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft resolution was made by the European Union and their  
East European allies at an emergency session of the U.N. Human 
Rights Commission, called at the request of Portugal, East Timor's 
former colonial power. 
</P>
<P>
	``The international community will exert every effort to ensure  
that those responsible are brought to justice,'' said the draft 
proposal. It condemns the widespread violations of human rights and 
the activities of militias terrorizing the population, and 
expresses concern at the ``desperate humanitarian situation of the 
East Timorese population.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nobel Laureate and East Timor resistance leader Jose Ramos Horta  
told the 53-nation commission that if it failed to act, it would be 
``an accomplice to impunity, an accomplice to genocide and war 
crimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ramos Horta compared the devastation of East Timor to the  
``wasteland'' of Europe after World War II and the destruction of 
Kuwait after the Iraqi occupation. 
</P>
<P>
	``My sentiments to the Republic of Indonesia are the same as the  
Jews toward Nazi Germany and the Kuwaitis toward Iraq,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed inquiry could be the first step towards the  
establishment of a U.N. criminal tribunal for East Timor and is 
supported by U.N. High Commissioner for Human Rights Mary Robinson. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I have called for and what I discussed with (Indonesian)  
President (B.J.) Habibie is an international commission of inquiry, 
because before there can be a decision about an international 
tribunal I think it's important to gather in the facts, assess the 
degree of accountability,'' Robinson told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Ambassador George Moose told the meeting: ``The violent  
events that have occurred in East Timor require a systematic and 
credible investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is important to send a signal to all parts of the world  
that gross violations of human rights will not be tolerated,'' said 
Moose. 
</P>
<P>
	Mozambique, Slovenia, Norway and Switzerland made similar  
statements. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas, speaking at the United  
Nations in New York on Thursday, rejected suggestions for an 
international investigation, saying Indonesia itself should first 
look into allegations of human rights violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, which is meeting in special session for only the  
fourth time in its history, could decide to send investigators, and 
could also ask human rights envoys to report on the situation in 
East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishop Carlos Belo, who shared the Nobel Peace Prize with Ramos  
Horta in 1996, also called for an investigation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
