<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Third Man' Tops 100 British Films </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- ``The Third Man,'' a classic tale of intrigue set  
in post-World War II Vienna, has been named the best British film 
of the century in a poll announced this week by the British Film 
Industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Other films to make the top 10 ranged from Alfred Hitchcock's  
``The 39 Steps,'' at No. 4, to Nicholas Roeg's erotic chiller 
``Don't Look Now,'' at No. 8. 
</P>
<P>
	David Lean was responsible for three top citations, with ``Brief  
Encounter,'' ``Lawrence of Arabia'' and ``Great Expectations'' -- 
placing second, third and fifth, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Alec Guinness starred in more listed films than anyone else,  
with nine, while Michael Caine headlined in seven and Julie 
Christie starred in six. 
</P>
<P>
	The list was chosen by 1,000 people in the British film and  
television industries, who collectively cast 25,700 votes covering 
820 films. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Third Man,'' directed by Carol Reed, is a stylish 1949  
adaptation of a Graham Greene thriller. Filmed against a backdrop 
of ruined buildings and starring Orson Welles and Joseph Cotten, it 
contains some of cinema's most memorable black-and-white images. 
The background theme of zither music is so powerfully connected to 
the story that it is instantly recognized by anyone who has seen 
the film. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the results, the '60s were the evident golden age for  
British movies. Twenty-six films from that decade made the list, as 
opposed to 17 from the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one recent film made the top 10 -- ``Trainspotting,''  
director Danny Boyle's scabrous 1996 look at heroin addicts in 
Scotland. It is also movie that launched Ewan McGregor as an 
international name. 
</P>
<P>
	The Oscar-winning ``Shakespeare In Love,'' Shekhar Kapur's  
``Elizabeth'' and Ken Loach's ``My Name Is Joe'' were three other 
films from last year to make the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of the choices may surprise Americans, since they  
include such films as ``The English Patient,'' ``Sense and 
Sensibility,'' and ``Shakespeare In Love,'' all of which were made 
either largely or wholly with American money. 
</P>
<P>
	But for the purposes of the poll, the industry qualified as a  
British film any movie employing a substantial number of Britons. 
All three of the movies named above used British talent who went on 
to win Academy Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	While most of the films draw on original scripts, many are  
adaptations of novels and plays, reflecting Britain's rich literary 
heritage. Shakespeare, Dickens, Alan Bennett, and Graham Greene 
were among the authorial heavyweights to have made the list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
