<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of Scotland Bids for NatWest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Bank of Scotland PLC, casting itself as a tightly  
managed David out to conquer a flabby Goliath, on Friday launched a 
hostile $34.3 billion takeover bid for National Westminster Bank 
PLC. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest, which is three times bigger than Bank of Scotland,  
quickly rejected the offer, and its shares soared as analysts 
speculated that other bidders might join the pursuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the offer would represent Britain's biggest bank  
merger, ``It's not a knockout bid. It's feasible someone could come 
in with a higher bid,'' said David Liston, analyst at Capel Cure 
Sharp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think they're paying enough. It's distinctly  
opportunistic'', said John Tyce, banking analyst at SG Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Burt, chief executive of Bank of Scotland, said his  
company first approached NatWest about a merger in 1997 but NatWest 
wasn't interested. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bank of Scotland has been growing since then and NatWest has  
been doing the opposite,'' Burt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Burt said Bank of Scotland decided to move after NatWest made a  
$17.7 billion offer to buy Legal &AMP; General Group PLC, an insurer 
and pension provider. Bank of Scotland said its offer was 
contingent on NatWest dropping that bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``NatWest has a history of under-performance,'' said Sir John  
Shaw, governor of the Bank of Scotland. ``Its proposed acquisition 
of Legal &AMP; General does not address NatWest's long-term problem -- 
its relative inability to extract value from its core banking 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that the NatWest business will prosper as part of a  
well-managed, focused group and that this bank-to-bank merger will 
enable Bank of Scotland to utilize its proven management skills to 
unlock substantial value for both sets of shareholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest responded that the offer ``does not reflect the value of  
the NatWest franchise and the NatWest Group as a whole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Scotland's offer valued NatWest at $20.55 a British  
share, representing a 20 percent premium over the closing price 
Thursday on the London Stock Exchange. But amid expectations of 
even bigger bids, NatWest Bank shares soared 29 percent on the 
London Stock Exchange to the equivalent of $22.21. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest's U.S. shares rose 27.5 percent Friday on the New York  
Stock Exchange, surging $27.81 1/4 to close at $128.81 1/4 a share. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland shares were up 6.2 percent in London, where  
Legal &AMP; General shares fell 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, NatWest shareholders would receive 1.6 new Bank  
of Scotland shares plus notes for each NatWest share. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland said it intended to preserve NatWest's separate  
identity if its bid succeeds, but that it would sell noncore 
businesses and return cash to shareholders. It also said it 
expected the combined banks to be profitable from the start. 
</P>
<P>
	``This move is almost as defensive as it is aggressive; it's a  
good strategy play by a medium-sized bank,'' said Justin Urquhart 
Stewart, a strategist at Barclays Stockbrokers. 
</P>
<P>
	``One reason they're doing this is as a pre-emptive action; It  
moves their share price, it shows they're aggressive and gives out 
a clear message to anyone who may be thinking of it as a takeover 
target,'' Stewart said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland said its offer was an attractive alternative to  
NatWest's plans to acquire Legal &AMP; General. Some analysts 
criticized that deal as risky and expensive and shares in both 
companies fell after that deal was announced earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	In its offer Friday, Bank of Scotland insisted that NatWest drop  
the bid and it urged NatWest shareholders to vote against the Legal 
&AMP; General acquisition at an Oct. 6 shareholder meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I were a NatWest shareholder, I would prefer the Bank of  
Scotland proposal'' to the Legal &AMP; General bid, said Martin Cross, 
banking analyst at broker Teather &AMP; Greenwood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the proposal by Bank of Scotland to acquire NatWest is  
attractive enough to persuade NatWest shareholders to vote against 
the Legal &AMP; General deal''. 
</P>
<P>
	NatWest had assets of $306 billion and pretax profits of $3.5  
billion last year. It has 1,730 branches and 64,400 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland reported assets of $90 billion and pretax  
profits of $1.2 billion in 1998. It has 325 branches and 21,000 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Bank of Scotland backed out of a deal with  
U.S. religious broadcaster Pat Robertson to launch a telephone 
banking service in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	That deal died after Robertson, based in Virginia Beach, Va.,  
criticized Scotland as ``a rather dark land'' that tolerates 
homosexuality. On his ``700 Club'' broadcast, Robertson said, ``in 
Scotland, you can't believe how strong the homosexuals are. It's 
just unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Scotland apologized to its shareholders in June,  
saying it had been a mistake to get involved with Robertson. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
