<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Phenom on Stage at Ryder Cup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Two years ago, a young rookie of immense  
talent was supposed to help a U.S. team reclaim the Ryder Cup at 
Valderrama in Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	Tiger Woods went 1-3-1 instead, finding out in the process that  
playing for national pride isn't the same as playing for cash. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, the new phenom is on the other side. And how Sergio  
Garcia handles the pressure of his first Ryder Cup might be a key 
to whether the Europeans can retain the cup once again. 
</P>
<P>
	It won't take long to find out, with Garcia paired against Woods  
in alternate shot competition today as the 33rd Ryder Cup opens at 
The Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	The rivalry that got its start last month at the PGA  
Championship could be in full bloom by the time the cup is decided 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait,'' Woods said Thursday after the pairings were  
announced. ``I know my experience from the last Ryder Cup is 
definitely going to help me deal with the nerves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The matchup that golf fans wanted to see came early when  
captains on both sides picked Garcia and Woods for the second 
alternate shot foursome of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not a pure meeting, though, as Woods will share his shots  
with Tom Lehman and Garcia will alternate with Jesper Parnevik. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not what the media is speculating. I know they want to  
see us play head-to-head,'' Woods said. ``But it's not necessarily 
head-to-head. We have to rely directly on our partners now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Though not be head-to-head, the match is pretty good for Ryder  
Cup starters. Both Woods and Garcia figure to play in five matches 
each, giving them four more possibilities of being paired in the 
blind draws. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though it's a team format, Sergio and Tiger going at it  
is a golf fan's dream,'' Lehman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia said after the PGA that he wanted to play against Woods  
in the Ryder Cup. His focus now, though, has changed to simply 
winning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be nice,'' Garcia said. ``But what I have in my mind  
is to help the European team try to win the cup, and I don't care 
if I'm going to play with Tiger or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woods was a 21-year-old with less than a full year as a pro when  
he bore the weight of the American cause at Valderrama. 
</P>
<P>
	He played sporadically, though, and was routed 4 and 2 by  
Italy's Constantino Rocca in Sunday's singles in a match that might 
have given the United States the cup if he could have won. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just didn't hit the shots at the right time. I didn't make  
the putts,'' Woods said. ``But this year I'm coming into the 
tournament with more of a positive attitude and rightfully so. It 
suits my game because it is match play. I absolutely love it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia is the young rookie this time, a 19-year-old who won his  
way onto the European team in a burst of fine play after turning 
pro just after the Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	He plays with abandon, much like countryman Seve Ballesteros,  
and seemed to enjoy himself immensely when he got within a shot of 
Woods on the back nine at Medinah and nearly beat him for the PGA 
Championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have all seen his play,'' fellow Spaniard Jose Maria  
Olazabal said. ``For a guy that is 19 years old and has played 
five, six months as a professional, he has done a hell of a job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia is one of seven Ryder Cup rookies on the European team,  
which has lost the cup to the Americans only twice in the last 
seven competitions. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, David Duval is the only rookie on the American team  
-- and he's the No. 2 player in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval, though, has been on two President's Cup teams. One was a  
winning effort, the other ended in a loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think everybody understands what they're trying to  
accomplish this week,'' Duval said. 
</P>
<P>
	Four days of attending team dinners and various entertainment  
events ended Thursday with opening ceremonies under breezy and 
sunny conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	That left players with only one final night of worrying about  
the excruciating pressure of the Ryder Cup and what kind of shot 
they might hit off the first tee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited and ready to get started,'' Hal Sutton said.  
``We've been here long enough practicing. It's time to get this 
thing underway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olazabal, who was left out of the first morning's matches after  
telling European captain Mark James that his game wasn't good 
enough for the alternate shot format, planned to spend his time 
instead talking to Garcia and other rookies about how to handle 
first tee jitters. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time in six Ryder Cups that Olazabal has missed  
a match. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're going to be nervous on the first tee like everybody  
else,'' Olazabal said. ``But mainly they need to be patient. Don't 
try to push things around. Just try to be patient and play the 
game.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
