<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Defends Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Seeking to prop up a faltering economy,  
Colombia's central bank sold U.S. dollars Friday to defend the peso 
against speculators, while finance officials negotiated a major 
loan agreement with the International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	President Andres Pastrana is counting on the loan to help him  
reverse Colombia's worst economic decline since the 1930s. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colombian peso closed at 1994.5 to the dollar after the  
central bank sold $182.8 million worth of currency reserves. 
Friday's intervention brought to more than $400 million the amount 
the bank spent this week to defend the peso. 
</P>
<P>
	The currency has lost a third of its value against the dollar in  
the past twelve months, despite a government policy -- widely 
ridiculed by economists -- of trying to maintain the peso within a 
controlled trading range. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Finance Minister Juan Camilo Restrepo and Central  
Bank President Miguel Urrutia were in Washington trying to seal an 
expected $3 billion loan from the IMF. 
</P>
<P>
	Colombia's economic slide is aggravating tensions in a country  
whose steady economy had been a stabilizing force during decades of 
political violence. The economy contracted by nearly 7 percent in 
the first half of the year, and unemployment is about 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to a business group Thursday, Pastrana said the economy  
was ``finishing its desert crossing.'' Private economists are 
dubious, citing a large budget deficit, lagging industrial 
production figures and weak coffee production. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
