<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-POWs in Belgrade Leaving Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two American soldiers who were formerly  
prisoners of war in Yugoslavia are getting out the Army. 
</P>
<P>
	Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone and Spc. Steven Gonzales had run  
into red tape after their resignations were cleared quickly through 
Army Command in Europe in July. The paperwork sat at the Pentagon 
for 1 1/2 months, and top Army officials there could not tell them if 
they would be allowed to leave. 
</P>
<P>
	They were given the go-ahead this week. ``Their resignations  
have been approved. It is official,'' Army spokeswoman Martha Rudd 
said Thursday from the Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
	During their 32 days of captivity, Stone and Gonzales, along  
with a third soldier, Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, endured beatings, 
interrogations and deaths threats. The three Americans were 
released May 2, seven weeks before the NATO bombings in Yugoslavia 
ended, and welcomed home as heroes. 
</P>
<P>
	The experience changed their priorities, turning the soldiers  
who had re-enlisted into men intent on quitting the Army so they 
could get college educations and rebuild their lives, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers said their division commander and other Army  
officials had told them after their captivity that they would get 
their choice of assignments -- including resigning from the 
active-duty military. 
</P>
<P>
	Their release date was set for Oct. 22, Rudd said, but the Army  
could allow the soldiers to leave earlier if they have vacation 
time remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're ecstatic. The family is very happy,'' said the  
mother-in-law of Stone's sister, Dorcas Reliford, from her home in 
Riley Center, Mich., northeast of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's what he needs -- to get on with his life,'' said Manny  
Ramos, Stone's brother-in-law, in Lapeer, Mich. ``We're happy for 
them both. They went through a rough time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers were ambushed on March 31 by about 20 Serb soldiers  
near the Macedonian border, where they were on lightly armed patrol 
in a Humvee vehicle. 
</P>
<P>
	During their first week of captivity, the soldiers were hooded  
and handcuffed with legs bound, forced to lie on one side without 
moving except to eat their one meal or make their only bathroom 
trip for the day, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone and Gonzales, both in Germany with the 1st Infantry  
Division, could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	But they have said they are eager to return to their home states  
and begin to rebuild their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, 25, said he plans to join the National Guard in Michigan  
and attend a state college. Gonzales, 22, said he wants to attend 
Texas A&AMP;M and join the reserves or National Guard. Both soldiers 
have been offered scholarships. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez, 24, has been granted a transfer to Fort Irwin near  
Barstow, Calif., where he will finish his time in the Army near 
relatives in Los Angeles before planning to go to college. He 
transfers on Oct. 3. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
