<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 13:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Gives NATO Commander Citation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For the second time in recent weeks, the  
Pentagon had a surprise for Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO 
commander who oversaw the alliance's successful air war over 
Kosovo. But Friday's was more pleasant than word Clark got in late 
July that he would be leaving his post early. 
</P>
<P>
	This time it was what Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon called a  
``surprise citation'': a Defense Distinguished Service Medal 
awarded Clark by Defense Secretary William Cohen in a private 
ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	The medal is the Pentagon's highest noncombat award. Norman  
Schwarzkopf, the retired Army general, received one for commanding 
allied forces in the 1991 Persian Gulf War, as did Joint Chiefs of 
Staff Chairman Gen. Henry H. Shelton for leading American troops in 
the near-invasion of Haiti in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The official citation accompanying Clark's award praised him for  
``decisive leadership and sound policy decisions'' and cited his 
``diplomatic, political and military acumen as well as his personal 
command presence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It has been reported that Clark's behind-the-scenes advocacy of  
preparing for a possible NATO ground invasion of Kosovo was a 
source of friction with Cohen and Shelton, who were reluctant to 
send in troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark was told in a surprise phone call from Shelton in late  
July that he would be leaving his post as NATO supreme commander 
and as commander of the U.S. European Command two months early next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	It has been widely reported -- but denied by Cohen and President  
Clinton -- that Clark was forced out early because of 
dissatisfaction with how he prosecuted the war over Kosovo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
