<DOCNO> APW19990924.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 14:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hospitals Treating Floyd Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina residents are keeping  
emergency room doctors busy with cuts, bites, stings, diarrhea and 
nausea as they clean up in the wake of Hurricane Floyd. 
</P>
<P>
	People are fumbling with chainsaws, bees and mosquitoes are  
swarming, and floodwaters are teeming with bacteria, sewage and 
chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been quite busy, day and night,'' Dr. Cathy Dover, an  
emergency medicine physician at Lenoir County Memorial Hospital, 
said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, especially due to the flooding, we are seeing more nausea  
and diarrhea, from drinking contaminated water, most likely. We're 
also seeing a lot of rashes, poison ivy, a lot of fire ant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sewage treatment plants and lagoons of hog waste have overflowed  
and contaminated drinking water supplies. Farm and industrial 
chemicals have also flowed into the water. In some places, people 
will have to drink bottled water or boil tap water for weeks to 
come. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, there have been no outbreaks of infectious disease. The  
federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention is helping the 
state Health Department keep watch so that they can stamp out an 
outbreak as soon as it happens. 
</P>
<P>
	Nash General Hospital doctors have treated two snakebites. At  
Pitt County Memorial Hospital, doctors are seeing more people stung 
by bees as they try to clear away brush and other debris. Other 
patients have cut or punctured themselves with chainsaws and other 
things and have gotten tetanus shots to ward off infection. 
</P>
<P>
	A big problem is expected to emerge over the weekend --  
mosquitoes, which breed in standing water and can spread deadly 
encephalitis to animals and humans. Planes are scheduled to start 
spraying pesticides late next week. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, mold growing in soggy furniture and carpeting could  
worsen allergies and asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of thousands of dead hogs, chickens and turkeys pose a  
health threat because they attract flies. Incinerators are being 
used to burn the carcasses, but many areas with dead livestock 
remain blocked by water. 
</P>
<P>
	State health officials are trying to stop flies from spreading  
by sprinkling piles of carcasses with insecticides that kill 
maggots. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
