<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AL Umpire Suspended Three Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Shulock became the second umpire to be  
disciplined this season when he was suspended by the American 
League today for three games for his ``display of temper'' in a 
game this week. 
</P>
<P>
	AL president Gene Budig, in his first major decision since being  
told his position was being terminated by commissioner Bud Selig, 
suspended Shulock for the final three games his crew is to work 
this season and fined him an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The penalties were levied, Budig said, for Shulock's ``overly  
aggressive behavior, display of temper, inappropriate remarks and 
physical contact'' with Tampa Bay catcher Mike DeFelice during and 
following the Devils Rays' game against the Anaheim Angels on 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock apparently became upset with DeFelice during the third  
inning of the Angels' 10-5 victory, a game in which the Devil Rays 
complained about the umpire's ball and strike calls. 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble began when Devils Rays pitcher Wilson Alvarez threw  
a fastball that struck Shulock in the mask. DeFelice barely raised 
his mitt to catch the pitch, and the ball squarely struck Shulock. 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock, unhurt, straightened up and slowly headed toward the  
mound. DeFelice caught up with the umpire as Tampa Bay manager 
Larry Rothschild came out of the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock and Alvarez argued briefly, but the umpire did not eject  
the pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	After the game, Shulock said, ``The more I think about it, I  
think he (Alvarez) did it intentionally. I can't prove it, but I'm 
upset, and I have a right to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the season, National League umpire Tom Hallion was  
suspended for three games without pay for allegedly bumping 
Colorado catcher Jeff Reed and pitching coach Milt May. 
</P>
<P>
	Terry Tata, working the game with Hallion, denied Hallion had  
made contact with Reed and May. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball officials couldn't recall another suspension of an  
umpire for an on-field dispute. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 16:30:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI WorldCom May Buy Sprint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Will three be a charm for MCI WorldCom?  
</P>
<P>
	The nation's second biggest long-distance company has failed  
twice this year to acquire a wireless phone company. Now MCI 
WorldCom is said to be eyeing Sprint, the No. 3 long-distance 
company and parent of the Sprint PCS mobile phone business. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom and Sprint both declined to comment following a  
report on Friday in The Wall Street Journal saying the companies 
have discussed a merger. 
</P>
<P>
	If MCI WorldCom can bring Sprint to the altar, the merger would  
make a stronger No. 2 in long distance to AT&AMP;T Corp. and finally 
give WorldCom a foothold in the fast-growing wireless business. 
Sprint PCS has 4 million wireless customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not surprised that MCI WorldCom is making this move  
because of the void in their wireless space. Sprint would give them 
the capability,'' said Liza Henderson, a director with TeleChoice 
Inc., a Boston-based consulting company. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, MCI WorldCom made an overture to acquire  
AirTouch Communications, but was trumped by Vodafone PLC of 
Britain. MCI WorldCom then started negotiating with Nextel 
Communications, but those talks fell apart in May in a dispute over 
price. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after, MCI WorldCom chief executive Bernard Ebbers told  
investors he expected to get into the wireless business within a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Ebbers is worried that another big merger like last year's  
acquisition of MCI, paid for by issuing billions of dollars worth 
of new stock, will dilute the value of MCI WorldCom's shares. 
</P>
<P>
	But his delays may prove costly because the explosive growth of  
the wireless business is a popular theme on Wall Street. At last 
count, the number of wireless customers in the United States 
totaled 79 million, up from 16 million in 1993, according to the 
Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Notably, Nextel's stock has nearly doubled to about $65 a share  
since talks with MCI WorldCom ended. And last week, Bell Atlantic 
struck an agreement to acquire the U.S. mobile phone network of 
Vodafone AirTouch in a deal that will create the nation's largest 
wireless phone company with 20 million customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, MCI WorldCom and Sprint would control about 30 percent  
of the U.S. consumer long-distance market, still far behind AT&AMP;T's 
60 percent share. 
</P>
<P>
	No deal between MCI WorldCom and Sprint appears imminent, and  
any alliance would face tough scrutiny from regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Another obstacle could come from France Telecom and Germany's  
Deutsche Telekom AG, which each own 10 percent of Sprint and are 
partners with Sprint in Global One, a struggling international 
venture. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint, based in Westwood, Kan., has a stock market value of  
nearly $40 billion, while its PCS wireless business, which is 
represented by a separate tracking stock, is valued at about $33 
billion. The market value for MCI WorldCom, based in Clinton, 
Miss., is about $151 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's trading, MCI WorldCom fell $2.37 1/2 per share to  
$76.12 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. Sprint's stock rose $2.87 1/2 to 
$54 and Sprint PCS fell $1 to $73.50, both on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
