<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Deck Cleaner Being Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The possibility of eye or skin injuries has  
forced the recall of some 420,000 bottles of Olympic Deck Cleaner. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission says jugs of the  
cleaner may be sealed with caps that dangerously affect the air 
pressure inside the container. 
</P>
<P>
	Caps used by the manufacturer can permit air pressure to build  
up and be expelled once the lids are removed, the commission said 
Thursday. Contact with the cleaner can cause eye damage or skin 
irritation. 
</P>
<P>
	A consumer and three stores have contacted the cleaner's  
manufacturer, PPG Architectural Finishes, about bulging or seeping 
containers but no injuries were reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled Olympic Deck Cleaner was sold in plastic one- and  
2.5-gallon containers with green caps. Jugs with beige-colored caps 
were not affected. 
</P>
<P>
	The recalled deck cleaners have batch codes beginning with 06C,  
07C, 08C, 09C, 10C, 11C, 12C, 01D, 02D, 03D, 04D, 05D and 06D. They 
were sold at home improvement centers, hardware stores and lumber 
yards nationwide from June 1998 through June 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers with the unused containers should not open them. They  
may call PPGAF at (888) 774-7332 between 8 a.m. and 5 p.m. EDT 
weekdays for information about getting a free replacement cap. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
