<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Moseley-Braun New Zealand Bound? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Barring any last-minute hitches, controversial  
former Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun appears on her way to becoming the 
next U.S. ambassador to New Zealand. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman David Leavy said Friday he did not know if  
the final green-light from the New Zealand government had been 
received for Moseley-Braun's nomination. That would be the last 
step before President Clinton would make the formal announcement of 
her as his choice for the post. 
</P>
<P>
	Moseley-Braun did not immediately return a message left at her  
Chicago home. But earlier this month, she said she was thrilled at 
the prospect of taking the job. ``I just would love it,'' she said. 
``It sounds like a magical place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Illinois Democrat became the nation's first black female  
senator in 1992, but was defeated in her 1998 re-election bid by 
Republican Peter Fitzgerald, who used his personal wealth to attack 
her on several controversies that had surrounded her during her 
term. She was heavily criticized for a 1996 visit to a Nigerian 
dictator and never-proven allegations that she used 1993 campaign 
funds to pay for personal luxuries. 
</P>
<P>
	She was unsuccessful despite the White House's eagerness to see  
her win. Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and first lady Hillary 
Rodham Clinton each headlined several fund-raisers and campaigned 
repeatedly for Moseley-Braun for more than a year leading up to the 
election. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House first raised the New Zealand ambassadorship with  
her last December, shortly after her loss. 
</P>
<P>
	Since leaving office, she has spent time on the lecture circuit  
and worked part-time for the Clinton administration's push to use 
more federal dollars to rebuild public school buildings. The 
$56-an-hour job for the Education Department involves giving 
speeches to boost the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Moseley-Braun was the lead supporter in Congress of a bill to  
provide $22 billion to build and modernize 5,000 schools nationwide 
over two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambassadorial nominations must be approved by the Senate.  
</P>
<P>
	The current U.S. ambassador, Josiah Beeman, is nearly two years  
beyond his term, but has stayed as a favor to Clinton. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
