<DOCNO> APW19990924.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 22:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veto Raises Questions About Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton bundled his veto of the $792  
billion Republican tax cut bill with a call to Congress for a 
year-end compromise on spending, Medicare, Social Security, debt 
repayment and -- finally -- limited middle class tax relief. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a suggestion for a summit that GOP leaders hope to avoid.  
</P>
<P>
	``If he wants to engage us he hasn't given any indication,''  
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., responded coolly, 
shortly after Clinton's veto ceremony Thursday. Lott said he has 
spoken with the president only once since mid-July, and that was to 
discuss East Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., renewed the Republican  
determination to put the tax relief argument aside for the time 
being. 
</P>
<P>
	For now, the GOP plan is to pass the regular spending bills  
needed to keep the government functioning. Anticipating a clutch of 
vetoes, they will then challenge Clinton to say how he proposes to 
pay for higher spending without raising taxes or dipping into the 
Social Security trust fund. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to take money out of Social Security. We're  
going to balance the budget. We're going to give him a budget that 
he can sign or veto, and tell us why. And we're not going to raise 
taxes on the American people,'' Hastert said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans' decision to avoid the sort of complex,  
multi-issue negotiations that Clinton suggested stems from both 
fear and hope. 
</P>
<P>
	It's an article of faith among Republicans that they have been  
outmaneuvered time and again by Clinton in year-end negotiations. 
They still bear the political scars of two government shutdowns in 
the winter of 1995-1996. They also recall the massive spending 
increase they swallowed in last fall's closed-door negotiations 
with the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	For his part, Lott emphatically told fellow Republicans at a  
recent closed-door meeting that there will be no summit with the 
White House. Any vetoed spending bill would be resolved by the 
lawmakers whose committee assignments give them jurisdiction, and 
White House aides would wait outside, said sources who attended the 
meeting and spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The hope behind the Republican strategy is that the tax cut  
issue will work in the GOP's favor in the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous outside advisers, including former Republican National  
Chairman Haley Barbour, have urged Hastert and Lott privately to 
resist any temptation to reduce the tax cut to gain Clinton's 
signature. That deprives Vice President Al Gore of any part in a 
Rose Garden signing ceremony, the theory goes, and gives Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush, the front-running GOP presidential candidate, 
plenty of leeway to craft his own economic platform. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll tell you, this Congress is not going to throw in the  
towel on tax relief for the American people,'' Hastert told 
reporters Thursday. But aides said he was referring to next year, 
when Republicans may well produce another large tax cut -- and 
another veto stand-off -- closer to the election. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's message was different, even as he denounced a  
``bloated'' tax cut bill he was rejecting. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the days ahead, I will ask the Republican majority to work  
with me to fulfill these fundamental obligations'' relating to 
Social Security, Medicare and other issues, he said. ``If we can 
work together to meet these objectives, we can also work together 
to pass tax relief we can afford -- affordable, middle-class tax 
relief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans can ill afford politically to snub the president, so  
they'll try to refocus the debate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll be glad to work together on tax relief, but we're not  
going to tie it in with spending,'' said Rep. Tillie Fowler of 
Florida, a member of the House GOP leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton has more weapons at his disposal than mere rhetoric  
as he seeks to advance his objectives. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House upped the ante Friday when Clinton's aides  
relayed word that he would veto a minor tax bill extending certain 
politically popular tax breaks, contending they would soak up a 
portion of the budget surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is becoming painfully clear that the only specific priority  
for the president this fall is higher and higher Washington 
spending,'' said Rep. Bill Archer of Texas, chairman of the House 
Ways and Means Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether Archer is right or wrong about that, he and fellow  
Republicans will likely soon find themselves discussing taxes and 
spending with Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: David Espo is chief congressional correspondent  
for The Associated Press. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
