<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Show To Have Quick Cable Rerun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If you miss an episode of ``Once and Again,''  
ABC's new drama about divorced parents gingerly starting a new 
romance, you can catch it on cable's Lifetime network just three 
nights later. 
</P>
<P>
	The quick rerun results from a deal between the two networks,  
the most dramatic sign of a looming revolution in TV viewing and 
one likely to force some bruising business battles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once and Again'' aired its premiere Tuesday to strong critical  
acclaim and ratings. The same episode was scheduled for Lifetime 
Friday at 11 p.m. This weekly pattern will continue until the end 
of the series' limited opening run of six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Many in the TV industry predict such ``repurposing'' is the wave  
of the future. With TV networks in the hands of a few large 
corporations, deals to air programs at different times on different 
channels may proliferate. 
</P>
<P>
	Affiliates of the major broadcast networks strongly object to  
the practice, fearing they will lose viewers -- and advertising 
dollars -- if people have more than one choice of when to see a 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once and Again'' is a perfect fit for Lifetime's  
female-dominated audience, said Dawn Tarnofsky-Ostroff, the 
network's executive vice president for entertainment. It's also a 
perfect business fit: the show is produced by Touchstone 
Television, which is owned by the Walt Disney Co., which owns ABC. 
Disney also owns half of Lifetime. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet it's so touchy with affiliates that ABC didn't make its own  
announcement of the arrangement Friday and would not make 
executives available to talk about it. 
</P>
<P>
	After tense negotiations, ABC agreed this summer to wait at  
least six months or until after the TV season to ``repurpose'' most 
of its shows. But ABC retained the right to use up to one-quarter 
of its prime-time shows this way. ``Once and Again'' is the first. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC last winter agreed to let the USA Network show episodes of  
NBC's new series, ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit,'' two weeks 
after they are first broadcast. It was an arrangement made under 
some duress: NBC agreed to share when the producer threatened to 
stop making ``Law &AMP; Order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There are two schools of thought on how reruns affect original  
episodes of series. Some fear viewers become less interested in 
original shows when they can see other episodes elsewhere, but 
others think they help drum up interest for a program. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, ``Law &AMP; Order'' drew its largest season-opening  
audience this week since its 1990 premiere, a development NBC 
partly credits to frequent reruns of old episodes on the A&AMP;E 
network. 
</P>
<P>
	``The marketing value of having shows being viewed on more than  
one network in more than one time period is really quite surprising 
to people,'' Tarnofsky-Ostroff said. 
</P>
<P>
	After six weeks ``Once and Again'' will be supplanted by ``NYPD  
Blue'' when it returns to its customary Tuesday night time slot. 
The network then may place ``Once and Again'' elsewhere on the 
prime-time schedule -- or the series may go away until January. 
</P>
<P>
	Under no circumstances will Lifetime show original episodes  
before ABC, Tarnofsky-Ostroff said. And she said the network has 
not discussed picking up the series if it's eventually canceled by 
ABC. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
