<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flood Victims Return to Ruin, Mud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. (AP) -- Hosing down grime on the tables and  
chairs in his restaurant, which was underwater earlier this week, 
Mickey Bailey vowed to rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
	For 75 years, Bob Melton's has been a Rocky Mount institution.  
</P>
<P>
	``They'll figure if Bob Melton's can come back, they all can,''  
said Bailey, the building's owner. 
</P>
<P>
	The barbecue restaurant on the banks of the Tar River was among  
30,000 buildings damaged across eastern North Carolina after 
Hurricane Floyd tore through the state last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew there would be flooding,'' Bailey said. ``We didn't  
know it would be the flood of the millennium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Folks like Bailey returned Thursday to buildings submerged in up  
to 20 inches of rain from Floyd, and found everything a mess: 
filthy, soaked carpeting, bedding and chairs; ruined keepsakes, and 
mud everywhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Those able to return were the exception, not the rule.  
</P>
<P>
	Across the soggy, 18,000-square-mile region, more than 700 roads  
remained flooded, although sections of Interstate 40 submerged when 
Floyd passed through Sept. 16 were re-opened. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 42 people have been confirmed dead in North Carolina.  
Altogether, the storm killed at least 70 people from the Bahamas to 
New England, with the death toll expected to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Rescue workers continued searching by helicopter and boat  
Thursday for those still missing since Floyd hit a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	They hoped most would turn up safe in shelters or at the homes  
of friends and relatives, but braced themselves for more dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're preparing for many,'' Manning said. ``We just know from  
some of the circumstances ... we may have casualties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people remained in shelters, though more displaced  
families began moving into a trailer village that opened Wednesday 
outside Rocky Mount. Another temporary housing community is planned 
near Greenville. About 1,000 families are expected to occupy the 
villages, and state officials say other villages may open 
elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who could return to their homes were unsure about the  
future. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know if I'm coming back or not,'' said Carson Taylor,  
whose relatives and friends sloshed through his home, carrying out 
mattresses and chairs in a Rocky Mount community of 22 homes about 
100 yards from the Tar. ``Everyone says they're not coming back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Kinston, flooding worsened Thursday and 400 people fled their  
homes as the Neuse River crested at twice its flood stage, while 
the still-rising Lumber River pushed water into the town of Fair 
Bluff. 
</P>
<P>
	National Guard helicopters continued to airlift bottled water  
and supplies to stranded crossroads communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Jim Hunt was in Washington on Thursday, lobbying for more  
federal disaster aid. Losses are expected to surpass Hurricane 
Fran's $6 billion in 1996, with farm losses alone accounting for 
more than $1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have tens of thousands of homes completely lost,'' Hunt  
said. ``We have schools that will be closed for another month or 
two, businesses that are ruined, and the farms of eastern North 
Carolina are devastated. We absolutely cannot recover without a 
great deal of help from our government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd continues to cause problems in other states, too.  
</P>
<P>
	Spots on 15 primary roads and 132 secondary roads in  
southeastern Virginia were still closed Thursday due to high water, 
debris and damage, according to the state Department of 
Transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	Juanita Ellis, who lives near Williamsburg, said her road was  
washed out by flooding and now is barricaded. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just to get a loaf of bread you have to go 15 or 20 minutes  
out of your way,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
