<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Red Sox Release Veteran Pitcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Mark Portugal, recently removed from the Boston  
Red Sox starting rotation, was released Friday night with just nine 
games left and a playoff berth likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``We released Mark Portugal. We felt it was the best thing for  
the organization,'' Red Sox manager Jimy Williams said after a 1-0 
loss to the Baltimore Orioles. 
</P>
<P>
	He refused to elaborate and Portugal didn't comment.  
</P>
<P>
	But several of Portugal's ex-teammates appeared upset that a  
pitcher who had started 27 of his 31 games and was second on the 
team with 150 1-3 innings would be released so late in the season 
with Boston holding a comfortable lead over Oakland in the 
wild-card race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a shame,'' designated hitter Reggie Jefferson  
said. ``You hate to see a guy stay here all year and then get 
released with (nine) games to go. It doesn't make any sense.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand why now, but I don't know. I couldn't tell  
you,'' Nomar Garciaparra said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I should really comment on that right now,''  
said Bret Saberhagen, who pitched seven strong innings in Friday 
night's loss. ``It just hit me. That's something that we'll have to 
deal with. It's an inside thing. I'm kind of surprised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Portugal was 7-12 with a 5.51 ERA and allowed 28 homers. He had  
lost four consecutive decisions since his last victory on Aug. 4 
against Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	He made his last start Sept. 11 in an 11-10 win in New York over  
the Yankees. He allowed four runs and seven hits in four innings. 
Since then, he had been used only twice, pitching three innings in 
relief. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Sox signed Portugal, 36, as a free agent after he went  
10-5 last year with Philadelphia. He had been signed through 1999 
with an option for 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier in the season, Portugal left the team briefly and  
considered retirement to spend more time with his children. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
