<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 03:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wolverines Must Slow Dayne </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADISON, Wis. (AP) -- The Michigan Wolverines held Syracuse to 59  
rushing yards last week. If they can do the same to Wisconsin's Ron 
Dayne, they'll shift the balance of power in the Big Ten and the 
Heisman Trophy race. 
</P>
<P>
	No. 4 Michigan visits Camp Randall Stadium on Saturday. The  
Wolverines will try to repeat last year's performance against the 
20th-ranked Badgers' dominating tailback, who managed only 53 yards 
in Wisconsin's only loss of the year. Wisconsin went on to win the 
Big Ten title. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows he's a load, he's a big guy, he's powerful,''  
said Michigan linebacker James Hall. ``Up front we're going to try 
to get him before he gets started, try to get him behind the line 
of scrimmage. Once he gets in the secondary, that's when he does 
his thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Dayne is serious about winning the Heisman, this game would  
be a good time to start proving it. A loss to Michigan or Ohio 
State next week will kill the Badgers' already slim chances of 
contending for the national title, the main reason Dayne came back 
to Wisconsin for his senior year. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been solid but unspectacular after three games, during  
which he moved into sixth place on the NCAA's career rushing list. 
But last week he was unable to prevent the Badgers from suffering 
an embarrassing loss to Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne has been good, but he'll have to be great at some point in  
order to win the big trophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking at it as a big game for me and for the team,''  
Dayne said. ``After losing last week, we have something to make up 
for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The stage is set for Dayne to have a breakout game. With no  
other marquee matchups on the college football schedule this week, 
the eyes of Heisman voters will be focused on Madison. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne plays at about 252 pounds. That makes him heavier than  
seven starters on Michigan's defense, but the Wolverines (3-0) say 
they can stop him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I admit, once he gets going, it's a struggle to bring him  
down,'' senior linebacker Ian Gold said. ``But the bigger they are, 
the harder they fall. We'll go for his legs. It's that simple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their undefeated record and lofty ranking, the  
Wolverines are dealing with the puzzling disappearance of their 
offense, particularly their running game. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan averaged just 155.4 rushing yards per game last season,  
the school's lowest average since 1963. The Wolverines have just 
377 rushing yards this year, including a dismal 121 on 36 attempts 
against Syracuse. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course the Badgers let Michigan accumulate a season-high 257  
yards on the ground during the Wolverines' 27-10 win over Wisconsin 
in Ann Arbor last season. 
</P>
<P>
	Tailback Anthony Thomas rushed for 102 yards against the Badgers  
last year and 97 last week against Syracuse but no solid second 
option has emerged in the Michigan backfield. 
</P>
<P>
	That lack of depth could be a problem against the Badgers, whose  
rapidly improving defense would love to make its reputation against 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to stop the run,'' said Wisconsin defensive  
coordinator Kevin Cosgrove. ``That's one of the things we didn't do 
against them last year. We did a poor job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week's 17-12 loss at Cincinnati was the only reminder the  
Badgers (2-1) should ever need that Dayne cannot carry the team to 
victory alone. Dayne racked up 231 yards but he also fumbled in the 
Bearcats' end zone, his first turnover in 336 carries. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne missed several series while nursing a first-quarter  
sprained ankle, but he said the injury won't limit him against 
Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ron's been scrutinized more than any athlete, particularly  
here,'' said Wisconsin offensive coordinator Brian White. ``Every 
game's a litmus test for the Heisman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One Badger will be severely constrained by injury, however.  
Coach Barry Alvarez may watch the game from the press box because 
of his damaged right knee, which will be replaced after the Ohio 
State game. 
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Chris Chambers is expected to play for Wisconsin  
after missing two games with a broken bone in his hand. Some 
Badgers say their terrible outing last week will jump-start the 
team into conference play. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it was a good thing, because it woke us up,'' kick  
returner and wide receiver Nick Davis said. ``The beast is alive. 
The sleeping giant is alive.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
