<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 11:20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rural School Opposes Bush Proposal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GOODRICH, Texas (AP) -- Some folks in this rural crossroads find  
it hard to understand presidential candidate George W. Bush's 
education proposal that would strip an impoverished public school 
of funds. Supporters counter that it's an effective way to improve 
poorly performing schools. 
</P>
<P>
	For Goodrich superintendent James B. Boyce, one thing is clear:  
His district has become ``a political lightning rod'' on issues 
ranging from standardized testing to school vouchers. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month Bush, the Texas governor who is seeking the  
Republican presidential nomination, pledged to change federal 
policies that ``cheat poor children.'' The cornerstone of his 
platform takes federal Title 1 funds from the worst-scoring 
schools, transferring the approximately $1,500 per pupil to poor 
parents for use toward educational alternatives, such as private 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	States would be required to test students in grades 3 through 8  
annually, and schools that fell below performance standards for 
three consecutive years would lose Title 1 funds, which amount to 
more than $8 billion annually nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Federal money will no longer flow to failure,'' Bush vowed.  
</P>
<P>
	In Texas, only one of 1,100 districts would lose money under  
this reform: Goodrich. And that has some in this poor town of 300 
people 60 miles northeast of Houston rethinking their support for 
the popular governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've always been proud of what the Bush family has done for  
Texas, but this is not fair,'' said Mark Ryman, the town's mayor 
who is also a substitute teacher. ``We do everything in this town 
for this school, and yet the governor, who I would vote for as 
president, says we have to lose our money? 
</P>
<P>
	``Then I will do everything I can to stop him from being  
president, because I don't think he's in touch with reality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodrich Elementary, attended by 150 children in kindergarten  
through fifth grade, was built in 1936 by the Works Progress 
Administration. The red-brick schoolhouse has long operated with 
the aid of the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	But for three years running, the Texas Education Agency has  
ranked the school as ``low-performing,'' based on student scores on 
the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills. Last year, 44.2 percent of 
52 poor students taking the math portion of the TAAS test passed. 
Schools with less than a 45 percent passing rate are considered low 
performing. 
</P>
<P>
	If Bush's plan were law, Goodrich Elementary would stand to lose  
some of its $47,000 in annual Title 1 funding. 
</P>
<P>
	That prospect and the town's newfound notoriety bother the  
mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryman, a disabled retiree with a straw cowboy hat and a long  
white mustache, received the state's Heroes for Children award for 
volunteer school work four years ago. He says poverty is 
education's worst enemy in Goodrich, where many families earn less 
than $15,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are kids I know who have come to school in their pajamas  
because that's the only thing they have to wear,'' he said. ``We do 
the best we can with the funds we have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boyce, the district's fourth superintendent since 1997, works in  
an aging, two-story frame house the district converted into an 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	To explain the school's performance, he rattles off a list of  
challenges in addition to poverty: a transient population, higher 
than average turnover in administration and high levels of adult 
illiteracy. 
</P>
<P>
	But Boyce's chief complaint -- the crux of the district's appeal  
of its rankings -- is directed at state education officials in 
Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the test, it's the percentage way it's calculated,''  
Boyce said. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodrich's ranking would have improved if the scoring formula  
had not been changed to include the scores of learning-disabled 
students, Boyce said. None of the 10 special education students in 
the district who took the TAAS last school year passed it, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas Education Agency rejects this notion. ``I don't think  
that was a cause for anyone going from acceptable to 
low-performing,'' said agency spokesman Joey Lozano. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Boyce has aggressively pursued federal and state  
grants to address his district's shortcomings. A new computer lab 
and parents' resource center are evidence of his success. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next three years, Goodrich schools will collect about  
$850,000 in grants. Ironically, the elementary school's low ranking 
helped capture much of this money. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a Catch-22,'' says Alison Breteler, president of the  
Goodrich Parent Teacher Association. ``You can't say, 'Because of 
the ranking we're going to give you an increase,' then say, 
'Because of the low ranking we're going to take money away from 
you.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush campaign spokesman Scott McClellan says the candidate  
intends to address this disparity in proposals that have yet to be 
unveiled. Other states are following Texas' lead on school 
accountability, he says. ``Without tests, there is no pressure to 
improve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Testing aside, the voucher provisions of Bush's plan would hurt  
minority schoolchildren, such as those who make up nearly half of 
Goodrich's enrollment, says Rick Dovalina, national president of 
the League of United Latin American Citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	``The governor was very much in support of voucher legislation  
that eventually failed in Texas,'' Dovalina said. ``We feel, as 
president, he's going to continue that mentality of finding ways to 
divert funds from public education, which will hurt the minority 
community and the poor community.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goodrich, which has only one restaurant and one industry -- a  
company that refurbishes box cars -- is unlikely ever to support a 
private school. Although there are Christian schools in Livingston, 
five miles to the north, most have entrance exams or waiting lists 
and costs that exceed the $1,500 per year Bush's proposal offers. 
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't dampen the enthusiasm of the governor's supporters.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are all responsible for helping those kids in Goodrich get  
help,'' said Greg Talley, executive director of Putting Children 
First, an Austin-based pro-voucher group. ``I think Bush is right 
on target when he says school choice is about holding schools 
accountable. If you don't do a good job in three years, we're going 
to do something about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For most Goodrich students, Boyce said, educational alternatives  
are unrealistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is their home, and they're going to be with us until they  
graduate,'' he said. ``We're concerned about these kids and their 
future.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
