<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Awards Injured Boxer Damages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Michael Watson, who is brain injured from a world  
title bout eight years ago, is entitled to damages from the British 
Boxing Board of Control because he did not receive ``proper 
attention,'' a High Court judge ruled Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Ian Kennedy, dealing only with the issue of liability,  
held that Watson would have made a good recovery if proper medical 
procedures had been followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson, who is reported to have lost half of his brain function  
and is paralyzed on his left side, is believed to be seeking about 
$1.6 million in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	A date for damage-award portion of the trial was not announced.  
The Board of Control said it would seek permission to appeal the 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Watson did not comment after the ruling but in a statement read  
by his solicitor, he said: ``I am delighted that I have won my case 
and that I will now be compensated for my injuries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I am pleased that as a result of what has happened to me, new  
rules have been introduced which have made boxing, the sport I 
love, safer,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I take comfort from the fact that those changes may have  
already saved others from a similar fate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watson fought Chris Eubank for the World Boxing Organization  
super-middleweight title in September 1991. Watson was ahead on 
points when he knocked Eubank down in the 11th round. 
</P>
<P>
	But Eubank got up to knock Watson down and the fight was halted  
26 seconds into the 12th with Watson unable to defend himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The British Board of Boxing Control argued that even if Watson  
had been given the treatment he says he should have received, he 
would have suffered the same level of brain damage. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the board said it had ``complete sympathy'' for  
Watson but didn't believe it had a legal liability. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
