<DOCNO> APW19990924.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 07:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutors Head Off Financial Guru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A financial guru accused of defrauding Japanese  
investors of about $1 billion, may have tried to thwart federal 
prosecutors' fraud probe by attempting to liquidate his New Jersey 
company in a West Indies island court. 
</P>
<P>
	Princeton Economics International Ltd., the firm run by Martin  
A. Armstrong that is at the heart of the investment turmoil, filed 
for bankruptcy last Friday in the Turks and Caicos Islands, where 
it is incorporated. 
</P>
<P>
	The filing surprised U.S. prosecutors, who had frozen all of  
Armstrong's bank accounts four days earlier. The prosecutors were 
forced to scramble last weekend to get a court order to prevent 
Armstrong from liquidating the company or any of its subsidiaries 
around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Cohen, the U.S. court receiver for Armstrong's companies,  
requested the restraining order to stop Armstrong from taking 
actions ``that may adversely impact this court's jurisdiction and 
ability to manage this case.'' Authorities are still trying to 
figure out what happened to the Japanese investments, and how much 
money is left to repay them. That would be hard to do if Armstrong 
started selling off assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, an oft-quoted investment advisor renown for  
forecasting market swings, was arrested Sept. 13 on allegations of 
securities fraud. He was released on $5 million bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints against Armstrong were filed by the U.S. Attorney,  
and two regulators, the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and 
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Unger, an attorney for Armstrong, said Princeton  
Economics filed for bankruptcy ``because of all the problems that 
are out there.'' He said the interim liquidator appointed by the 
Turks and Caicos court ``is going to be able to deal with issues 
that may arise wherever they arise in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why Armstrong did not forewarn U.S. prosecutors, Unger  
said only that, ``It was a company decision. They went to court and 
they did it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. prosecutors and regulators believe Armstrong raised more  
than $3 billion from Japanese investors, promising to repay them 
with interest. 
</P>
<P>
	He invested the Japanese funds in currencies, options andother  
securities, but lost more than $500 million between 1997 and August 
1999 and tried to hide the losses, prosecutors have claimed in 
court documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The money was held in accounts in the securities unit of  
Republic Bank of New York. Prosecutors allege that the bank 
provided letters to Armstrong, at his request, which overstated the 
balances in the accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he repaid the investors much of their money, today  
there is only $43 million left in the Republic accounts to repay 
almost $1 billion in securities still held by the Japanese 
investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, through a lawyer, has denied any fraud or criminal  
conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's never been any dispute some money was lost, the  
question is whether it was honest or criminal,'' said Marc Durant, 
who is representing Armstrong in his criminal case. Armstrong's 
company has accused Republic of mismanaging its accounts. Princeton 
Economics International, is based in Princeton, N.J., but has no 
connection to the nearby Ivy League university. It has lost a lot 
of business since Armstrong's arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Until last week, Armstrong was the investment advisor on three  
investment funds, all unrelated to the problems with the Japanese 
securities, and all earning solid returns. 
</P>
<P>
	Two are now closing and the third is looking for a new advisor.  
</P>
<P>
	``How can he possibly manage the fund with this on his head?''  
asks Dion Friedland, chairman of the Magnum Group of Funds, which 
sponsored the $14 million Princeton Global Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Friedland said he opted to close the fund, although he said  
Armstrong was an ``incredible'' investor and the fund posted a 
whopping 60 percent return in the last 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Japanese-based funds Armstrong ran were also closed,  
though it is unclear when and why they did so. 
</P>
<P>
	Armstrong, who turned a boyhood love of coins into a lucrative  
silver and commodities business, spent almost 30 years building 
Princeton Economics International and its subsidiaries into a 
global research group with 300 employees and offices on five 
continents. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, within days of his arrest, Armstrong's empire started to  
contract. The office in Japan, a subsidiary called Cresvale 
International Ltd., will shut its doors at the end of the month and 
lay off its 50 employees. 

</P>
<P>
	 *Investigative researcher Randy Herschaft contributed to this  
story. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
