<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                         *Philip Brownstein    	
</P>
<P>
	SILVER SPRING, Md. (AP) -- Philip Brownstein, a federal housing  
administrator who fought discrimination by developers and 
landlords, died Sept. 17. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	Brownstein was a top housing administrator in the Kennedy and  
Johnson administrations who expanded Depression-era housing laws to 
increase home ownership among minorities. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1963 he was named commissioner of the Federal Housing  
Administration, which insured mortgages issued by banks to 
homeowners. Brownstein amended the mortgage laws to allow more 
blacks and other minorities to buy their own homes. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Drew Cloud    	
</P>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE (AP) -- Drew Cloud, a longtime New Mexico Democratic  
Party leader, died Wednesday after a long bout with cancer. He was 
75. 
</P>
<P>
	A former union representative and state legislator, Cloud went  
on to manage political campaigns and serve as chairman of the state 
Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	He served in the Army during World War II. On his return, Cloud  
went to work in a southern New Mexico potash mine and later became 
a union representative. He became active in veterans affairs and 
for a time was chairman of the New Mexico Veterans Service 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Cloud became chairman of the state Democratic Party in 1970 and  
was appointed to the state Racing Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Cloud ran for governor in 1974 but lost in the primary election  
to the eventual winner, Jerry Apodaca. 
</P>
<P>
	Cloud also headed the New Mexico Rural Rehabilitation Corp., a  
nonprofit corporation created with federal funds granted to the 
state during the Great Depression to help the rural poor. 

</P>
<P>
                          *William Eckert    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Dr. William Eckert, a forensic pathologist  
who was a consultant on major cases including the assassination of 
Robert F. Kennedy and the Jonestown massacre, died Sept. 17. He was 
73. 
</P>
<P>
	Eckert founded the International Organization of Forensic  
Medicine and the American Journal of Forensic Medicine and 
Pathology. 
</P>
<P>
	He was president of the International Association of Forensic  
Sciences and the National Association of Medical Examiners, wrote 
several books and held academic appointments at a number of 
universities, including Tulane Medical School. 
</P>
<P>
	Eckert was consulted on such famous cases as the Charles Manson  
murders, the John Wayne Gacy serial killings, the exhumation of 
Nazi doctor Joseph Mengele's body and the terrorist bombing of Pan 
Am Flight 103. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1980s, Eckert put together an investigative team  
that re-examined the 100-year-old Jack the Ripper prostitute 
murders. He also served as a consultant for the television series 
``Quincy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Upon hearing that Robert Kennedy had been assassinated in his  
jurisdiction, former Los Angeles County Coroner Thomas Noguchi 
wrote in one of his books that he immediately called in Eckert 
because he wanted to make sure there were no mistakes. 

</P>
<P>
                             *Ivan Goff    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- Ivan Goff, co-creator of the TV  
series ``Charlie's Angels'' and co-writer of the films ``White 
Heat,'' ``Captain Horatio Hornblower'' and ``Man of a Thousand 
Faces,'' died Thursday. He was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	With his writing partner for 39 years, the late Ben Roberts,  
Goff wrote 25 feature films that starred James Cagney, Gregory 
Peck, Clark Gable, Doris Day, Joan Crawford and others. Among their 
credits: ``Midnight Lace,'' ``Shake Hands with the Devil,'' ``Band 
of Angels,'' ``Green Fire,'' ``King of the Khyber Rifles,'' ``Come 
Fill the Cup'' and ``Goodbye, My Fancy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Goff and Roberts were Oscar-nominated for their screenplay of  
``Man of a Thousand Faces,'' which starred Cagney as Lon Chaney. In 
1954-55, Goff served as president of the screen writers council of 
the Screen Writers Guild, predecessor of the Writers Guild of 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1960s, the pair turned to television, writing ``The  
Rogues'' for Dick Powell, David Niven and Charles Boyer. They also 
produced ``Mannix'' (1967-75) and created ``Charlie's Angels'' 
(1976-81). 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Perth, Goff worked as a newspaperman in Australia,  
freelanced in London in the early 1930s and became Hollywood 
correspondent for the London Daily Mirror in 1936. He wrote a 
novel, ``No Longer Innocent,'' and a play ``Portrait in Black'' 
before turning to films. He met Roberts while both served in the 
U.S. Army Signal Corps during World War II. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Robert Galbraith Heath    	
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Dr. Robert Galbraith Heath, a noted  
schizophrenia researcher who founded and chaired Tulane 
University's Department of Psychiatry and Neurology, died Sept. 21. 
He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a two-year stint in the military, Heath earned  
graduate degrees in neurophysiological research and psychoanalysis 
at Columbia University. In 1949, he founded and became the first 
chairman of Tulane University's Department of Psychiatry and 
Neurology, a post he held until 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 31 years leading Tulane's psychiatry department and  
until 1985, Heath headed a multidisciplinary team investigating 
brain and behavior with an emphasis on schizophrenia. 
</P>
<P>
	Heath was recognized nationally and internationally for research  
into the cause and treatments for schizophrenia, writing and 
editing three books and publishing more than 420 scientific 
articles. He summarized his research with a monograph, ``Exploring 
the Mind-Brain Relationship,'' published in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Herbert Leupin    	
</P>
<P>
	BASEL, Switzerland (AP) -- Swiss graphic artist Herbert Leupin,  
who gained international recognition for his colorful product 
posters, died Tuesday. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	The creator of the purple cow that advertised Suchard's Milka  
chocolate, Leupin also designed posters for Coca Cola. 
</P>
<P>
	Leupin also exhibited in New York and in 1960 received the Art  
Directors Club's Medal Award. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Lynn DeLaney Saunders    	
</P>
<P>
	BREMERTON, Wash. (AP) -- Lynn DeLaney Saunders, photo editor of  
The Sun newspaper in Bremerton, died Thursday of injuries suffered 
in a traffic accident. She was 46. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Saunders died after her 1993 Toyota swerved off the left  
lane into a grass median along Washington 3 and struck an overpass 
support near Bremerton. 
</P>
<P>
	Before coming to The Sun in December 1991, she worked at The  
Tennessean in Nashville; Vanderbilt University Medical Center in 
Nashville; The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla.; The Commercial Appeal of 
Memphis, Tenn.; and the Orlando Sentinel of Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include her husband, a son, her parents, two brothers,  
two sisters and a half-sister. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
