<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up a Bit Against the Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar on Friday rose modestly against the  
Japanese yen for a second straight session amid renewed fears about 
Japan's economic recovery and in advance of a weekend meeting of 
international finance ministers. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 104.17  
Japanese yen, up from 103.95 late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders sold the yen Friday after Japan's Nikkei 225-stock  
benchmark index dropped 2.6 percent following heightened worries 
about whether Japan could keep alive its recovery from a steep 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	Some traders also were anxious in advance of a Washington  
meeting of the Group of Seven industrialized nations. There has 
been speculation that Japan and other G-7 nations may try to 
coordinate action to weaken the surging yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan has intervened in its currency markets several times this  
summer in an attempt to slow the yen's gains, but without success. 
As recently as May, the dollar bought more than 124 yen, but the 
dollar since has fallen 16 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials believe that the yen has strengthened too  
much and could derail the economic recovery. A rising yen makes it 
harder for Japanese exports to compete on world markets. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders doubt the United States would be willing to support  
a new currency policy. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the euro rose to $1.0464 from $1.0440 late  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5310 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5362, and 1.4734 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4711. The British 
pound rose to $1.6437 from $1.6407. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8685 German 
marks, down from 1.8734; 6.2666 French francs, down from 6.2831; 
and 1,849.79 Italian lire, down from 1,854.66. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
