<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Signals Tough Talks Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Israel signaled today it will not yield easily  
to Arab demands in peacemaking. ``We have principles,'' Foreign 
Minister David Levy said. 
</P>
<P>
	And while Israel is willing to take risks for peace with the  
Palestinians, Syria and Lebanon, it wants an end to ``double talk'' 
and hostility in international forums, Levy said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not a favor we ask for Israel,'' the foreign minister  
told the Center for Middle East Peace and Cooperation, a private 
group that tries to promote compromise and business in the Middle 
East. ``A true peace will benefit everyone in the area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Levy urged Egypt, with which Israel signed a peace treaty 20  
years ago, to consent to a ``warmer peace'' with the Jewish state -- 
relations are strictly formal with little in the way of exchanges 
between the two sides despite Israeli overtures. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreign minister, who has served in various Israeli  
governments along a broad political spectrum, gave no indication on 
what issues Israel would take a tough line. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said ``in order to achieve peace we must insist on  
aspects that are indispensable for us. Sometimes people don't 
understand we have principles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In negotiations with the Palestinians, Israel faces demands that  
it give up virtually the entire West Bank, agree to establishment 
of a Palestinian state, consent to having its capital in Jerusalem 
and take in tens of thousands of Arab refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	In negotiations not yet opened with Syria, Israel faces demands  
that it give up the strategic Golan Heights border enclave as well 
as land up to the shores of the Sea of Galilee, which holds 
Israel's precious water reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	``Israel is ready to take risks,'' Levy said. ``There will be  
obstacles, but we must not let that discourage us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elaborating on Levy's remarks, Zalman Shoval, the Israeli  
ambassador to the United States, said that with the peace process 
advancing, Israel could not accept continued use of the United 
Nations and other international forums to promote an anti-Israel 
agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the only case in which a country that has been the  
victim of aggression has been in the dock, as an accused, at the 
U.N.,'' Shoval said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	The ambassador said Israel should not remain excluded from  
taking its turn on the Security Council, and that the United States 
was trying to help. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said, meanwhile, that the  
United States ``would stand with those who take risks for peace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But she added that ``only the parties, not their friends, can  
make the tough decisions themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, on the other hand, said  
the U.S. role in peacemaking is crucial -- and has been since 
U.S.-hosted talks at Camp David in 1978 produced a peace treaty 
between Egypt and Israel the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Underscoring the Arabs' approach, which the Clinton  
administration endorses, Moussa reminded Israel that ``the name of 
the game is land for peace.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 02:50:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Retailer's Advertisements Banned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- In Germany, some guarantees are just  
too good to be true. 
</P>
<P>
	Threatened by the American catalogue company Lands' End  
money-back guarantee, no matter what, retail competitors took the 
company to Germany's highest court -- and won a ban on 
advertisements publicizing the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Lands' End is responding with a set of ads in German  
newspapers and magazines poking fun at the ban. There's a picture 
of a fly with the caption: 1-Day Guarantee. A washing machine, 
guaranteed 6 months. 
</P>
<P>
	And next to the Lands' End logo: ``Advertisement forbidden in  
Germany.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dodgeville, Wis.-based company expanded overseas to England  
in 1993, Japan in 1994 and Germany in 1996, exporting along with 
its classic chinos and wool cardigans the guarantee that it will 
take back any of its products, any time, no questions asked, cash 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a year of launching the German business, the company was  
being sued by an agency that monitors advertising claiming unfair 
advertisement. The case went all the way to the Supreme Court in 
Karlsruhe, which banned the advertisements last month ruling the 
guarantee was ``economically unfeasible'' and therefore amounted to 
unfair competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The guarantee was not an issue either in Japan or England.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult to understand from an American perspective. All  
we're trying to do is to offer the same service level in Germany 
that we offer everywhere else in the world,'' said Steve Bechwar, 
manager of Lands' Ends operations in Mettlach, Germany, opened in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is not the first time that American marketing savvy and  
German conservatism have clashed. In a previous instance, American 
producers of Tupperware were banned from advertising an unlimited 
guarantee, so they dropped theirs to 30 years to match Germany 
statute of limitations on lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Zippo lighters avoided legal action by deciding to remove their  
lifetime guarantee from German packaging. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun in a way to watch Lands' End,'' said Philip Haleen,  
an American lawyer in Germany who has done work for Zippo. ``I've 
been here in Europe for a long time and there's a U.S. way of doing 
business and there's a German way of doing business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	High-court decisions are final in Germany, and Lands' End is  
considering whether to appeal at the European Union-level. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the meantime, the company is trying to get the word out  
to its German customers any way it can -- such as the oblique print 
ads launched last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The company may be aided by the expanding world of electronic  
commerce, which seems to be quickly outpacing German law. Customers 
who log onto Lands' End German site can enter the U.S. site, where 
the guarantee is spelled out. 
</P>
<P>
	And, ironically, the ban has been good advertising.  
</P>
<P>
	In Britain, the company has run print ads proclaiming: ``A  
Guarantee so good the Germans banned it.'' 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
