<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Finances Deemed Healthy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Private auditors have given a clean audit for  
the first time to House financial operations, which in the past 
have been characterized by scandal and mismanagement, House 
Republicans announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one of our crowning achievements,'' said Rep. John  
Boehner, R-Ohio, a leader in GOP efforts to run the House more like 
a business. ``This is a day I thought I'd never see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The accounting firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, in a report on 1998  
House operations, said real progress was made in correcting past 
problems. The auditors found ``no instances of noncompliance'' with 
laws and regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	Their report listed five remaining internal control weaknesses,  
including an outdated payroll system, poor controls over computers 
and data and poor tracking of foods and services, but said progress 
was being made even in those areas. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an exciting day for many of us,'' said House  
Administration Committee Chairman Bill Thomas, R-Calif. 
``Considering the hill that we had to climb it is a significant 
accomplishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of the first acts of the new Republican majority in 1995 was  
to make the House accountable to the same financial standards that 
private businesses must abide by. Some subsidized operations, such 
as the House barbershop and restaurant, were turned over to private 
management, and the U.S. Postal Service took over the post office. 
</P>
<P>
	Then-Speaker Newt Gingrich ordered the first outside audit of  
House operations, which found considerable problems, including $14 
million in over-budget spending by House offices, but also 
concluded that the lack of organization in the often handwritten 
books made a true assessment difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``The books were so bad, the computer files were so inept and  
ambiguous, that they really couldn't find anything,'' said House 
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Steny Hoyer of Maryland, the ranking Democrat on the House  
Administration panel, said efforts to professionalize House 
operations began under Speaker Tom Foley, a Democrat, but the 
Republican leadership ``deserves a fair amount of the credit for 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Republicans took over in 1995 looking for major  
irregularities but instead found mostly poor bookkeeping. ``It was 
a sloppy system, and it needed to be cleaned up,'' Hoyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The previous Democratic majority established an inspector  
general's office in the House in the aftermath of scandals 
involving the House-run bank and post office. GOP leaders expanded 
the IG office staff from two in 1994 to 20 this year and increased 
its budget from $347,500 to $3.9 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
