<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants Congress' Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Deriding the Republican tax cut he just  
vetoed, President Clinton criticized GOP presidential candidate 
George W. Bush today for a policy address promising better military 
pay and new weapons if he were elected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought to myself, `That's a nice speech, but if I sign this  
tax bill he's for there won't be any money for the promise he just 
made,''' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Addressing a gathering of party officials, Clinton also called  
on Congress to set aside partisan rancor and work on a budget that 
would shore up Social Security, Medicare and the education system. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still believe there's the opportunity for us to work  
together,'' Clinton said of the Republican leadership on Capitol 
Hill. ``This is not an election year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton made frequent reference to the early start to the 2000  
election cycle in his remarks to the annual meeting of the 
Democratic National Committee. He noted that he didn't announce his 
first presidential bid until October 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I've been going through this campaign all my life,  
and I'm not even running,'' he quipped. 
</P>
<P>
	More to the point, he gave encouragement to Vice President Al  
Gore, whose campaign to move into the Oval Office has struggled to 
gain support in public opinion polls. 
</P>
<P>
	Without mentioning Gore directly, Clinton noted that he was in  
third place and the pundits were giving him long odds when the 
voting public finally began to focus on the race in June 1992 and 
he won primaries in California, New Jersey and Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``It became real,'' Clinton said. ``And people began to look and  
listen and they opened not just their minds but their hearts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush offered his vision for the Defense Department in a speech  
Wednesday at The Citadel. He called for greater investment in 
futuristic weapons research and accused the Clinton administration 
of paying military personnel too little. 
</P>
<P>
	Signaling that he will sign a massive military spending bill  
despite reservations about a provision that would reorganize the 
Energy Department, Clinton said Bush was ``ignoring the fact that 
we're just about to pay a big pay increase and build new weapons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he criticized the GOP candidates who supported the  
congressional tax cut proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once again I did the Republican candidates running for  
president a favor,'' Clinton said. ``If I had signed it, it would 
have made a lie out of every campaign speech they're going to give 
between now and the election about what they're going to do because 
they wouldn't have any money to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton used the speech to recap the economic success of his  
administration and champion the work Democrats have done to fight 
crime and toughen gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want you to be of good cheer and proud because America is a  
better place than it was in 1992,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The group cheered when the president mentioned that he had  
vetoed the Republicans' $792 billion tax cut a day earlier because, 
he said, it would have squandered the opportunity to strengthen the 
retirement and health care systems and invest in education. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason I vetoed the tax bill is that it would make it  
impossible for America to meet its long-term challenges,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told the party officials that their stand on Medicare,  
Social Security and crime would set Democrats apart from 
Republicans in the upcoming elections. ``There really are 
differences between these parties,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always believed if ... we just thought about the people that  
nobody else in Washington seems to think about,'' he said, ``you 
could marry good politics and good policy and everything would be 
all right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
