<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Relief Agency Criticizes IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund is failing to  
complete its mission of reducing poverty in the world's poorest 
nations and needs a radical overhaul, the international relief 
agency Oxfam said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A report by the group said IMF programs in developing countries  
not only are failing to spur economic growth but also are fostering 
deep cuts in spending on public health and education. 
</P>
<P>
	``IMF staff like to portray themselves as providers of `tough  
love,' prescribing strong medicine to sick national economies,'' 
said Kevin Watkins, author of the 40-page report. ``Unfortunately, 
they are prescribing the wrong medicine in lethal doses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report also accuses governments of major industrialized  
countries, which control the 182-nation IMF, of negligence for 
continuing to insist that poor countries comply with IMF programs 
as a condition for receiving foreign aid and debt relief. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxfam said even though the IMF and the G-7 finance ministers,  
who largely determine its policies, are out of touch. But the 
relief agency said the IMF should be reformed, not dissolved as 
some members of Congress have proposed. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was issued as ministers and central bankers from  
around the world started arriving in Washington for the annual 
meetings of the IMF and its sister organization, the World Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Among main findings in the report:  
</P>
<P>
	--Growth rates countries of sub-Saharan Africa that following IMF  
programs are less than half of rates required to achieve an 
internationally agreed human development goal of halving world 
poverty by 2015. 
</P>
<P>
	--Twelve out of 16 African countries whose IMF programs were  
reviewed by Oxfam analysts cut per-capita spending on education in 
a region where 47 million children don't go to school. 
</P>
<P>
	--In Indonesia, IMF austerity programs have prolonged and  
deepened a recession that has forced 20 million people below the 
poverty line, ``one of the greatest postwar human development 
reversals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Failure to protect jobs and the education budget in Thailand  
has resulted in a threefold increase in the number of children 
dropping out of school. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxfam, comprising 11 nongovernmental organizations around the  
world, lobbies governments and financial institutions to fight 
poverty and conducts anti-poverty projects in more than 100 
countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
