<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Modern Art Goes Back Centuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's first museum devoted to modern art  
is putting on a splashy show full of the verve -- if not nerve -- of 
a collector who dared see value in less-than-ancient paintings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Renoir to Rothko: The Eye of Duncan Phillips,'' opens Saturday  
at the Phillips Collection, a pioneering mansion-turned-museum that 
began celebrating modernism some eight years before the opening of 
New York's Museum of Modern Art. 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibition of some 360 paintings, running until Jan. 23,  
ranges from Pierre Auguste Renoir, the French Impressionist who 
started painting in the mid-1800s, to Mark Rothko, Russian-born 
leader of American abstract expressionists, who died in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	The 78-year-old Phillips Collection is largely the life work of  
one man. A critic as well as a collector, Duncan Phillips saw 
painters going back to El Greco in the 16th century as precursors 
of modernism. Phillips died in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	A favorite of Phillips was Honore Daumier, who liked to  
caricature legislators, lawyers and art collectors in the Paris of 
Renoir's youth. One painting is being shown now, but the collection 
owns six more and 50 of his other works. 
</P>
<P>
	For the past 15 years, the Phillips staff has been working on a  
10-pound, 840-page catalog of its 2,400 works, to be published with 
the opening of the exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	In the course of cleaning work for the show, curators discovered  
that one painting had another canvas underneath it -- both by the 
American artist Gifford Beal, who died in 1956. A ``Parade of 
Elephants'' was what the museum thought it had acquired, but below 
that was a picture of a woman and two children looking down a 
hillside, apparently in the Hudson River Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	But neither picture is hung in the show. The curators liked  
another by the same artist. 
</P>
<P>
	Son of a wealthy Pittsburgh glass manufacturer, Phillips had a  
lifelong passion for art. 
</P>
<P>
	His early taste ran to traditional paintings on traditional  
subjects, in dark colors. He was one of 75,000 visitors to the 
famous ``Armory Show'' of 1913, where many Americans got their 
first taste of the dazzling Pablo Picasso, Paul Gauguin and Marcel 
Duchamp's sensational ``Nude Descending a Staircase.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, like many others, was outraged. He reviewed the show  
for an art magazine, calling it ``stupefying in its vulgarity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But when he reprinted the review in a book 14 years later, he  
wrote: 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of the ideas I was then eager to oppose I am now eager to  
uphold. ... Consistency from youth to middle age is at best a 
stiff-necked virtue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He became a leading supporter of American painter Arthur Dove,  
who has a claim to be the first of the abstract painters. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through his patronage of living artists, Phillips disseminated  
and evangelized modernism to a not-always-receptive American 
audience,'' said chief curator Eliza Rathbone. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit will be on view through Jan. 23 and will not travel.  
Admission is $7.50 for adults, $4 for seniors and students. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
