<HEADLINE> Phillips Shares Slump on Sale News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) -- Shares of Phillips Petroleum Co.  
slumped more than 8 percent Friday as investors reacted to the 
company's plans to sell its chemicals and refining businesses and 
focus on exploration and production. 
</P>
<P>
	The plans cooled off Wall Street's speculation that Phillips  
would be acquired by Chevron Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Mulva, who became chief executive officer in July, outlined  
a new five-year plan for the company on Thursday. He told analysts 
he expects to raise $3 billion from the sale of its natural gas 
gathering, marketing and processing subsidiary and other assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulva plans to use some of that money to expand its exploration  
and production business. But Phillips also will increase its 
capital expenditures by 90 percent to $2.25 billion to make 
investments and acquisitions in areas like Alaska, Texas and the 
Permian Basin in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips, the nation's eighth-largest oil company, wants to  
concentrate on developing discoveries made recently in the Timor 
Sea and in China and on its assets in the North Sea, North America 
and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's aim is to double its reserves from the current 2  
billion-barrel level in five years. Much of the growth this year 
will come from the Hamaca project in Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some positive changes in Phillips' strategies,''  
Paul Ting, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, wrote in a 
research report Friday. ``There is no question that Mr. James Mulva 
is intensely focused on restructuring the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Worried about the cost of that restructuring, and disappointed  
about the unlikely prospects of a merger with Chevron, investors 
pushed shares of Phillips' down $4.37 1/2 to $49.50 on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulva will be looking for joint-venture partners to share in the  
cost of the growth. Phillips has looked at joint venture efforts in 
the past with the gas marketing, gathering and processing unit. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips and Ultramar Diamond Shamrock Corp. failed earlier this  
year to forge a joint venture that would have created the largest 
independent refining, marketing and transportation company in North 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies couldn't work out details and negotiations ended  
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	An attempt at a similar joint venture with Conoco failed in  
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The strategic plan marks a new strategy for the company's  
chemical operation, which includes assets worth $2.9 billion. The 
chemical unit includes the production of petrochemicals, specialty 
chemicals and plastics. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
