<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP, Clinton at Farm Bill Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican congressional leaders struggled  
Friday to break an impasse over an agricultural spending bill. The 
Clinton administration had new criticism of the measure's emergency 
farm assistance and trade provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman said the measure would fall  
$700 million short of covering farmers' losses from droughts and 
floods this year, not including hurricane damages still being 
counted in North Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to make sure in this package that there is an  
adequate amount of resources dedicated to those people who have 
actually suffered losses,'' Glickman said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	He stopped short of threatening to recommend President Clinton  
veto the measure, however. ``I'm not signaling anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders have agreed to put at least $8 billion worth  
of farm aid in the bill, including $500 million for weather-related 
losses. But the legislation stalled because of disputes over dairy 
policy and a Senate amendment that would allow exports of food and 
medicine to Cuba and make it difficult for the president to stop 
such sales with other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration is concerned about the trade measure,  
according to lawmakers, because it would require a president to get 
congressional approval before imposing sanctions on food and 
medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would have ``grave implications for our  
nonproliferation, counterterrorism and counternarcotics 
initiatives,'' said Gus Shumacher, USDA's undersecretary for farm 
and foreign agricultural services. He declined to elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	The House-Senate conference committee responsible for writing  
the final version of the spending bill stopped work on Wednesday 
because of the impasse. House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., met 
with Republican members of the panel Friday morning but no 
resolution was expected before next week, lawmakers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're up against a wall on that (bill) and the leadership  
needs to take it on,'' said Rep. Bill Young, a Florida Republican 
who chairs the House Appropriations Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the House leadership offered farm-state lawmakers  
an additional $700 million in disaster relief in exchange for 
dropping the Cuba and dairy provisions, but the proposal was 
rebuffed by farm organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need the money, but I think farmers know the export market  
is their future,'' said Mary Kay Thatcher, a lobbyist for the 
American Farm Bureau Federation. ``Sanctions are simply the wrong 
message.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dairy dispute involves an Agriculture Department overhaul of  
milk pricing set to take effect next month. Lawmakers in the South 
and East want to scrap the new system and replace it with regional 
price-setting agreements. Lawmakers in the Midwest support the 
proposed changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Glickman clashed with farm groups over how to  
distribute $5.5 billion that is expected to be in the bill as 
compensation for depressed commodity prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Farm Bureau and major commodity groups want the payments  
calculated on the basis of farmers' ``market transition'' contracts 
with USDA that provide them with guaranteed annual subsidies. The 
groups say that's the best way of ensuring USDA issues the checks 
quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Glickman wants to set up a new system. Payments under the market  
transition contracts are based on outdated planting patterns, not 
what farmers grew this year, and he says some of the money will go 
to producers who didn't even plant a crop. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0237 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 20:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Royals' Closer Montgomery To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Kansas City closer Jeff Montgomery, one  
of 11 players to save 300 games in his career, will retire at the 
end of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery, who earned his 300th save last month, has 12 saves  
this season and seven of the Royals' 30 blown saves. He is 1-4 with 
a 6.34 ERA and hitters are batting .342 against him. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last few months of last year were real positive, but this  
year has not been the same,'' he said. ``The big thing is knowing 
that I'm not a fit anymore. I'm 37. When this team gets to a point 
where it is competitive, it needs someone that is definitely going 
to be there. Because of the years, it can't be me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery battled a shoulder problem last year and a hip  
problem this year, limiting his effectiveness. 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery has 304 saves in his career, all for the Royals. He  
is the only member of the 300-save club to record all of them with 
one team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you get the 300th save, you get to a different level as  
far as recognition,'' he said. ``It puts you on the map a little 
more. The fact that I was able to accomplish that goal with Kansas 
City, all with one team, is very satisfying to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Montgomery, acquired from the Cincinnati Reds on Feb. 13, 1988  
for Van Snider, took over the Royals' closing job from Dan 
Quisenberry midway through the 1990 season and has held it since. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was fortunate to come into an organization at a time when  
they needed someone who does what I do,'' he said. ``They stuck 
with me. The team and I have both given over the years on certain 
occasions. It's been a good fit.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
