<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Enters Final Stage of Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee is entering  
the final stages of a reform process designed to reshape the 
organization after its worst crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 10 months after the IOC became engulfed in a vote-buying  
scandal that battered its image and credibility, a special panel 
meets this weekend to review proposed changes in the committee's 
structure, rules and procedures. 
</P>
<P>
	New rules on age limits, term limits, member selection and the  
Olympic bidding process will be discussed by the executive 
committee of IOC 2000, a reform commission set up in the wake of 
the Salt Lake City bribery affair. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC purged 10 members (six were expelled and four resigned)  
in connection with $1.2 million worth of cash, gifts, travel and 
other inducements stemming from Salt Lake City's successful bid for 
the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	But the house-cleaning was seen only as a short-term response,  
with observers and critics waiting to see whether the IOC enacts 
lasting reforms to make the organization more accountable and less 
open to corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	The 80-member IOC 2000 panel was split into three working  
groups, which will present reports Saturday to a closed meeting of 
the 26-member executive body at Lausanne, Switzerland. The 13 
non-IOC members on the executive group include former Secretary of 
State Henry Kissinger and fomer United Nations Secretary-General 
Boutros Boutros-Ghali. 
</P>
<P>
	The executive's recommendations will be put to the full reform  
commission Oct. 30-31. They will then be submitted for a vote by 
the entire IOC at a special session at Lausanne Dec. 11-12 . 
</P>
<P>
	``These will be very important changes,'' IOC president Juan  
Antonio Samaranch said. 
</P>
<P>
	The weekend meetings come at a time when the IOC is facing fresh  
scrutiny amid allegations of vote-buying associated with Atlanta's 
winning bid for the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	A report delivered to Congress this week detailed how Atlanta  
bidders lavished gifts, college scholarships, job offers and other 
inducements on IOC members and their families. 
</P>
<P>
	The House commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigation  
will hold hearings into the bid process next month. Rep. Fred 
Upton, R-Mich., said the panel will subpoena Samaranch to testify 
if he doesn't appear voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Dick Pound hopes Congress will take into  
account ``the massive reform'' which the organization has embarked 
upon in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've implemented much more than the critics ever  
expected,'' executive board member Jacques Rogge said. ``We did not 
act under pressure from anybody ...'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl, a member of the IOC  
2000 group, said, ``The changes will be substantive, not cosmetic. 
The reforms are significant ..'' 
</P>
<P>
	Based on numerous interviews with members of the panel, here is  
a look at some of the key proposals: 
</P>
<P>
	-- One of the most sensitive issues is the age limit. In 1995,  
the IOC voted to raise the limit from 75 to 80 in order to allow 
Samaranch to win another term in office. 
</P>
<P>
	The reform working group is proposing lowering the limit to 70,  
but apparently only for future members. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The panel has recommended instituting term limits for the  
first time, with members facing re-election after eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The IOC president would be limited to one eight-year term.  
That would be a major change from the present system, under which 
Samaranch has been in office since 1980 and re-elected by 
acclamation three times. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Traditionally, IOC members have been essentially handpicked by  
the president. The reform panel proposes the creation of a special 
nominating committee, which would screen potential candidates and 
put names forward to the executive board for consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Fifteen contemporary athletes, elected by their peers, would  
be appointed to the IOC. ``I believe this will be the most 
important short-term and long-term change,'' Hybl said. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Also represented on the IOC would be heads of 15 international  
sports federations and leaders of 15 national Olympic committees. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The IOC will have a maximum of 115 members once all the new  
rules are phased in. 
</P>
<P>
	-- A large majority of IOC delegates (70) should be ``independent  
members'' chosen as individuals and not elected to represent 
constituent bodies. 
</P>
<P>
	-- On the Olympic site-selection process, a ``bid acceptance  
procedure'' would be introduced, requiring cities to meet certain 
technical criteria before being allowed to mount a bid. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Visits of IOC members to bid cities would be permitted only if  
``deemed necessary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- The final decision on the host city would continue to be made  
in a vote of all IOC members, not by the executive board or other 
small panel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
