<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 09:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Bill Might Help Young Boxers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House members eager to protect young fighters  
from unscrupulous promoters moved ahead legislation today that 
would set up new federal rules for professional boxing. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., called the bill a way to  
``re-establish boxing as the honest and clean sport so many of us 
grew up appreciating.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The measure was approved by the House Commerce consumer  
protection subcommittee on a 15-1 vote. The dissenter, Rep. Bobby 
Rush, D-Ill., said he wanted to discuss the bill with Muhammad Ali 
before supporting it. The bill is named in honor of the former 
heavyweight champion, who testified in favor of it in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure now goes to the full committee.  
</P>
<P>
	``For too long in boxing, the fix has been in. Boxers and fans  
deserve fair fights,'' said Rep. Mike Oxley, R-Ohio, sponsor of the 
bill, which would require promoters to file financial disclosure 
forms and prohibit conflicts of interest between promoters and 
managers. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would make it illegal for a fighter to sign any  
contract extending longer than five years. 
</P>
<P>
	In response to the fury over the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis  
bout earlier this year, it also would require all boxing referees 
and judges to be certified and approved by state boxing 
commissions. 
</P>
<P>
	It addition, the bill specifies that boxers can be suspended for  
unsportsmanlike conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., wrote the bill, which passed the  
Senate unanimously, and cooperated with House members in writing 
changes that were incorporated into the measure today. The 
five-year limit on contracts was one such change; McCain initially 
wanted no contract to last longer than one year. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bills are S.305 and H.R.1832.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
