<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF To Help Y2K-Stricken Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund said Friday  
that it will offer special loans to countries whose economies 
encounter problems caused by the Y2K computer bug. 
</P>
<P>
	But Managing Director Michel Camdessus said it was possible the  
funds might not be used because businesses, financial institutions 
and governments have made considerable progress in preparing their 
computers for any problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have no reason to believe that there will be widespread Y2K  
problems or associated balance of payments difficulties,'' 
Camdessus said in a statement. ``In fact, it may well be that the 
Y2K facility will not be used.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Nevertheless, there are uncertainties, and the potential  
consequences for international trade and growth of possible 
interruptions to production and shipments may be significant,'' he 
said. ``Equally important is the potential for temporary 
interruptions to international capital flows in response to 
perceived problems that may -- or may not -- materialize.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF chief said the Y2K fund will provide rapid, short-term  
assistance to the 182 IMF member countries and must be repaid 
within six months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Y2K concern is that computer programs that read only the  
last two digits of the year might mistake 2000 for 1900 and cause 
systems to go haywire. 
</P>
<P>
	Industrial nations have spent billions preparing for any Y2K  
problems, and many of them expect only minor disruptions. Poor 
countries appear to be less prepared. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Bank has been helping many of these developing  
countries fix Y2K problems with grants, loans and technical aid. 
Some of these countries may be able to revert to manual systems 
still in place while they deal with the changeover. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
