<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flooding Devastates N.C. Farms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Hurricane Floyd's floodwaters could put one  
in seven farms in North Carolina out of business, the state 
agriculture commissioner says. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner Jim Graham estimated on Wednesday that up to 7,000  
of North Carolina's nearly 50,000 farms, or about 15 percent, may 
be lost. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ones who are in trouble are the farmers on the edge  
already,'' he said. ``These people may not lose their land. But say 
it takes them a year to dry out and have plantable soil. How are 
they supposed to pay their equipment loans between now and then?'' 
</P>
<P>
	State experts expect the agricultural damage to exceed $1  
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot we won't know until things dry out,'' Graham  
said. ``A lot of people haven't gotten back onto their land yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the bright side, Graham said reports that the floods killed  
100,000 hogs -- about 1 percent of the state's total production -- 
were overly pessimistic. He said the loss is believed to be closer 
to 40,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The flooding spared much of the year's tobacco crop, most of  
which was already harvested, but about half the expected 
872,000-acre cotton crop is feared lost, Graham said. The peanut 
and sweet potato crops were also hit hard. 
</P>
<P>
	Farm leaders are lobbying for government relief money.  
</P>
<P>
	``This could be just catastrophic for us without some help,''  
Graham said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
