<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley's Civil Rights Plan Rebuked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley's suggestion that the 1964 Civil  
Rights Act be expanded to include sexual orientation drew a rebuke 
Friday from the head of the Democratic National Committee's black 
caucus, who called the suggestion ``ill-advised.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas state Rep. Al Edwards of Houston, head of the DNC caucus,  
asked the party's executive committee to pass a resolution against 
reopening the 1994 law they did so unanimously late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The DNC would urge that the 1964 Civil Rights Act, which is  
the benchmark for all other civil rights bills, not be reopened for 
debate or amendments that diminish its existing protections,'' the 
resolution said. 
</P>
<P>
	The full Democratic National Committee, which includes many  
supporters of Vice President Al Gore, could consider the resolution 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley is waging an insurgent's challenge to Gore for the 2000  
presidential nomination. On gay rights, Gore supports the narrower 
-- more achievable, he says -- Employment Non-Discrimination Act, or 
ENDA, pending in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Hauser, a spokesman for Bradley, said the measure was not  
at odds with Bradley's position because the former New Jersey 
senator doesn't favor any changes that would diminish the law's 
``existing protections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``My commitment to the Civil Rights Act will never waver''  
Bradley said. ``As president, I would never sign any law that would 
weaken that act and would use every tool at my disposal to advance 
racial harmony and justice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said that during the 1980s ``courageous Democrats sought  
to broaden the protections of the Civil Rights Act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Edwards suggested that any protections for gays and lesbians  
should be handled in separate legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics warn that opening that law to amendment now would give  
the Republican-led Congress a chance to gut its protections against 
racial, gender and religious discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Party leaders also said Friday that Democrats have an edge over  
Republicans on and that the party has been successful at erasing 
its debts from past years. 
</P>
<P>
	During an afternoon meeting, the party's rules panel:  
</P>
<P>
	--Denied South Carolina's request to have its primary on Feb. 19,  
the same day as the Republican primary, rather than later. South 
Carolina party officials pleaded for the change, saying that 
sharing the early date with Republicans would dramatically reduce 
expenses and keep the party more competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	--Told Arizona Democrats their plans to allow Internet voting  
from home in that state's primary were not a problem for the DNC if 
they made Internet voting an additional option to absentee voting 
by mail, and not a replacement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
