<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Rallies Democratic Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton rallied fellow Democrats to  
prepare for the 2000 campaign by touting economic accomplishments 
of his administration that he said have made America a better 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, I saw a survey the other day that said that times  
had been so good for so long, the American people couldn't remember 
when it was bad and tended to give everybody good ratings on the 
economy -- Bush, Hoover, the whole crowd,'' Clinton said Friday to 
laughter by members of the Democratic National Committee. He 
referred to former President Bush, father of the current Republican 
presidential front-runner, George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's big advantage in money and the polls over Vice President  
Al Gore and the increased strength of Gore's Democratic opponent, 
former Sen. Bill Bradley, have made some at the DNC's annual 
meeting nervous. 
</P>
<P>
	But Clinton reassured them that the election was a long way off.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long time between now and November of 2000,'' he said.  
``In June of 1992, you know where I was in the polls? Not behind. 
Third. Third.'' He said he would never forget his comeback victory 
in California primary June 2, 1992, and subsequent successes in New 
Jersey and Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Americans are not paying attention to politics now, the  
president said. ``For most people,'' he said, ``the election is not 
going on. If you live in Iowa or New Hampshire, it's already going 
on. If you live in Arkansas, you're still worried about the price 
of cattle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton reminded the crowd repeatedly of the economic  
accomplishments of his administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, my economy has made it possible for those  
Republicans to give George Bush all that money,'' he said with a 
grin. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Clinton generally has refrained from attacking Gov.  
Bush, he knocked the Republican for saying he would have signed the 
Republicans' $792 billion tax cut bill. The president vetoed the 
bill Thursday -- the same day Bush promised to increase military 
pay, accelerate high-tech weaponry and develop an anti-missile 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	``And I thought to myself, this is a nice speech but if I sign  
this tax bill that (Bush) is for, there won't be any money for the 
promise he just made,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush was not perturbed by the attention.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm flattered that once again the president has taken time  
from his busy schedule to talk about me and my policies, even 
before I've won my party's nomination,'' Bush told The Associated 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said after he and Gore were elected in 1992 they set out  
to fix the economy. ``And now we have the longest peacetime 
expansion in our history instead of the worst recession since the 
Great Depression.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Actually, Clinton's recollection was incorrect. The 1981-82  
recession during the Reagan administration was the worst since the 
Depression. In comparison, the 1990-91 recession during the Bush 
administration was relatively mild. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Friday, the DNC's executive committee approved a  
resolution supporting the 1964 Civil Rights Act and cautioning that 
the ``bill not be reopened for debate or amendments that diminish 
its existing protections.'' Bradley has suggested expanding the act 
to include gays and lesbians, but critics say that once open to 
amendments, the law could be gutted by the Republican Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	And the DNC's rules committee:  
</P>
<P>
	--Denied South Carolina's request to have its primary on Feb. 19,  
the same day as the Republican primary. South Carolina party 
officials pleaded for the change, saying that sharing the early 
date with Republicans would dramatically reduce expenses and keep 
the party more competitive. Now they likely will have a caucus that 
could be held no earlier than March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	--Told Arizona Democrats their plans to allow Internet voting  
from home in that state's primary were not a problem for the DNC if 
they made Internet voting an additional option to absentee voting 
by mail, and not a replacement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
