<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House GOP Wants China Firms List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Republican leaders complained Friday  
that President Clinton has yet to heed a 1998 law requiring a 
listing of companies tied to the Chinese military that are 
operating in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton sent lawmakers a letter earlier this month saying the  
Pentagon would be responsible for the list. But the Republicans 
said the Pentagon has shown little enthusiasm for the project. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is essential that the president comply,'' said Rep.  
Christopher Cox, R-Calif., chairman of the House GOP policy 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	``By violating this statutory obligation, the president shows  
contempt not only for the law, but for congressional oversight and 
the national security,'' Cox said. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter was signed by 10 GOP leaders, including Cox, House  
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Majority Leader Dick Armey, 
R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	As a part of a defense spending bill for the current fiscal  
year, which ends Thursday, Congress set a Jan. 15, 1999, deadline 
for a listing of Chinese Liberation Army-controlled companies doing 
business in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans contend the Chinese military controls a vast network  
of export businesses and other enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese government announced in July 1998 that the Chinese  
Army would no longer engage in commercial activity. 
</P>
<P>
	Thus, compiling a list of companies that may still have  
unofficial ties with the military is difficult and time-consuming, 
Pentagon officials said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
