<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Friday, Sept. 24, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Kinkel Pleads Guilty to Murder  
</P>
<P>
	EUGENE, Ore. (AP) -- Kip Kinkel abandoned an insanity defense and  
pleaded guilty today to murdering his parents at home and then 
killing two classmates in a shooting rampage at Springfield's 
Thurston High School. The 17-year-old could get a life sentence 
when Circuit Judge Jack Mattison sentences him for the May 1998 
attack. He told investigators after his arrest that he had ``no 
choice'' but to kill after shaming his parents by getting expelled 
from school. 

</P>
<P>
	East Timor Militia Leader Arrested  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- The multinational peacekeeping force in  
East Timor arrested a leader of a notorious anti-independence 
militia as a U.N. commission today considered investigating 
atrocities in the half-island territory. Troops and armored 
personnel carriers sealed off a central district near Dili's port 
today and conducted a house-to-house search for militiamen. The 
multinational force commander says his men will shoot to kill 
anyone who threatens them or East Timor's terrified citizens. 

</P>
<P>
	N. Korea To Freeze Tests for Talks  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- North Korea said today that it will freeze  
test-launches of its long-range missiles while its government is in 
talks with the United States. It is the first time since the United 
States agreed last week to ease sanctions against the North that 
Pyongyang formally announced that it would halt the missile 
testing. Pyongyang also said that the United States should lift all 
the economic sanctions that it has long maintained against the 
communist North, not just the few it has promised to abolish. South 
Korea's foreign ministry welcomed North Korea's decision. 

</P>
<P>
	Democrats Acknowledge Bradley Progress  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore has a big advantage in  
support from the Democratic Party establishment, but some party 
regulars acknowledge Bill Bradley's growing strength in the polls 
makes them uneasy about the consequences of a tough presidential 
primary fight. Carolyn Boyce, vice chairman of Idaho Democrats, 
yesterday said Gore will have to spend precious campaign money to 
fend off a nomination challenge from Bradley, while GOP 
front-runner George W. Bush is building up a huge campaign fund for 
the 2000 general election. 

</P>
<P>
	Former Nurse Taken Sick at Trial  
</P>
<P>
	BRAZIL, Ind. (AP) -- A former nurse charged with killing seven  
elderly patients with drug injections was hurried from court to a 
hospital today when he became ill during his trial. Orville Lynn 
Majors Jr. became ill about five minutes after his attorneys began 
presenting their case and was taken from the courthouse in an 
ambulance. Lead defense attorney I. Marshall Pinkus said paramedics 
told him Majors' blood pressure was elevated. He said Majors has 
high blood pressure and diabetes and has been receiving medication 
for the ailments while in jail. 

</P>
<P>
	Car Crashes Into NYC Restaurant  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A woman driving out of a midtown Manhattan  
parking garage lost control of her car and smashed through the 
front of a restaurant, killing one person and injuring more than 20 
others. ``People were sprawled all over,'' said firefighter Brian 
Kearney. ``It's the worst I've ever seen.'' The Mercedes-Benz 
accelerated suddenly yesterday evening and plowed through Arno, 
striking patrons before coming to a rest against the restaurant's 
rear wall. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Drops More Bombs on Chechnya  
</P>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian jets fired rockets today at  
targets around the capital of Chechnya in an escalation of its 
attacks on the breakaway republic that has raised fears of a 
full-scale war. The air raids followed attacks yesterday in which 
Russian planes pounded targets around Grozny in the first major 
raid on the city since the bloody 1994-96 Chechnya war. Thousands 
of people have fled as the raids have escalated. Today, a line of 
some 5,000 vehicles jammed a road leading to the neighboring 
republic of Ingushetia. 

</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom, Sprint Might Merge  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom and Sprint have been discussing a  
merger that would combine the nation's second- and third-largest 
long-distance carriers, The Wall Street Journal reported today. But 
the newspaper said significant obstacles remain that could scuttle 
a pact. MCI WorldCom ranks behind AT&AMP;T in the long-distance 
business and Sprint is No. 3. MCI and Sprint have about 30 percent 
of the U.S. consumer long-distance market, while AT&AMP;T holds about 
60 percent, the Journal said. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 54; Nasdaq Falls 35  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow Jones industrial  
average was down 54.46 points at 10,264.13. Decliners on the New 
York Stock Exchange lead advancers 1,916-841. The Nasdaq was down 
35.07 at 2,714.76. 

</P>
<P>
	Europeans Take 1st Ryder Cup Point  
</P>
<P>
	BROOKLINE, Mass. (AP) -- Colin Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie won  
the first match and Sergio Garcia won his first pairing with Tiger 
Woods today as Europe got off to a fast start in its defense of the 
Ryder Cup. Garcia gave the European team its second point when he 
and Jesper Parnevik teamed to beat Woods and Tom Lehman, helping 
Europe to a 2 1/2-1 1/2 lead after the four morning alternate shot 
matches. The United States needs 14 1/2 points to regain the cup from 
Europe, which has won the last two competitions. Europe can keep 
the cup if it gets 14 points or better. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by PAULINE MILLARD  







  	   	
