<HEADLINE> N.J. Man Guilty of NYPD Horse Punch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A man was found guilty Friday of punching a  
police horse in the nose during a rowdy protest rally last year. 
</P>
<P>
	James Hornacek, 35, could spend up to 90 days in jail for the  
misdemeanor crime. The New Jersey man is to be sentenced in two 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The electrician was among nearly 40,000 construction workers  
marching on a construction site where non-union workers reportedly 
were on the job when mounted police moved in. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornacek ``looked Police Officer John Reilly right in the face  
and punched his horse dead in the nose,'' Assistant District 
Attorney Carlos F. Ramirez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornacek claimed he just put his hands up to keep from being  
trampled. He rejected the prosecutor's offer of three days of 
community service for a guilty plea and chose to face trial. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury acquitted Hornacek of obstructing government  
administration but found him guilty of attempting to harm a police 
animal. 
</P>
<P>
	The police horse, Daily News 1, was retired after the incident  
and is living on a rural New York farm. 
  	   	
</P>
