<DOCNO> APW19990924.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 06:20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Dismisses Black Tobacco Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A federal judge has dismissed a lawsuit that  
accused the tobacco industry of violating the civil rights of 
blacks by specifically trying to sell them menthol cigarettes. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge John R. Padova ruled Thursday that federal  
civil rights laws do not bar tobacco product manufacturers from 
targeting a specific group of potential consumers in their 
advertising and marketing campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit filed last year claimed menthol cigarettes are  
heavily marketed in black communities and menthol compounds, when 
burned, create additional toxic substances that make such 
cigarettes more dangerous than other types. The plaintiffs included 
several black smokers and two black health groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs' lawyers said it was the first lawsuit brought  
against the tobacco industry under federal civil rights law rather 
than personal-injury or product-liability laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen A. Sheller said he and his clients would study the  
opinion before deciding whether to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	``In a way I'm not surprised, because we knew that this was a  
novel theory of law,'' Sheller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Government studies of smoking have suggested that menthol taste  
makes it easier for people to smoke longer and inhale more deeply, 
the lawsuit claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Although blacks account for about 10 percent of all U.S.  
smokers, the lawsuit said they make up as much as 70 percent of 
menthol cigarette consumers, and are 30 percent more likely to die 
of smoking-related illnesses than whites. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was based on the original Civil Rights Acts of 1866 and  
1870, passed to prevent the victimization of former slaves during 
Reconstruction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 15:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Gov. Edwards Faces More Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Former Gov. Edwin Edwards, already  
awaiting trial for allegedly rigging riverboat casino licenses, was 
indicted Friday on federal charges he took $100,000 to intervene on 
behalf of a failed insurance company. 
</P>
<P>
	Five other people were also indicted, including state Insurance  
Commissioner Jim Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Edwards was accused of charging the fee to set up a meeting  
between the owner of the insurance company and its court-appointed 
overseers after he was out of office. He was charged with fraud and 
conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI wiretaps of Edwards' phone calls apparently picked up  
conversations between Edwards and Brown about the Cascade Insurance 
Co., which failed in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown is the third straight Louisiana insurance commissioner to  
be indicted on federal charges. His two predecessors went to 
prison, and Brown was elected in 1991 as a reformer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I have been hit like a victim in a political drive-by  
shooting, because I was in the wrong place at the wrong time,'' 
Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was an innocent bystander caught up in an  
investigation of Edwards. Brown is running for a third term. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, Edwards said he simply charged a fee for a setting  
up a meeting. He did not return calls Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those also indicted were Cascade Insurance operator David  
Disiere and a judge. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cascade investigation is the second part of a probe of  
Edwards. In November, he and five others were indicted on charges 
of rigging the riverboat casino licensing process. Edwards has 
denied any wrongdong. His trial is set for January. 
</P>
<P>
	The new charges against Edwards carry up to 230 years in prison  
and nearly $12 million in fines. Brown could face up to 290 years 
in prison and fines of nearly $14 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 13:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Reacts to Soccer Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazilian soccer authorities have  
announced a series of suspensions and stadium closings in reaction 
to an increase in brawling, kicking, spitting and elbowing on the 
field and off. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sports Justice Tribunal suspended five players and two  
referees and ordered three stadiums temporarily shut. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those suspended Thursday night were Colombian star Freddy  
Rincon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will not accept the canalization of violence in Brazilian  
soccer, nor the lack of discipline,'' said tribunal president 
Sergio Zveiter. 
</P>
<P>
	Rincon, the playmaker of defending national champion  
Corinthians, drew a 30-day suspension for elbowing Flamengo striker 
Leandro. The referee didn't call the foul, but the tribunal saw it 
clearly on videotape. 
</P>
<P>
	Rincon also faces discipline for a subsequent run-in with Paulo  
Nunes of Palmeiras. TV cameras showed Rincon spitting in Nunes' 
face, and the Colombian later admitted he had become enraged when 
Nunes insulted his race and his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribunal also announced sanctions for violence that erupted  
during Atletico Mineiro's recent 2-1 loss to Vitoria. Both benches 
emptied and the game was briefly stopped, and the fighting resumed 
after the final whistle. 
</P>
<P>
	Fabio Costa and Otacilio of Vitoria and Lincoln and Galvan of  
Atletico Mineiro drew 30-day suspensions, as did referee Leonardo 
da Silva. Atletico's Independencia stadium was temporarily closed. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribunal punished referee Paulo Cesar Oliveira for failing  
to report an invasion of the field at Niteroi's Caio Martins 
stadium during a game between Botafogo and Internacional. Botafogo 
fans charged the field to attack their own players because the team 
was losing. Oliveira was suspended for 30 days and the stadium was 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 30-day suspension was imposed on Vasco da Gama's vice  
president Eurico Miranda, who charged onto the field to protest the 
expulsion of several players during a game with Parana. The club's 
stadium, Sao Januario, also was closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Confederation president Ricardo Teixeira blamed the increase in  
violence in part on poor officiating. He said a new, lower age 
limit had forced the many top referees into retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Teixeira also blamed coaches who encourage rough play and a  
rules change this year that suspends players only after five yellow 
cards instead of three. He said the confederation had proposed 
going back to the old way, but that clubs were opposed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 07:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Drops More Bombs on Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian jets fired rockets today at  
targets around the capital of Chechnya in an escalation of its 
attacks on the breakaway republic that has raised fears of a 
full-scale war. 
</P>
<P>
