<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MCI WorldCom, Sprint Might Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MCI WorldCom Inc. and Sprint Corp. have been  
discussing a merger that would combine the nation's second- and 
third-largest long-distance carriers, The Wall Street Journal 
reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	But the newspaper said no deal is imminent and that significant  
obstacles remain that could scuttle a pact. It cited unidentified 
people familiar with the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill White, a spokesman for Sprint, said the Westwood,  
Kan.-based company's policy is not to comment on speculation. 
Barbara Gibson, a spokesowman for MCI WorldCom, based in Clinton, 
Miss., said MCI also declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint alone is valued at nearly $40 billion, while its wireless  
business, which is separated into a distinct tracking stock, is 
valued at about $33 billion. MCI WorldCom's market valuation is 
about $151 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom ranks behind AT&AMP;T Corp. in the long-distance  
business and Sprint is No. 3. Any combination would be closely 
examined by regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI and Sprint have about 30 percent of the U.S. consumer  
long-distance market, while AT&AMP;T holds about 60 percent, the 
Journal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another obstacle could come from France Telecom and Germany's  
Deutsche Telekom AG, which each own 10 percent of Sprint and are 
partners with Sprint in Global One, a struggling international 
telecommunications venture. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-distance market has attracted a number of new entrants  
in recent years and could soon include the regional Bell operating 
companies, which are seeking permission to offer such service. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal said Sprint's nationwide wireless network is a major  
attraction for MCI WorldCom. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, MCI WorldCom engaged in serious negotiations  
to acquire the wireless company Nextel Communications Inc., but 
those discussions fell apart over price, the newspaper said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal said Sprint has held discussions with a handful of  
telecommunications companies, but said negotiations with MCI 
WorldCom have picked up recently. It said the talks are continuing. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
