<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Down on Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures prices edged lower but  
wheat futures were higher in early trading today on the Chicago 
Board of Trade ahead of what is expected to be a big harvest 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Forecasts for good weather throughout the soybean belt pressured  
soybean prices, which also fell sharply on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The ideal weather also pushed corn lower after it fell to  
eight-week lows the previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat opened higher after a report that Indonesia has banned  
some imports from Australia, which could be good news for U.S. 
exports. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 1 cent to $2.74 1/4 a bushel;  
December corn fell 1/4 cent to $2.08 a bushel; December oats fell 1/2 
cent to $1.12 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans fell 1 cent to $4.77 a 
bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .23 cent to 66.60 cents a pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .20 cent to 79.60 cents a pound; October 
lean hogs rose .10 cent to 46.20 cents a pound; February frozen 
pork bellies fell .17 cent to 59.25 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
