<DOCNO> APW19990924.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 03:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dems Edgy About Bradley Strength </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore has a big advantage in  
support from the Democratic Party establishment, but some party 
regulars acknowledge Bill Bradley's growing strength in the polls 
makes them uneasy about the consequences of a tough presidential 
primary fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolyn Boyce, vice chairman of Idaho Democrats, said Gore will  
have to spend precious campaign money to fend off a nomination 
challenge from Bradley, while GOP front-runner George W. Bush is 
building up a huge campaign fund for the 2000 general election. 
</P>
<P>
	``It diverts money and Democratic money is so limited,'' said  
Boyce, who was in town Thursday for a Democratic National Committee 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC is a stronghold of Gore support, but some in their ranks  
concede a bruising primary battle could hurt. In a stark contrast 
to the DNC's spring meeting, when Bradley was just beginning to 
make inroads against the vice president, party regulars were saying 
that Gore is vulnerable. 
</P>
<P>
	One Southern chairman said he had seen a ``sea change'' since  
spring and he worried that Gore's campaign was unprepared for a 
stiff challenge from Bradley, who is running neck-and-neck with 
Gore in recent polls in New Hampshire and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward Marcus, state chairman of the Connecticut Democratic  
Party, acknowledged the uneasiness among some party officials, 
saying, ``People who are neophytes tend to get shaken up.'' It's 
less worrisome, he said, for ``those who have been around for a 
while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is good for the party,'' said Iowa party chairman Rob  
Tully. ``I'm seeing a lot of people getting energized who were not 
involved in the past. I think part of that is due to Bill Bradley, 
who is touching people who might be coming back to the party. It 
will be a close race, but it will make Gore a better candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore had a much stronger presence than Bradley at the DNC  
meeting, with staff in every meeting, a political table set up near 
the registration desk and a meet-and-greet breakfast scheduled for 
today. He cannot afford to lose support within the DNC, while 
Bradley has never depended upon it, and hopes instead to draw less 
active Democrats and independents to his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, a former New Jersey senator and professional basketball  
player, has demonstrated an ability to raise money, with $7.5 
million in the bank at the end of June. Gore had $9.4 million. 
Bradley has also shown strength in polls in several states with 
early primaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've seen enough surveys to suggest that something is going on  
out there,'' said political analyst Stuart Rothenberg, who 
cautioned that it's far too early to focus on point margins. Party 
activists nevertheless are taking note of polls showing Bradley 
doing better than Gore in match-ups against Bush, partially due to 
Bradley's appeal with independents. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley has shown signs of making it a race in parts of the  
Northeast, and he got the endorsement Thursday of Sen. Daniel 
Patrick Moynihan of New York, the third senator to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why he preferred Bradley over Gore, Moynihan responded  
simply: ``Nothing is the matter with Gore, but he can't be 
elected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, meanwhile, has compiled endorsements from more than 100  
members of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gore has the support of most Democratic officeholders,'' said  
Merle Black, an Emory University political scientist. ``He would 
have the party establishment behind him in the South as well as the 
support of most black officeholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A CBS News poll out Thursday showed Bradley trailing Gore by a  
50 percent to 32 percent margin nationwide among Democrats and 
independents who lean Democratic. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent polls by Gallup and the Pew Research Center for the  
People &AMP; the Press suggest Gore's support is strongest among 
registered Democrats, blacks and women. Bradley runs closest to 
Gore among independents, men and the better educated. 
</P>
<P>
	The increased strength shown by Bradley may be more of a  
statement against Gore than for Bradley, said Andrew Kohut, 
director of the Pew poll, who says some Americans are tired of the 
Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people aren't too familiar with Bill Bradley,'' said  
Kohut. ``Our surveys show that most people, including Democrats, 
are not paying too much attention.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 10:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sales of Existing Homes Off 2.8 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sales of existing homes fell in August for the  
second straight month after hitting a record high in June. Still, 
sales are on track for a banner year. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Realtors said today that sales of  
existing single-family homes decreased by 2.8 percent in August to 
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 5.25 million units. 
</P>
<P>
	``Interest rates going up steadily over the last six months was  
probably the major factor,'' said Fred Flick, the association's 
vice president of economic research. 
</P>
<P>
	The average rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage was 7.94  
percent in August, up from 7.63 percent in July and 6.92 percent in 
August of 1998, the association said, citing figures from Freddie 
Mac, the mortgage company. 
</P>
<P>
	August's sales level was the lowest since May when 5 million  
units were sold. The 2.8 percent decline in August, followed a 4 
percent drop in sales in July. In June, sales hit an all-time high 
of 5.63 million units sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite August's decrease, association officials said they  
expect existing homes sales to post another record year in 1999. 
Last year's record was 4.97 million units. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5.25 million level of existing home sales in August are  
running about 9.2 percent higher than the sales level in August 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast was the only part of the country reporting a gain  
in sales in August, the association said. Sales there rose 7.6 
percent to an annual rate of 710,000 units. Sales were flat in the 
Midwest, unchanged at an annual rate of 1.18 million units. Sales 
in the South were down 1 percent to a rate of 2.05 million units 
and fell 12.1 percent in the West to a rate of 1.31 million units. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the national median sales price for existing homes  
rose 5.3 percent to a record $137,700 in August over the same month 
a year ago, the association said. The median is the point at which 
half the homes sell for less and half sell for more. 
</P>
<P>
	Flick attributed the increase in the median home price to strong  
demand, a healthy economy and a 29-year-low unemployment rate. 
``People can afford to pay,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The association's report follows a government report last week  
that construction of new homes and apartments rose 0.4 percent in 
August, leaving analysts marveling at the continued strength in 
housing despite rising mortgage rates. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 22:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grander Hendrix Memorial Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RENTON, Wash. (AP) -- For nearly three decades, Jimi Hendrix's  
flat, simple gravestone on a grassy hillside has drawn visitors 
from around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Within a year, the Hendrix family hopes to have a far grander  
memorial built at Greenwood Memorial Park for the guitarist who 
seared eardrums worldwide with hits such as ``Purple Haze,'' ``Hey 
Joe'' and ``Foxey Lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``So many people were behind it that we just decided to do it,''  
said Hendrix's father, James ``Al'' Hendrix. ``So many people come 
from all over the world (and) when they come here to Seattle, it's 
one of the first things they look for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Drawings unveiled Friday depicted a granite dome supported by  
nine pillars. Beneath the dome, surrounded by benches, would be a 
life-size 5-foot, 11 1/2-inch bronze statue of Hendrix as he appeared 
at the Woodstock music festival in 1969, the year before he died in 
London from an overdose of sleeping pills. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative dedication date is Sept. 18, 2000, the 30th  
anniversary of Hendrix's death. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 08:34:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hope for Quake Survivors Fading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- On a day traditionally reserved for joyous  
celebration, Taiwanese today vented anger at their government's 
bungling of rescue efforts and mourned the more than 2,100 people 
who perished in a deadly earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government reacted too slowly. It was many hours before  
they sent in troops to rescue victims and many hours until they 
sent helicopters,'' said Tsai Chia-ching as Buddhist monks chanted 
prayers for the dead at a Taipei memorial service. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was at least one bright note when rescuers pulled a  
6-year-old boy from a wrecked apartment building where he and his 
family had been buried for 87 hours. Rushed to a hospital, he was 
in stable condition, but suffering from trauma and dehydration. 
</P>
<P>
	The government admits it was not fully prepared to cope with a  
disaster of such magnitude, even though Taiwan is prone to periodic 
quakes. 
</P>
<P>
	After inspecting disaster areas Thursday, President Lee Teng-hui  
criticized the lack of central coordination and inefficient use of 
manpower and supplies, the official news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	He ordered the set up of a ``9-21'' earthquake rescue and relief  
operation center under direct Cabinet control. The earthquake 
struck Sept. 21. 
</P>
<P>
	What is normally a day of happiness, family reunions and  
feasting, the Autumn Moon Festival today was instead a time of 
grieving for many. The flag above the presidential palace in 
Taipei, the capital, flew at half-mast for the second day. 
</P>
<P>
	At a food pickup point, a big box of pineapple mooncakes sat  
open, another sad reminder that today should have been a holiday 
with family celebrations. 
</P>
<P>
	The round pastries are traditionally eaten during the festival,  
the Chinese equivalent of Thanksgiving in the United States, when 
the harvest moon is said to be at its fullest and most serene. 
</P>
<P>
	``Making a new, better life for us is the most important thing  
now,'' said Ong Chi-chai, gathering up donated food amid hundreds 
of tents in the stricken farming community of Chungliao. ``This 
holiday is no longer important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also ignoring the holiday were thousands of Taiwanese and  
foreign rescue workers who were finding few hopeful signs that many 
more survivors of Tuesday's earthquake could be found under 
collapsed buildings and landslides. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan has had more than 4,500 aftershocks, but they were  
gradually getting weaker. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 80 hours into the crisis, the focus began to shift  
from rescue to helping the hundreds of thousands of homeless 
survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	``Three days ago they knew where my friend was but still he is  
not out,'' said a man who would only give his surname Chung as he 
watched a crane dig at a pile of rubble that contained his school 
buddy. Rescuers had given up hope of finding the man alive. 
</P>
<P>
	The Disaster Management Center said today that 2,151 people had  
been killed, 8,140 were injured, 311 trapped under rubble and 33 
missing. 
</P>
<P>
	The official number of trapped stood in glaring contrast to  
media reports, often quoting on-site rescue workers, which said 
hundreds, if not more, were still buried under collapsed buildings 
and landslides. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan's third largest city, Taichung, was bracing for a major  
influx of the dead from isolated, mountain areas where mud and 
landslides reportedly buried large numbers of villagers. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials have said more than 100,000 people were  
displaced by the 7.6-magnitude earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people said it could take months, if not years, for their  
lives to return to normal. ``We're hoping the government will help 
us rebuild our homes,'' said farmer Chen Jung, who lost his home. 
</P>
<P>
	Chen was among some 500 homeless in Chungliao's tent city, which  
bustled today with people lugging boxes of fruit, diapers, bottled 
water and other donated supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid allegations that shoddy construction work was to blame for  
many deaths, authorities arrested a contractor responsible for 
three buildings that collapsed, burying about 100 people. The 
buildings had been made with substandard steel rods, and 
authorities found crumpled up vegetable oil cans had been used in 
place of bricks. 
</P>
<P>
	The official Central News Agency said teams from 25 countries  
and international organizations were working in Taiwan, with more 
on the way. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politically isolated Taiwan has felt the warmth from the  
international community following the natural disaster,'' the 
agency said, referring to the fact that many countries cut off 
diplomatic ties under pressure from China. 
</P>
<P>
	The government announced it would accept a $100,000 donation  
from the Chinese Red Cross but rejected offers of rescue and 
medical personnel, saying teams from many countries were already in 
place. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan also turned down official Beijing offers of material  
assistance. Taiwan rejects China's claim that the island nation is 
a province of the mainland and will one day be integrated. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 08:34:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
