<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Chrysler Boss To Retire in Shakeup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- The well-regarded president of DaimlerChrysler  
AG's Chrysler division, Thomas Stallkamp, will retire Dec. 31 as 
part of a shakeup in the company's top management. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said today that Stallkamp, 53, will leave as the  
head of DaimlerChrysler's North American unit and be replaced by 
James Holden, executive vice president for sales and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	``With our North American sales and profits strong, a new labor  
agreement negotiated and business systems defined, I believe this 
is an appropriate time to explore new opportunities for myself and 
my family,'' Stallkamp said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler also announced it was trimming its management  
board from 17 members to 14 and reorganizing the board's duties. 
Co-chairmen Juergen Schrempp and Robert Eaton said the moves would 
``keep up the momentum'' of the merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Also leaving the board is Theodor Cunningham, who will become  
executive vice president for global sales and marketing. The 
current head of the commercial vehicle division, Kurt Lauk, will 
also leave the company effective Sept. 30. And Heiner Tropitzch, 
head of human resources, will be replaced by Guenther Fleig. 
</P>
<P>
	Schrempp and Eaton praised Stallkamp's role in combining the two  
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has played a critical role in making our historic merger  
work, helping set DaimlerChrysler on a course to realize all the 
promise inherent in this landmark business combination,'' Eaton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In an e-mail to employees today, Stallkamp said he was concerned  
his retirement might be seen as a sign of a rift between the German 
and American sides of the company. He said he had left on good 
terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``In any merger, issues may arise as a result of different  
styles or corporate cultures. But, these issues have been worked 
out, and will be worked out in the future, because they are not the 
result of personalities or national differences,'' Stallkamp said 
in the e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Stallkamp joined the company in 1980, and rose through the  
ranks, taking over as Chrysler Corp. president in January 1998. He 
had been credited with leading a drive to cut billions in costs and 
improving Chrysler's relations with suppliers. 
</P>
<P>
	He got the job of president a week before Eaton, then chairman  
of Chrysler Corp., began negotiations with Daimler-Benz AG. 
</P>
<P>
	As the merger deal came together in the summer and fall of 1998,  
Stallkamp threw himself into making it work. He took German 
language classes and learned how to sleep on a red-eye flight 
across the Atlantic, conduct a full day's business in Stuttgart, 
and return to Detroit in time to fall asleep that night -- all 
without jet lag. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview last October, he said Chrysler needed the merger  
to become one of what he called ``the Global 5'' automakers: 
General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co., Toyota Motor Corp., 
Volkswagen AG and DaimlerChrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	``The folks at Daimler-Benz and the folks at Chrysler are a lot  
more alike than you might think,'' he said in another interview 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time of the merger, Stallkamp dismissed the idea that one  
company and its culture would inevitably dominate. Chrysler was 
known for having a more freewheeling, open culture, in contrast to 
the more traditional, top-down management style practiced at 
Daimler-Benz. 
</P>
<P>
	He also rejected the view that the deal represented Daimler's  
buyout of Chrysler. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's hardly an apt description,'' Stallkamp said. ``Really,  
it's a birth, the birth of a new hybrid company, one that will have 
an all-new stock, a new name and corporate identity, equal 
representation in senior management from each of the parent 
companies, and dual headquarters.'' 
</P>
<P>
	News of the move helped push DaimlerChrysler's stock to a record  
low closing price in trading Thursday, falling $3.93 3/4 to $66.25 in 
dealings on the New York Stock Exchange. Auto industry analysts 
said the reports on Stallkamp's future, along with concern that 
DaimlerChrysler might miss its financial goals, worried investors. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the shares on the Frankfurt stock exchange edged higher  
today after news of the shakeup was released. The shares were up 
0.6 percent at noon. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the changes announced today, DaimlerChrysler will manage  
its automotive operations in three divisions: the 
Mercedes-Benz/smart division, headed by Juergen Hubbert, the 
Chrysler division, headed by Holden, and the commercial vehicle 
division headed by Dieter Zetsche. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having completed our integration in only 16 months, we are now  
one company. It is vital that we keep up the momentum that we built 
in the integration process to ensure that we maintain our lead in 
technology and innovation,'' Schrempp and Eaton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced that Mike Jackson, the head of  
Mercedes-Benz USA, has resigned and will be replaced by Paul 
Halata, head of Mercedes-Benz UK. 
</P>
<P>
	Several key executives, including Schrempp, last month said the  
company was planning to reorganize and reduce the size of the 
company's board of management. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've known from day one and we so indicated that the board of  
management was actually too large for the long term, but we felt it 
was necessary to have everyone involved initially,'' Eaton said 
today. ``We felt it was now time to move on to the next stage in 
the organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton is scheduled to leave in two years, and said today he had  
no immediate plans to retire. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
