<HEADLINE> George Magazine To Stay Alive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A co-owner of George magazine is making plans to  
keep the publication alive, but with fewer issues each year, 
following the death of John F. Kennedy Jr., its charismatic founder 
and editor. 
</P>
<P>
	There had been concerns after Kennedy's death in a July 16  
airplane crash about whether the four-year-old magazine could 
survive without him. 
</P>
<P>
	Hachette Filipacchi Magazines, which shared ownership of the  
magazine with Kennedy, announced Friday the magazine would cut back 
to 10 issues a year from 12 next year but would guarantee 
advertisers a larger circulation. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting with the February 2000 issue, advertisers are being  
promised circulation of 450,000 per issue of the magazine that 
mixed political commentary and celebrity profiles, up 12.5 percent 
from the current 400,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Kliger, president and chief executive of Hachette  
Filipacchi Magazines, said the reduced frequency ``reflects a need 
to ensure that each issue received the maximum resources and 
attention that it deserves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to the continued success of George, and we  
are aggressively pursuing all roads to that end,'' Kliger said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The new circulation guarantee is higher than the nearly 404,000  
which the Audit Bureau of Circulations says George achieved in the 
last six months of 1998, the latest period for which such figures 
are available. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to boost circulation, the magazine recently cut its  
yearly subscription price to $9.97 from $17.76, Hachette spokesman 
Keith Estabrook said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hachette and the Kennedy family are in continuing discussions  
about how to proceed with the magazine but have not yet reached any 
agreement, Estabrook said. ``We are committed to continuing to 
publish,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hachette Filipacchi Magazines publishes 28 consumer magazines  
including Car and Driver, Elle, Mirabella, Premiere and Woman's 
Day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
