<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Friday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
 *Allstate Corp., down 3 1/2 at 28 1/4    	
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest publicly held insurance company expects to  
report third-quarter operating earnings that will be below Wall 
Street analysts' estimates. Allstate blamed the shortfall on 
projected higher catastrophe losses from Hurricane Floyd and 
reserve strengthening for asbestos-related losses. 

</P>
<P>
 *Watsco Inc., down 1 7/16 at 11 1/2    	
</P>
<P>
	The Miami-based company, which distributes air conditioning,  
heating and refrigeration equipment, expects its third-quarter 
earnings to fall below Wall Street analysts' estimates. Watsco 
attributed the shortfall Hurricane Floyd and lower demand for air 
conditioners. 

</P>
<P>
 *Sprint Corp., up 2 7/8 at 54  
</P>
<P>
 *MCI WorldCom Inc., down 2 3/8 at 76 1/8 on the Nasdaq 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported that MCI WorldCom and Sprint  
are discussing a merger that would combine the nation's second- and 
third-largest long-distance carriers. Spokesmen for both companies 
declined to comment. 

</P>
<P>
 *National Westminster Bank PLC, up 27 13/16 at 128 13/16    	
</P>
<P>
	Bank of Scotland PLC launched a hostile $34.3 billion takeover  
bid for the larger NatWest, which NatWest quickly rejected as 
inadequate. The proposed takeover would be the largest in British 
banking history. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	
</P>
<P>
 *Kroll-O'Gara, down 11 1/2 at 14 5/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The Fairfield, Ohio, investigative and security-services  
provider hired the investment firm Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. to advise it 
on strategic alternatives, including the possible sale of the 
company. Kroll also said it will put off acquisitions it had 
planned for the third quarter and lowered its third-quarter 
earnings estimates. 

</P>
<P>
 *Qualcomm Inc., up 2 7/8 at 189 1/2  
</P>
<P>
 *Lucent Technologies Inc., down 1/2 at 64 3/4 on the NYSE 
</P>
<P>
	Lucent Technologies Inc. signed a co-development agreement with  
Qualcomm to build wireless network equipment. Qualcomm, a San Diego 
developer of digital-wireless-communications technology, will 
supply chips and software, to be incorporated into Lucent's 
wireless base-station equipment. Trials are expected by the middle 
of next year. 

</P>
<P>
 *Intuit Corp., down 6 1/2 at 94 1/16    	
</P>
<P>
	The Mountain View, Calif., maker of personal-finance software  
said its chief executive officer, Bill Harris, resigned and will be 
succeeded temporarily by its chairman and former CEO, Bill 
Campbell. Mr. Harris will remain on the company's board, but Mr. 
Campbell will run day-to-day operations. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
