<DOCNO> APW19990924.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 19:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds 5, Cardinals 4  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Sean Casey's check-swing single drove in a  
pair of runs during a four-run sixth inning Friday night that 
rallied the Cincinnati Reds to a 5-4 victory over the St. Louis 
Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds kept Mark McGwire stuck at 59 homers and overcame a  
three-run deficit set up by their throwing errors to make up ground 
in the NL playoff chase. 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati moved within a game of New York for the NL wild card  
as the Mets lost in Philadelphia 3-2 Friday night. The Reds began 
the day 2 1/2 behind Houston in the NL Central. 
</P>
<P>
	Things looked grim in the first inning, when the Reds made a  
wild throw into each dugout and let in a pair of unearned runs. 
Cincinnati has committed eight errors in its last three games. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals' lead grew to 4-1 in the fifth when Adam Kennedy  
had a sacrifice fly off Steve Parris (11-2) and the Reds chose to 
intentionally walk McGwire to face Ray Lankford, who lined a 
run-scoring single on the next pitch. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Hammonds led off the sixth with a homer, his third hit  
off Darren Oliver, and the Reds sent nine batters to the plate in 
all against four pitchers to take the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds loaded the bases with one out, and Rick Croushore (3-6)  
struck out Barry Larkin on three pitches to leave it to Casey. He 
checked his swing on a pitch from Mike Mohler, accidentally hitting 
a soft liner to the opposite field for a pair of runs that tied it. 
Greg Vaughn followed with a first-pitch single off Heathcliff 
Slocumb for a 5-4 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Danny Graves pitched out of a threat in the eighth by inducing a  
double play grounder, then finished for his 26th save. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire went 0-for-2 and walked twice. Sammy Sosa also failed to  
homer in the Cubs' 9-0 victory over Pittsburgh, leaving him two 
homers ahead of McGwire for the major league lead. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire's first-inning grounder to Larkin at shortstop started a  
run of defensive lapses by the Reds. Larkin threw the ball into the 
Reds' dugout, and second baseman Pokey Reese threw a ball into the 
Cardinals' dugout after McGwire rounded third on Lankford's infield 
single. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Larkin charged and missed Thomas Howard's grounder for  
a run-scoring single and a 2-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Vaughn's RBI single made it 2-1 in the third. Vaughn had led the  
Reds' late run at the playoffs by hitting 13 homers in September -- 
one shy of the franchise record -- and driving in 30 runs. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* McGwire is 5-for-30 career in Cincinnati with four singles  
and one homer. ... The Reds activated 1B Hal Morris off the DL. 
Morris broke his right wrist on Aug. 26. ... Casey flipped 
backwards over the railing of the Reds' dugout while trying to 
catch a foul in the fifth inning and landed hard on his back. He 
got up and jogged back to his position smiling. ... Manager Jack 
McKeon said before the game that he'd like a multiyear contract. 
He's been working on one-year deals. The front office is waiting 
for ownership to change in early October before considering 
personnel matters for next year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
