<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley, Gore Tied in N.H. Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- Another poll shows former New Jersey Sen.  
Bill Bradley has pulled into a statistical tie with Vice President 
Al Gore in the Democratic presidential contest in New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	The TIME/CNN poll released Friday shows Bradley favored by 44  
percent of likely voters in New Hampshire's Democratic primary next 
February, compared with 41 percent for Gore. The difference was 
within the poll's margin of error of 4 percentage points, putting 
the candidates in a statistical tie. 
</P>
<P>
	The gap was wider nationally, with 52 percent of Democratic  
voters favoring Gore, compared with 29 percent for Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	In a similar poll last week, 46 percent of likely voters in New  
Hampshire's first-in-the-nation Feb. 8 primary supported Gore, 
compared with 41 percent who supported Bradley. The WMUR-CNN poll's 
margin of error was 5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest poll, Bradley scored higher with men -- 50 percent  
versus 38 percent -- in New Hampshire, among college graduates --55 
percent versus 32 percent -- and among people earning more than 
$75,000 -- 56 percent versus 33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore did better among voters under age 34 -- 52 percent versus 33  
percent -- and those earning less than $35,000 -- 48 percent versus 
34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly half of Gore's New Hampshire supporters -- 46 percent --  
said there was some chance they would decide to vote for Bradley 
instead. Thirty-five percent of Bradley's supporters said there was 
some chance they would vote for Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll of 516 likely voters in the Democratic primary was  
conducted Sept. 21-23 by Yankelovich Partners. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
