<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 18:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cards' DT Smith Ends Holdout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- The Arizona Cardinals resolved two long,  
often-bitter contract disputes Friday when defensive tackle Mark 
Smith accepted the team's minimum offer and rookie offensive tackle 
L.J. Shelton agreed to a five-year deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith accepted the $325,000 tender offer minus the salary he  
would have received for the two games he missed. That means the 
third-year pro will get just under $285,000, far less than the more 
than $1 million he had originally demanded. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said he was ready to play football,'' Smith's agent, Gil  
Thompson, said. ``It was an instinctive type of thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton, the No. 21 overall pick from Eastern Michigan and son  
of former NBA player Lonnie Shelton, is the last first-round draft 
choice to sign. Terms were not revealed, and his agent, Lamont 
Smith, did not return calls to his office. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton had held out for a four-year contract or a five-year  
deal with incentive clauses or a fifth year that would be voidable 
had he met certain conditions. Those embellishments have almost 
always been rejected by conservative Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton apparently grew anxious as the season began and agreed  
to a straight deal with no incentives or voidable clauses. 
</P>
<P>
	``The season starting always has a lot to do with tugging at the  
strings. He's probably sitting at home watching games,'' general 
manager Bob Ferguson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton had been considered a strong candidate to start had he  
been with the team from the start of training camp. Now he faces an 
uphill battle to even get playing time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously he's a long way behind,'' Ferguson said. ``He's the  
kind of player who's going to come in and compete, but there are 
players already here who are competing at a pretty high level. 
Hopefully within time he'll pick up things but he's got a long way 
to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lamont Smith had filed a grievance against the Cardinals  
accusing them of unfair bargaining, but the grievance was 
dismissed. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Smith had virtually no leverage in his holdout. He couldn't  
sign with another team and had to be available to play for at least 
six games this season to count toward him becoming a restricted 
free agent next year and an unrestricted free agent in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's play didn't help him much either. Without Mark Smith,  
Arizona is sixth in the NFL in total defense after two games. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, the Cardinals offered $500,000, but withdrew that  
offer and retreated to the $325,000 Smith was due under NFL rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson declined to say the holdout was a mistake or that his  
client regrets not accepting the $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just a small contract battle in a war,'' Thompson  
said. ``I'd prefer to look forward instead of backward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Vince Tobin said he will have to see how Smith looks when  
he gets to Arizona before making a decision on whether to suit him 
up for Monday night's game against the San Francisco 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no idea what kind of shape he's in,'' Tobin said. ``He  
hasn't seen any of our defenses. ... It probably will be awfully 
hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith had 56 tackles, 31 solos, as a rookie. Last year, as a  
starter, he led the team in sacks with nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Greene, the Hall of Fame defensive lineman who as Cardinals'  
defensive line coach worked extensively to make Smith a force in 
the NFL, said Smith has hurt himself greatly by the holdout. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had great hopes for Mark, as did everybody in the  
organization,'' Greene said. ``I was extremely disappointed that he 
wasn't here during mini-camp and training camp. I thought he needed 
that to move to the next level. I was disappointed and angry. Now 
that he's here, I've got to get over it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 19:40:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillies 3, Mets 2  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mike Lieberthal's RBI single off Armando  
Benitez capped a two-run eighth-inning rally that gave the 
Philadelphia Phillies a 3-2 victory over the Mets on Friday night, 
New York's fourth straight loss. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets, still stunned from their three losses to NL  
East-leading Atlanta, further jeopardized their playoff hopes by 
blowing a 2-1 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	After Masato Yoshii pitched seven strong innings, Dennis Cook  
started the eighth and walked pinch-hitter Kevin Sefcik. Cook 
kicked the mound angrily when he was replaced by Turk Wendell, who 
retired Doug Glanville and Ron Gant. 
</P>
<P>
	But manager Bobby Valentine brought in right-handed closer  
Benitez (3-3) to face the left-handed hitting Bobby Abreu, who is 
second in the league in batting. With first base open, after a 
steal, Abreu doubled home Sefcik on a full count for the tying run. 
</P>
<P>
	Lieberthal hit Benitez's first pitch to right, scoring Abreu  
with the go-ahead run for the Phillies' fifth win in 28 games. 
Scott Aldred pitched a perfect ninth for his first save. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets began the night four games behind the Braves in the  
division and two ahead of Cincinnati for the wild card. The Braves 
were in Montreal on Friday night, while Cincinnati played host to 
St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Grahe (1-3) allowed two runs -- one earned -- and nine hits in  
eight innings with no walks and two strikeouts. It was his first 
victory since 1995 and longest outing since 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Robin Ventura hit his 31st homer and John Olerud -- 1-for-13  
against the Braves -- made it 2-1 with an RBI single in the fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshii allowed one run and four hits. He walked two and struck  
out three. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets' nightmare at Turner Field prompted a pep talk by  
Valentine following a 6-3 loss Thursday. It worked, until the 
eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team has been addressed,'' Valentine said. ``They're good  
and they won. We're good and we lost. They're not perfect, and 
neither are we.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York had runners at first and second in three straight  
innings and failed to get any of them in. After Ventura's one-out 
homer in the second, Darryl Hamilton and Roger Cedeno both singled 
before Rey Ordonez grounded into a 1-6-3 double play. 
</P>
<P>
	Olerud struck out with runners at first and second in the third,  
and Rickey Henderson was thrown out trying to steal third on a 
double steal for another double play. Ordonez grounded out with 
runners at first and second and two outs in the fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies tied it when Glanville broke up Yoshii's perfect  
game with a leadoff double in the fourth and scored on Mike 
Lieberthal's RBI single. 
</P>
<P>
	Olerud made it 2-1 and ended New York's string of stranding  
runners with a two-out RBI single in the fifth that scored Yoshii, 
who reached on third baseman Kevin Jordan's throwing error. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* Henderson, who ran through a stop sign and was thrown out  
at home in Thursday's loss, tested his tight hamstring before the 
game and played. He was 2-for-4. ... A crowd that included many 
Mets fans was late arriving because of a busy night in South 
Philadelphia. Across the street, the Rangers and Flyers played an 
NHL exhibition game at the First Union Center, and Bruce 
Springsteen gave a concert at the Spectrum. ... Mets LHP Kenny 
Rogers, originally not expected to start in this series, will pitch 
on Saturday after testing his injured left hamstring. ``He's 
probably better now than he was for his last two starts,'' 
Valentine said. ... With a double in the fourth, Glanville is four 
hits away from becoming the first Phillies player with 200 hits 
since Pete Rose had 208 in 1979. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
