<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Allstate Stock Plunges 11 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Allstate Corp. shares tumbled 11 percent in heavy  
trading Friday after the insurer, hit by stiff competition that has 
forced auto coverage rates lower industrywide, revised its 
second-half earnings outlook sharply downward. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest publicly held insurance company cited  
higher catastrophe losses, including flooding and other damage 
claims from Hurricane Floyd, among a number of reasons for the 
earnings warning. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts downplayed the effect of Floyd on Allstate and  
other insurers and said competition on the Internet and elsewhere 
is a far bigger factor in scaled-back earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``An intensified operating environment, especially in the  
automobile insurance area, is putting pressure on underwriting 
margins of the key players in the industry,'' said Mike Lewis, an 
analyst for Warburg Dillon Read in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one competitor, Progressive Corp., has taken a similar  
hit to its stock after saying it would miss earnings expectations 
due to price cuts and changes in the auto industry. Analysts said 
Safeco, State Farm and Geico are among others affected. 
</P>
<P>
	After plummeting 17 percent early in the session, Allstate stock  
ended the day down $3.50 at $28.25 a share Friday on the New York 
Stock Exchange. More than 16.7 million shares changed hands, more 
than six times the average daily volume of 2.6 million shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Allstate said its earnings would be well below analysts'  
estmates for the final half of this year, projecting higher losses 
for catastrophe coverage and rising reserves set aside for 
asbestos-related claims. It also cited increased expenses to 
support the company's new marketing campaign and continued 
investments in technology. 
</P>
<P>
	It is among U.S. insurers who will pay homeowners and businesses  
a combined $1.3 billion for insured property damages wrought by 
Hurricane Floyd, according to preliminary calculations released 
Friday by Insurance Services Office Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said third-quarter operating earnings would be 50  
cents to 55 cents a share -- down from 76 cents for the same period 
a year ago and well under the 78 cents expected by analysts 
surveyed by First Call Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Fourth-quarter earnings could be between 65 cents and 73 cents a  
share depending on weather-related developments, said Allstate, 
headquartered in the Chicago suburb of Northbrook. Analysts had 
forecast 81 cents a share, up 3 cents from the fourth quarter of 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Edward M. Liddy, Allstate's chairman, president and chief  
executive officer, said there is no threat to long-term earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Intense competition in the personal lines industry coupled  
with a rise in the cost of doing business is putting pressure on 
our near-term earnings,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Auto insurers, benefiting from low inflation and a reduction in  
claims as the percentage of young drivers declines, have been 
lowering rates in an intensified scramble for business. 
</P>
<P>
	Allstate executives told analysts in a conference call Friday  
that the company plans to undertake more aggressive marketing, 
spending more on advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans by the end of the year to announce actions to  
improve its strategic and competitive position after completing a 
review of its cost structure and prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Management up 'til now has done a very admirable job in a  
tough market,'' said Adam Klauber, an analyst for Cochran, Caronia 
&AMP; Co. in Chicago. ``I think they have made all the right strategic 
moves, but they're fighting in a very tough market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Allstate is the second-biggest U.S. company in personal-lines  
insurance -- automobile, home and life insurance -- behind privately 
held State Farm. It had 1998 revenues of $25.9 billion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
