<HEADLINE> New Bids Sought for Thai Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- The government is calling for new bids  
for the design and construction of an addition to Bangkok's main 
airport, a newspaper reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The move comes less than two weeks after bidders alleged there  
were irregularities in earlier bidding. 
</P>
<P>
	The call for new tenders will be issued within 45 days, The  
Nation reported. 
</P>
<P>
	A consortium led by a large Thai construction company, Ch.  
Karnchang, had been named the provisional winner of the contract 
after several major rivals were eliminated for failing to meet a 
financing requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The four foreign-linked consortiums that were ruled out during  
the pre-qualification stage said the requirement, mandating a 
certain kind of bank guarantee, was highly unusual. 
</P>
<P>
	Their main foreign members were Bouygues of France, Nishimatsu  
Construction of Japan, ABB Airport Technology of Germany and Thai 
Obayashi. 
</P>
<P>
	The original tender call had included a suggested median price  
of $87.8 million for the project. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
