<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 15:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise Again as Stocks Tumble / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices crept higher Friday as stocks fell  
for a fourth straight day, leading more and more investors to seek 
shelter in less volatile fixed-income markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 9/32  
points, or $2.81 1/4 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, fell to 5.96 percent from 5.98 
percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market swoon has pushed the 30-year Treasury's yield  
below 6 percent for the first time in nearly four weeks. The last 
time the yield on the long-term Treasury was lower was Aug. 26, 
when it closed at 5.90 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors often flee to the relative safety of government-backed  
bonds when the stock market is unsettled. The Dow Jones industrial 
average has shed more than 1,000 points, or by more than 9 percent, 
since reaching a high of 11,326.04 on Aug. 26. The blue-chip 
average closed down 39.26 Friday at 10279.33. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged to up 1/16 point, while intermediate maturities rose 
3/32 to 7/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Friday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
fell to 4.77 percent, as the discount fell 0.02 percentage point 
from Thursday to 4.65 percent. Six-month yields held at 5.01 
percent as the discount was unchanged at 4.82 percent. One-year 
yields slipped to 5.13 percent as the discount fell 0.03 percentage 
point to 4.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 5.25 percent from 5.31 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 7/8 to 113 13/32. The average yield to 
maturity of the index fell to 5.83 percent from 5.89 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
