<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ohio Mine Collapse Kills Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLARINGTON, Ohio (AP) -- The roof of a coal mine collapsed  
Friday, killing two miners and injuring several others who were 
working 700 feet underground. 
</P>
<P>
	The roof fell about 2 p.m. at the Consolidation Coal Co. mine,  
which was once one of the state's largest and is now in the process 
of being closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Tom Hoffman, a vice president for parent company Consol Energy  
in Pittsburgh, said eight people were in the mine but only three 
were near the site of the accident. Monroe County Sheriff's Deputy 
Andrea Smith said nine workers in all were involved. 
</P>
<P>
	At least three miners had been taken to hospitals, including one  
who suffered severe shoulder injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The collapse affected a ``very small portion'' of the mine, said  
Tom Hoffman, a vice president for Consol Energy in Pittsburgh, the 
parent company of Consolidation Coal Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoffman said authorities had not determined what caused the  
collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the collapse had not been determined.  
</P>
<P>
	Consol stopped mining coal in March, but has had small crew on  
duty since then to ship the remaining inventory and to close the 
mine. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four people work at the mine, which was established in  
1971. 
</P>
<P>
	Clarington is in southeast Ohio, about 22 miles south of  
Wheeling, W.V. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
