<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 11:20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sen. Faces Harassment Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELENA, Mont. (AP) -- Four years after Oregon Republican Bob  
Packwood was forced from the Senate due to allegations of sexual 
harassment, the issue has arisen again -- this time involving Sen. 
Max Baucus of Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Christine Niedermeier, Baucus' chief of staff who was fired in  
August, today filed a formal sexual harassment complaint against 
her former boss in Congress, a source close to the case told The 
Associated Press on condition of anonymity. Niedermeier contends 
she was fired as retribution for shunning Baucus' sexual advances 
for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus, a four-term Democrat, had said she was fired for her  
brutal management style that made work intolerable for the rest of 
his staff. 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus -- who in 1994, during the Packwood scandal stepped  
forward to endorse a bill that would make Congress subject to the 
same workplace laws as businesses -- has vehemently denied any 
sexual harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me state, unequivocally, that I have never, under any  
circumstances, sexually harassed Christine Niedermeier,'' he said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Niedermeier, who is single, said Baucus never touched her  
improperly, but started hitting on her shortly after she went to 
work for him in May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first I thought I was imagining things, because I have  
never been in a workplace before where I had been harassed,'' said 
Ms. Niedermeier, 47. ``It became more frequent. It took different 
forms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus, 57, and married to his second wife, would comment  
frequently on her appearance in front of others, constantly quiz 
her about her boyfriends, who she was dating and where she would go 
on dates, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	He asked her to take weekend trips together and compared her to  
his wife, Wanda, Ms. Niedermeier said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I gave him every possible signal I could to let him know I  
wasn't interested,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus has refused to comment on her specific examples.  
</P>
<P>
	Baucus said he fired Ms. Niedermeier when confronted with a  
revolt by staff fed up with her belittling and abusive treatment. 
He said a petition complaining about her was signed by 36 of 39 
staffers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I resigned because of Ms. Niedermeier,'' said Jan Metzmaker,  
former field director for one of Baucus' offices in Montana. ``It 
was way too stressful. It was too difficult to work for her and be 
sane and have a family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-eight female former Baucus employees signed a letter  
defending him as a ``man of highest integrity'' being subjected to 
``unwarranted personal attack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baucus said he gave Niedermeier several chances to improve her  
relations with the staff in Washington and Montana. But in the end, 
he said his only regret was that he did not fire her sooner. 
</P>
<P>
	Montana's senior senator said he supports the complaint system  
created in the wake of the Packwood scandal by the Congressional 
Accountability Act of 1995. He also said he welcomed the chance to 
defend himself in court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because I have nothing to hide, I want this issue fully aired  
and resolved in a forum where Christine will be required to tell 
the truth,'' he said. ``If she believes that I sexually harassed 
her, then she should lay her case out on the table -- and under 
oath.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Niedermeier, a two-time congressional candidate in  
Connecticut, said she's willing to do that. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one would ever want to lie about this,'' she said. ``Why  
would I want to lie about something that would damage, if not 
destroy, my career?'' 
</P>
<P>
	If successful, Ms. Niedermeier could receive damages for lost  
wages and her old job back. If the case goes to court, she could 
also demand punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Going to court also would move the issue behind closed doors,  
because the administrative proceedings are confidential by law -- 
and they could take more than a year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
