<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 07:59:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rooney Explains Column </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Andy Rooney has taken steps to clear up a little  
wreck of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``60 Minutes'' curmudgeon set tongues wagging with a  
newspaper column this week that suggested that the most beautiful 
woman in TV news ``looks as if she had been in a minor automobile 
accident'' because of plastic surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	He didn't name any names. That's because, Rooney said Thursday,  
he wasn't talking about anybody. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was writing metaphorically,'' he said. ``I didn't have  
anybody really in mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his column about aging, Rooney said that most people are more  
attractive if they look their age instead of synthetically trying 
to improve their appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	That's something many people in his business can't accept, he  
noted. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most beautiful -- OK, THE most beautiful -- woman in  
television news had a job done on herself a few years ago and, 
while she doesn't look bad, she does not look the same or as good 
to me as when she had what must have seemed to her to be 
shortcomings,'' he wrote. ``She looks as if she had been in a minor 
automobile accident.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gossip columnists -- and undoubtedly a few of Rooney's female  
colleagues -- immediately began the guessing game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suppose there must be 20 women in television who thought I  
was talking about them,'' Rooney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some speculated Rooney meant Diane Sawyer, his former colleague  
on ``60 Minutes.'' Not so fast, the New York Post's Page Six opined 
on Thursday, tossing the names Barbara Walters, Christiane 
Amanpour, Maria Shriver, Jane Pauley, Lesley Stahl and Connie Chung 
into the mix. 
</P>
<P>
	Yikes!  
</P>
<P>
	With so many women to potentially offend, Rooney put a stop to  
it. He said he regretted writing it: ``I didn't mean to call this 
much attention to myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And he offered a verbal bouquet to Ms. Sawyer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Diane is a good friend of mine and I like her a lot,'' he  
said. ``I think she's not only one of the great people in 
television but she's one of the good people, too. She's as smart as 
she is beautiful.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990924.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-24 17:00:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reggie Jackson May Join Angels Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Since his group's attempt to buy the Oakland  
Athletics stalled, Reggie Jackson may try to become involved in the 
purchase of another of his former teams, the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson reportedly has discussed joining billionaires Henry  
Nicholas III and Henry Samueli in an attempt to buy the Angels from 
the Walt Disney Co. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know Nicholas and Samueli and we have had a short visit,''  
Jackson told The Los Angeles Times. ``I'd certainly be interested, 
but there is nothing concrete.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, who played five seasons for the Angels, also might  
consider a front office position with the club if he teams up with 
Nicholas and Samueli, who co-founded the Irvine, Calif.-based 
Broadcom Corp. semiconductor group. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney spokeswoman Chris Castro declined to comment on the  
report Friday. Calls to Broadcom, Jackson's office and his agent's 
office were not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Nicholas, Samueli and a small group of other  
investors reportedly were close to a signing a letter of intent to 
buy the Angels and the NHL's Mighty Ducks from Disney for between 
$400 million and $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Tavares, president of Disney subsidiary Anaheim Sports  
Inc., later acknowledged only that Disney had been approached by 
potential buyers and that the company was in ``a listening mode.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Any deal involving the Angels would need the approval of Major  
League Baseball. Tavares said last week that talks weren't at the 
stage where the team would seek permission from the commissioner's 
office to share its financial information with possible investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was on five World Series champions during a career that  
included stints with the Angels, Oakland, the New York Yankees and 
Baltimore. He was known as ``Mr. October,'' hitting .357 with 10 
home runs and 24 RBIs in 27 World Series games. 
</P>
<P>
	He is currently director of new business alliances for Viking  
Components, a Rancho Santa Margarita, Calif.-based computer 
equipment company. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort to buy the Athletics was shelved recently by major  
league owners, pending a report of a committee studying the sport's 
economic problems. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
